[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Once Upon a Time in 1.e4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Once upon a time, there was a boy called Morphy who defeated his opponents with ease with amazing sacrifices and piece odds, then came Steinitz, the 'Father of Chess' who taught us the principles of chess... but the story continues when Lasker our rulebreaker managed to put the emphasis on practical value than objective correctness of an idea/move! His game against Capablanca where he stunned the World with his f5 move breaking the typical rules of chess is one such example. Enter the Invincible Capablanca who refuted a stunning gambit line in the Marshall variation invented by one of the greatest masters of the Romantic era - Frank Marshall.Next stop is the first hero of the aggressive era - Alexander Alekhine who created an amazing miniature by sacrificing the queen leading to an epic checkmate... Not to lag behind the next World Champion Max Euwe, who used the same violent means for which Alekhine was famous to dethrone him! The first World Champion under Fide's jurisdiction Mikhail Botvinnik used his creation 'The Panov-Botvinnik' Attack to floor his opponent Salo Flohr.  sorry couldn't resist making this stupid pun :@@EndBracket@@. Vassily Smyslov always believed in playing accurate chess as his famous quote said ' I will play 40 good moves, if you play 40 good moves, we will draw'! But not many were able to do it and he would be ruthless in execution against bad Sicilian setups.Petrosian and his systematic development of the initiative followed by a piece sacrifice destroying the defenses of the enemy king. Spassky's brilliant double-piece en-prise against Bronstein in the King's Gambit cemented his place as the first overall World Champion who was very good in all stages of the game. The magician from Riga - Mikhail Tal's demolition of Petrosian's fabled defensive concepts! One of the strongest World Champions of all time - Fischer's colorful queen sacrifice against another attacking legend!Karpov's restrained defensive attack against the fearsome Dragon variation against Korchnoi. Kasparov's fantastic opening innovation which led to an epic rook sacrifice followed by his endgame virtuoso skills in the conversion of a winning endgame. Kramnik used his endgame expertise to win a losing match against the challenger Leko.I can go on... but I think we have reached the end of the 20th century, so it was time to end the intro before it became too long and boring :@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introducing the Beastly 1.e4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hello everyone! A huge welcome to my second Lifetimes Repertoires featuring 1. e4 which was famously quoted by Bobby Fischer 'With 1.e4! I win'. With this, I am putting you on the spot and forcing you to take on the mantle left by  Fischer, I don't care what opposition you face... but when you play 1.e4, you have no choice but to win :@@EndBracket@@!I want you to understand the underlining concepts and themes of the repertoire to eventually invoke the spirits of the  World Champions who have played the King's Pawn opening successfully! It is in our hands to make the famous quote said by Fischer into reality!I am happy to join you on this journey to make you into the ultimate samurai of 1.e4. I hope that you become an expert by studying the course thoroughly and feel free to reach out in the discussion forums or the course sections whenever you have any doubts about the lines or explanations... I am just one message away :@@EndBracket@@.It is my sincere wish that your future opponents will fear when they face you from the Black side! 'In the hands of a true master, 1.e4 is a weapon to be feared even by the strongest of players!'. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "One for All - 1.e4 Summary"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ We will have a quick overview of the lines which I recommend and the reasoning in 'Short and Sweet' format. Black has many ways to play here, but none of them is going to bring him any relief :@@EndBracket@@. }
1... e5
{ The most solid response, but thanks to my find, I think we can make the game messy and force him to play unpleasant complicated positions. Our concept is simple - force our opponent to do what he doesn't like :@@EndBracket@@. If he wants to be solid, we go dynamic, and if he wants to fight actively, either we take over the initiative or we bore him to death :@@EndBracket@@.   A@@EndBracket@@  1...c5  The fabled Sicilian Defense, but in our mind it doesn't bother us...as we are well versed with what we are going to do! Surprising him in every turn :@@EndBracket@@!  2.Nf3   A1@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.Bb5+  Time to bully our opponents by playing this boring check where the active players will have a hard time trying to neutralize our space advantage.   A1a@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nd7  4.c4!  Creating the Maroczy bind leading to very interesting positions.   A1b@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bd7  As a rule after the exchange of the light-squared bishop, we are left with a slightly superior due to the pawn structure of Black who has dimmed his f8-bishop by placing his pawns on c5, d6, and e7.  4.c4  It is good that we follow the same concept for both Nd7 and Bd7. I think this fresh and less explored approach leads to very sleepy and passive positions for Black which is a good thing for us :@@EndBracket@@.   A1c@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  This line is just worse for Black, though we must know what we are doing!  4.O-O  Bd7  5.Re1  Nf6  6.Bf1!  A cool retreat preparing c3-d4 with a nice advantageous game.   A2@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  3.b3  In the end, I couldn't fully overcome my first love and have recommended the cowboy variant against the e6 systems :@@EndBracket@@. I don't think Black equalizes here and even if he does, I am confident nobody would want to take the final position as Black :@@EndBracket@@.   A3@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.Bc4  Jorden's brilliant innovation which I feel gives Black a lot of practical problems due to the uncharted territories which are left unexplored for all these years...   B@@EndBracket@@  1...e6  The unruly French Defense which could turn out to be a deadly weapon in the hands of a Morozevich or a Bluebaum :@@EndBracket@@.  2.d4  d5  3.e5!  Advancing in the center with the idea to sacrifice a pawn for the initiative! What more do we want from the White side?  3...c5  4.c3  Nc6  5.Nf3   B1@@EndBracket@@  5...Qb6  6.Bd3  cxd4  7.O-O  Giving up the d4-pawn for fun and gaining a lot of positional trumps like piece play, open files, and easy ways to create attacking chances!   B2@@EndBracket@@  5...Bd7  6.Be2  A slight twist giving us the better game.   C@@EndBracket@@  1...c6  Black wants to be very solid.  2.Nf3  d5  3.Nc3  The two knights variation which will always remain one of the toughest openings for the Black side of the Caro-Kann. He has to give up the bishop or the central control and we are happy with either of those simple...but powerful advantages. }
2. Nf3 Nc6
{ 2...Nf6  This was a tough nut to crack! But in the end, I think I found a very convincing way to gain strong forcing play leading to positions with a lot of practical difficulties for Black.  3.Nxe5  d6  4.Nf3  Nxe4  5.Nc3  This annoying line is my recommendation, which has been used very successfully by Karjakin to defeat some of the best players in the Petroff like Caruana, Kramnik, and Gelfand. }
3. Bc4
{ I am very happy with my recommendations and I feel we can get a full-fledged fight where there is no easy way to equality for Black :@@EndBracket@@. }
*

