[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Petroff: 1...e5 2.Nf3 Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... e5
{ To date, this is one of the most solid responses intended to put an end to our attacking ambitions! Black wants to copy our central pawn push and wants to believe that it is enough to neutralize our first move advantage. If you are looking for a cool repertoire with 1...e5 from the Black side, I would recommend Sethuraman's 1...e5 Lifetime Repertoires which is definitely one of the best LTR's out there and raised the standard of opening theory forever! }
2. Nf3
{ We begin the fight for the center, developing our knight and increasing the influence over e5, d4, g5, and h4-squares.   Since our repertoire is Italian based, we can also play  2.Bc4  Nf6  3.d3  If Black is not careful he can run into a transposition after  3...Nc6  4.Nf3  leading to our mainlines.   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/2B1P3/3P4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c6!  is the right way for a Petroff player, leading to an equal and comfortable game for Black. }
2... Nf6
{ And so it begins! The Petroff is one of the oldest and most reliable defenses used by almost all the top players from time to time. It was used successfully in the Candidates 2018 by Fabiano Caruana, who went on to win the event and even used the Petroff twice in the World Championship match in 2018, forcing the reigning World Champion to temporarily abandon  1.e4! }
3. Nxe5
{ Apart from this,  3.d4  remains to be the only challenging attempt to try for an advantage and this has been recommended by Anish Giri in his 1.e4 Lifetime Repertoires. I feel that the line I give is more annoying and quite depressing for the Black side compared to 3.d4 where you can survive by being well equipped with engine lines and trusting in correspondence players who have managed to exhaust most of White's tries. }
3... d6
{ A necessary inclusion before restoring the material balance by taking on e4. }
4. Nf3
{ White has tried other knight retreats to d3 and c4, but frankly it can hardly challenge Black...If he knows what he is doing! }
4... Nxe4 5. Nc3
{ Don Fabi was pretty much unstoppable during Berlin Candidates 2018...there was only one person who could stop him delivering him the only defeat in the event, It was none other than Sergey Karjakin - the previous challenger for the World Championship. He used this line and created an absolute masterpiece! }
5... Nf6
{ This lame retreat is not recommended and we can achieve an easy edge with simple means. }
6. d4 { Capturing the center. One day our extra tempo will be useful for us. }
6... Be7
{ Black prefers to finish his development first avoiding any ambitious pitfalls like capturing the center with d5. }
7. Bd3
{ If we want to make use of the extra tempi offered by @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p4/8/4n3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  ,  we need to optimize the best locations for our minor pieces to gain the advantage. }
7... O-O 8. O-O
{ Our pieces are well placed with the slight exception of the c3-knight which can be quickly transferred to better posts via e2-f4 or g3. }
8... Re8
{ Black's idea is to exchange a pair of rooks using the only open file. } 9. h3
{ I guess now that we don't have targets, it is time to make time for prophylaxis :@@EndBracket@@. Stopping the c8-bishop from entering the game. }
9... Nbd7
{ Black is playing a tight defense keeping his army behind the enemy lines and hoping that his position will be solid enough to withstand our superior space control.   9...b6  10.a4!  Gaining more space on the queenside with the threat of a5.  10...a6  Now Black can meet a5 with b5.  11.d5!  Controlling the light squares on the queenside with a clear space advantage. }
10. Ne2
{ The knight's journey is just beginning, it will go to g3 that will provoke g6 which in turn weakens Black's kingside. Our aim will be to exchange the dark-squared bishop with the advantage due to the better center and slightly more active pieces. }
*

