{ Black prefers to finish his development first avoiding any ambitious pitfalls like capturing the center with d5. }
7. Bd3
{ If we want to make use of the extra tempi offered by @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p4/8/4n3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  ,  we need to optimize the best locations for our minor pieces to gain the advantage. }
7... O-O 8. O-O
{ Our pieces are well placed with the slight exception of the c3-knight which can be quickly transferred to better posts via e2-f4 or g3. }
8... Nc6
{ The knight is feeling very brave and hopes to trick us into provoking d5.   8...d5  will allow a transposition.  9.h3  We are back in the 6...d5lines covered inchapter 1. }
9. Re1
{ Taking control of the e-file and asking Black to show his plans and we will base our plans against it! }
9... Nb4
{ 9...d5  10.Ne2  followed by Ng3 is better for us due to the activity of our pieces and a slight lead in development. }
10. Be2
{ Improving over Anish Giri-Yu Yangi 2018. The bishop is paradoxically kept at a place where it will be perfect for the upcoming tactical skirmish. }
10... Bf5 { Taking the bait :@@EndBracket@@. } 11. a3
{ The brilliant point behind our last move. We are not afraid of Nxc2 and in fact, we will welcome it with open arms :@@EndBracket@@! }
11... Nxc2
{ Taking on c2 with the bishop would be disastrous after the only move with Qd2 leading to a loss of piece for Black as he has to give up the c2-bishop or the b4-knight. }
12. Nh4
{ With a material advantage as Black will have to give up two pieces for the rook which works in our favor. }
