{ The most popular move outlasting the other alternatives by a huge margin. Black gives the invitation to enter the complex lines of Najdorf, Classical, Scheveningen, and the last but not the least - Dragon. }
3. Bb5+
{ Before you completely lose interest in my course and reject it, just hear me out :@@EndBracket@@! My entire life I have been playing 3.d4 and was never a big fan of the Moscow system from both sides. I would hate it when people play it against me from White, but that didn't stop me from gaining a good score from Black as I put a lot of effort into making creative lines work and surprising opponents!Slowly but surely I realized that there were not many lines where Black can hope to equalize and he is forced into a rigid path where he has to memorize very precise lines to neutralize White's initiative. Trying to get 0.00 by playing accurate chess is not what Black players envisioned when they choose to play the Sicilian Defence! If they want to equalize with Black, I would say that 1...e5 is the way to do it as it is very solid and reliable with many good lines to choose from, like the Petroff and the Berlin!Now moving on to the main point of why I recommend the Moscow system... Our play is very straightforward with so many interesting systems to choose from! Black has only three main options and I will try to break it down as simply as possible.A@@EndBracket@@ Bd7 - The most solid and also boring :@@EndBracket@@. I think we can achieve a concrete advantage against the best play from the Black side. I found a novel direction that hasn't been tested heavily and I couldn't equalize from the Black side. I noticed that both Anish Giri and Shankland have missed this direction in their Lifetime Repertoires.B@@EndBracket@@ Nd7 - This is the most ambitious attempt to play for a fighting game. Once again I found an interesting way missed by my lord Mr. Najdorf- Anish Giri. Frankly, it is a pain to play this line from Black as there are many move order deviations with people messing it up from time to time @@StartBracket@@including myself@@EndBracket@@ , not understanding the subtleties of each move order. With my direction, I feel we can gain the advantage by force! Trust me, I was as surprised as you!C@@EndBracket@@ Nc6 - I was a big fan of this line as it was suggested to me by my 'Uncle' Lev Psakhis, playing it to confuse opponents during my childhood! But unfortunately, those dreamy days are over and now I have to accept the reality that it is just a bad line leading to a better position... if white knows what he is doing. I am very happy with my find as I feel it is the right way to play for the advantage, but for some reason not very popular! }
3... Bd7
{ Black is ready to accept a slightly worse position with the hope that one day that he will be able to equalize by preparing the d5 or b5 break. }
4. c4
{ Changing the character of the game. Surprisingly this move is not so well researched compared to the mainline with 4.Bxd7+. As a former Bogo-Indian player I do have a soft spot for lines involving the existence of a pawn on the 5th rank as it severely restricts his pieces and a strong pawn ready to become a queen in just three steps :@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ This has the stamp of approval as the best line for Black.   5...Nc6  will transpose to 4...Nc6 lines.   5...a6  6.Bxd7+  Nbxd7  7.O-O  will transpose to 4...a6 lines. }
6. Bxd7+
{ The right time to take on d7 and then choose our plans depending on how Black will recapture the bishop. }
6... Qxd7
{ In the fianchetto systems, it is better to recapture with the queen to develop the b8-knight to c6 fighting for the central square on d4. }
7. d4 { Just in time before Black can play Nc6 stopping our main concept. }
7... cxd4 8. Qxd4
{ This has been featured in 8 games, while the mainline with Nxd4 has been played in more than 1100 games! The knight on f3 is quite decently placed, so why not improve the activity of the queen? The queen always has a nice retreat square on d3 where it keeps an eye on both the e4 and c4 pawns. }
8... Bg7
{ Black is trying to play without Nc6 to have the idea to play an early Rc8. }
9. O-O O-O
{ Black has defined his setup and is waiting for us to do the same.   9...Nc6  10.Qd3  will  transpose to 7...Nc6 lines. }
10. Bg5 { Trying to provoke h6 which will weaken the kingside. } 10... h6
{ One day Black will regret making this move!   10...Rc8  is toothless.  11.Rad1  Nc6  12.Qd3  Black didn't get anything with the early rook move and we have a slight advantage due to the recurring space advantage. }
11. Bd2
{ The only place where the bishop can't be attacked with a discovered attack using the battery along the h8-a1 diagonal. Alternatively  11.Bxf6  Bxf6  12.Qe3  Bg7  13.Rad1  followed by b3 and Nd5 might also offer a decent edge. }
11... Rc8
{ Retaining ideas involving a different pathway for the b8-knight with Na6-c5. }
12. b3 { Overprotecting our dear pawn on c4. } 12... a6 13. Rac1
{ Forecasting the future opening of the c-file. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Sicilian: 1...c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bc4 Jorden's Italian Gambit #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense: The answer for all the living beings who aren't satisfied with just equalizing and want to fight for the full point against any form of opposition! }
2. Nf3
{ Although I have had my fair share of fun with the Alapin and the Closed Sicilian with 2.Nc3, when I want to decimate my opponents this is the move I resort to! }
2... Nc6
{ This was always the respected choice for many years, but I feel it remained a very dangerous weapon in the hands of Magnus Carlsen who was practically unstoppable with it during his fantastic 2019 run where he was using this exclusively and went on to beat everyone who stood in his path! }
3. Bc4
{ Sometimes, it's not a bad idea to be very stubborn in our opening principles :@@EndBracket@@. To be honest, my original plan was to cover the mainlines arising from 3.d4 which gives Black a huge variety of options to choose from like the Sveshnikov/ Pelikan, Taimanov, Accelerated Dragon, Paulsen/ Kan, Four Horsemen, and many other lines.I was inspired by this fantastic invention of Jorden who managed to win in great style against Prag in the Tata Steel Masters 2022, that I have decided to keep it as my main recommendation. It has the surprise value since it is fresh and unexplored while at the same time leads to very interesting play where the better-prepared player will have the edge!I can guarantee you that this shall remain a great surprise weapon and Black players will have to figure out things on their own with no existing Chessable course or books to help them out here :@@EndBracket@@! Ironically I am happy that we can develop our bishop to c4 irrespective of the opening choice of our opponent! And the best part about this line is that I found it hard to find a clean equalizer for Black! Fedoseev was the first super grandmaster to use this line in a classical game against Antipov in 2017. }
3... e6
{ Black is preparing a quick d5 to punish and utilize our early bishop sortie. }
4. O-O a6
{ This is the most popular move trying to bully our light-squared with b5. } 5.
d4 { Getting the center. } 5... d5
{ Black's best bet for trying to equalize the situation.   5...b5  is just bad, but it is worth knowing how to deal with it.  6.d5!  Crashing through in the center, leading to a depressing position where the poor development of Black will be deciding factor that guarantees our advantage. }
6. exd5 exd5
{ The position resembles the Tarrasch variation from the French. As a full-fledged Sicilian player, I wouldn't be happy with such a shift of openings! After all, If I wanted to play French I could go for 1...e6 instead of 1...c5! }
7. Re1+
{ Using the time to deliver a check and prepare the retreat of the light-squared bishop to f1. }
7... Be7 8. Bf1
{ The bishop will be safe here and can come back to the game when the time is right and after the dust has been settled in the center. }
8... cxd4 9. Nxd4
{ A better pawn structure is sometimes enough to win the game! I think studying Karpov's games might be a useful way to master playing such positions, he is very ruthless in executing White's plan to perfection, while at the same time stopping Black from getting any form of counterplay. }
9... Nf6
{ Black's main hope lies in creating an active play using the isolated pawn on d5. }
10. Be3
{ Overprotecting the blockading piece on d4. This is an essential part of the Isolani strategy. }
10... O-O 11. h3
{ Stopping Ng4 ideas and preparing to stabilize our blockade on d4 with Nd2 and N2f3 with full control over the position. I will just repeat Nimzowitsch saying about Isolani pawns 'Control, blockade, and destroy!' We have already done the first two and I will believe that the readers will do the final one: Destroy!! }
*

