[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Sicilian 2nd Move Deviations: 1...c5 2.Nf3 g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense: The answer for all the living beings who aren't satisfied with just equalizing and want to fight for the full point against any form of opposition! }
2. Nf3
{ Although I have had my fair share of fun with the Alapin and the Closed Sicilian with 2. Nc3, when I want to decimate my opponents this is the move I resort to! }
2... g6
{ 'Hyper Accelerated Dragon' - Black is aiming for fianchetto systems. } 3. Bc4
{ We are continuing to pretend like Italian players and sticking to lines where we can develop our bishop to c4 irrespective of the line Black chooses :@@EndBracket@@. Our main idea is to prepare c3-d4, but the immediate 3.c3 @@StartBracket@@recommendation of Wesley@@EndBracket@@ allows 3...d5 after which Mr. Equalizer @@StartBracket@@Anish Giri@@EndBracket@@ managed to find a way to make this line also work for Black :@@EndBracket@@. Hence we are stopping d5 ideas and only then go for the capture of the center. }
3... Bg7
{ Black is ready for d6 and Nf6, so we must strike in the center before he can do that.   3...Nc6  would transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.Bc4  g6  Jorden's Italian Gambit lines. }
4. c3 { Time to prepare for the center break with d4. } 4... e6
{ Black has to prepare d5 to fight for central control, it is not a good idea to let us have our way in the center. Alternative moves will allow d4 giving us a strong center. }
5. d4 { Going for it anyway! } 5... cxd4
{ Black hopes to play d5 on the next move...   5...d5  doesn't work well for Black.  6.exd5  exd5  7.Bb5+  and Black will end up with an isolated pawn after dxc5 giving us very easy playing against the d5-pawn. }
6. Bb3
{ This stunning bishop retreat has been seen in only one game so far. The main idea is to stop Black from liquidating in the center with d5. }
6... dxc3 { This greedy move is not so bad. } 7. Nxc3 Nc6
{ Black is asking us to show the compensation for the pawn. } 8. Bf4
{ We are more than happy to do so! } 8... Nge7 9. Bd6
{ Occupying a powerful post after which Black won't feel like he has an extra pawn! }
9... O-O 10. h4 { Harry the h-pawn moves forward to attack via the h-file. }
10... h5 { Black can't afford to allow h5. } 11. Qd2 b6
{ How else to develop the bishop on c8? } 12. O-O
{ Comp gives a slight edge to White despite the pawn deficit which just shows how good our compensation is! We can play Rfd1 and Rac1 with a cool middlegame and Black will face an uphill struggle to fight against our mighty bishop on d6. }
*

[Event "?"]
