[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Sicilian 2nd Move Deviations: 1...c5 2.Nf3 a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense: The answer for all the living beings who aren't satisfied with just equalizing and want to fight for the full point against any form of opposition! }
2. Nf3
{ Although I have had my fair share of fun with the Alapin and the Closed Sicilian with 2. Nc3, when I want to decimate my opponents this is the move I resort to! }
2... a6
{ The famous trappy line is known as 'O'Kelly variation' which is very popular at the lower level where many tend to go for 3.d4 after which Black can get a decent game... If White is not careful enough. }
3. c4
{ The strongest option taking a lot of space in the center before going for the d4 break. For some reason, both Wesley and Sethu chose to give 3.c3 when our main move is the top recommendation of the engine. }
3... Nc6
{ This line has found its way into the repertoire of many creative players like Rapport, Artemiev and Van Foreest.   3...Nf6  is a move that can be compared to 'Shooting with a gun into thin air!' :@@EndBracket@@.  4.e5  followed by d4 next with a big advantage due to the central influence! }
4. d4
{ We can't afford to allow Black to execute e5 fixing the pawn structure. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5
{ Since this line is a mix of O'Kelly Sicilian and Kalashnikov, let's call it 'Kellyshnikov' :@@EndBracket@@.   5...e6  would transpose back to 3...e6 4. d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 lines. }
6. Nf5 { Of course the d6-square is the target for our knight! } 6... d6
{ Preventing Nd6+ and preparing g6 next to kick our brave knight from f5.   6...Nf6  7.Nc3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p1n5/8/2PNP3/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Nc3  e5  7.Nf5  . }
7. Nc3 { Giving Black the chance to give up his bishop pair with Bxf5. } 7...
g6
{ Black is not planning on tolerating our knight on f5 any longer.   7...Bxf5  is just horrible and hands the fight for the light-square to us on a silver platter.  8.exf5  with a big advantage and can be continued with Bd3 followed by O-O. }
8. Ne3 Bh6
{ This was Black's point attempting to exchange his bad bishop to its superior counterpart on c1. }
9. Be2
{ This strong yet simple developing move was not played by the elite players... }
9... Nge7 { Artemiev's choice. } 10. Nc2
{ Halting any Nd4 ideas and exchanging the dark-squared bishop. } 10... Bxc1
11. Rxc1
{ Although Black has achieved his main aim of getting rid of the dark-squared bishop, this by no means has reduced his problems as the d6-pawn will always remain a target for our pieces and his kingside is very weak due to the disappearance of the main guardian which was the h6-bishop! }
11... O-O { Black would like to create his counterplay with f5. } 12. Qd2
{ Threatening Rd1 to attack the d6-pawn with a clear advantage due to the grip on the position. Only after asserting our dominance on the d-file, we castle kingside! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "French Defense: 1...e6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... e6
{ 'The unpredictableFrench Defense' - Most of the time, it is very hard to understand what Black players want with this opening... Do they want to aim for a complicated game? Suffer in a worse endgame? Outprepare us under the huge mage of theoretical lines? I guess in the end, it all comes to the player himself.Compared to the king's pawn opening with 1...e5 or the Sicilian defense with 1...c5, Black is willing to give up the center to White to organize an attack against our mighty center combined with both pieces and pawn artillery! In this way, I think it resembles the Caro-Kann the most. }
2. d4
{ There are many ways to combat the French, but I feel this is the most principled - taking control of the center and gaining a lot of room for easy development for our pieces. }
2... d5
{ Black was building up towards this with his first move. The fight for center begins and White has to decide on whether he wants to maintain his center by protecting the pawn on e4, give in to the pressure by taking on d5, or finally the most dangerous attempt - advancing his forces by creating a strong pawn hook in the center. }
3. e5
{ With this ambitious move nicknamed the 'The Advance Variation', the standards are set by us. The aim is to go for a kingside attack using the e5-pawn as the battering ram while Black will use everything in his power to distract us from our plans with maximum pressure on the central d4-square where lies the key, the collapse of which could sway the struggle towards the winner of the battle! }
3... c5
{ True to his word, Black starts the assault on the center without any delay! }
4. c3
{ There have been ways to continue the fight by taking on c5, but in my opinion, it is a major concession. We stand our ground and protect the center... at least for the time being :@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Qb6
{ This is one idea that has found its way into many players' repertoires, intending to execute a sneaky move order trick! }
5. Nf3 { Continuing without a worry in the world! } 5... Bd7
{ Finally, the moment of truth has arrived :@@EndBracket@@. Black's major struggle is always associated with the passive c8-bishop which remains a major source of worry for Black until his eventual liberation into the fight. Here he forgets about his central pressure and prefers to spend two tempi on getting rid of his main problem by offering the exchange of the light-squared bishops with Bb5 next.If Black can pull off this operation and fully finish his development, he might even be the one with the better game as he will be left with the superior bishop on f8 compared to our bishop on c1. This is only assuming that most of the pieces are exchanged and we are unable to drum up any attack against Black's forces.   5...Nc6  6.Bd3  would transpose to ourmainline. }
6. Be2
{ I felt this was the easiest way to gain the advantage without any hurdles! }
6... Bb5 { Here we have two tempting options to gain the advantage. } 7. dxc5
{ An intermediate shot that Black always has to watch out for in this early Bb5 exchange line. }
7... Bxc5 8. b4
{ Black won't have the time to take on f2 as the bishop will then meet an early death. }
8... Bxf2+
{ Black has to take the pawn otherwise, his whole opening concept doesn't make any sense. }
9. Kf1
{ At the cost of weakening our king permanently, we won the fight for the initiative! }
9... Bc6 10. a4
{ A strong novelty that changes the evaluation of the line permanently. Black's entire concept lies in the fact whether the f2-bishop will survive or not and we use that very point to continue improving our position on the queenside by threatening the deadly a5 which will force Black to lose his bishop on f2. }
10... a6 11. Na3
{ Although Black's position doesn't look so bad, his position is highly suspect and he has to walk a narrow path to avoid ending up in a completely lost position. }
11... Be3
{ Black is forced to enter a line where he has no control over what is about to happen, 'The entire line will be dictated by us!' }
12. a5 { Why else did we play a4? } 12... Qa7 13. b5 { Winter is coming! }
13... axb5 { Stopping b6 ideas. } 14. Nxb5
{ We have to be slightly precise to gain maximum advantage :@@EndBracket@@. }
14... Bxb5 { The only way not to lose the e3-bishop. } 15. Bxb5+
{ At first I wasn't sure if I should enter these complications... but in the end, I realized that Black's king is in a lot of danger due to his sleeping army and the extra pawn is only a minor consolation for that. }
15... Kf8 16. Ke2
{ A very powerful centralizing move coordinating the queen and the h1-rook which can be brought to f1 to deliver justice to the Black king on f8 with dangerous ideas like Ng5 which would collapse the f7/e6 point. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "French Defense: 1...e6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... e6
{ 'The unpredictableFrench Defense' - Most of the time, it is very hard to understand what Black players want with this opening... Do they want to aim for a complicated game? Suffer in a worse endgame? Outprepare us under the huge mage of theoretical lines? I guess in the end, it all comes to the player himself.Compared to the king's pawn opening with 1...e5 or the Sicilian defense with 1...c5, Black is willing to give up the center to White to organize an attack against our mighty center combined with both pieces and pawn artillery! In this way, I think it resembles the Caro-Kann the most. }
2. d4
{ There are many ways to combat the French, but I feel this is the most principled - taking control of the center and gaining a lot of room for easy development for our pieces. }
2... d5
{ Black was building up towards this with his first move. The fight for center begins and White has to decide on whether he wants to maintain his center by protecting the pawn on e4, give in to the pressure by taking on d5, or finally the most dangerous attempt - advancing his forces by creating a strong pawn hook in the center. }
3. e5
{ With this ambitious move nicknamed the 'The Advance Variation', the standards are set by us. The aim is to go for a kingside attack using the e5-pawn as the battering ram while Black will use everything in his power to distract us from our plans with maximum pressure on the central d4-square where lies the key, the collapse of which could sway the struggle towards the winner of the battle! }
3... c5
{ True to his word, Black starts the assault on the center without any delay! }
4. c3
{ There have been ways to continue the fight by taking on c5, but in my opinion, it is a major concession. We stand our ground and protect the center... at least for the time being :@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Nc6
{ Black is slowly but surely starting to organize his play against the main weakness in White's camp - 'The d4-pawn'. }
5. Nf3
{ Bolstering our center pawn on d4, the whole fight depends on that :@@EndBracket@@...  At least we pretend to let Black into believing so : @@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bd7
{ Black doesn't go with the traditional way and prefers to first finish his development. }
6. Be2
{ It is important to note that our usual  6.Bd3  move is met by  6...cxd4  with a good game for Black as taking on d4 would be entering lines which don't suit us or being a pawn down, but with the queen on d8 which reduces our attacking potential. The game move is designed to follow up with our development.We have already achieved the space advantage and a strong central pawn hook on e5, hence it is the duty of Black to find a way to neutralize our long-term advantages. }
6... Nge7
{ If Black attempts to execute a sneaky move-order trick with  6...Qb6  then wetranspose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2ppP3/3P4/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qb6  lines. }
7. O-O Nf5 { Black's pressure on d4 is about to reach its full power... } 8.
dxc5
{ 'When the going gets tough, the center gets going' - AD 2021. Giving up the center to play for long-term positional trumps like potentially more active pieces. }
8... Bxc5 9. b4
{ Asking Black to choose between b6 or e7, both have their shortcomings. } 9...
Bb6
{ Black hopes to keep some pressure along the a7-g1 diagonal, but without any other piece backing him... he is not gonna give us any headache! }
10. Bd3
{ The concept has changed, it is time to protect our advanced pawn on e5 with our major pieces! }
10... O-O { This natural move hasn't been played yet. } 11. Re1
{ Followed by Nbd2 with a big advantage, since the knight on f5 gets in the way of the f6-break... while the attempt to exchange it with Nh4 will be met by the Greek's gift with Bxh7+ leading to a winning attack for White. }
