[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Caro-Kann: 1...c6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... c6
{ TheCaro-Kann defense is one of my personal favorites as I scored a memorable 23-move victory over Kryvoruchko Yuri. This opening is named after the English player Horatio Caro and the Austrian player Marcus Kann, who analyzed it in 1886. It was a significant moment in its history and marked the beginning of this solid opening which can be molded according to the preference of the player!It is an opening that can be played and mastered by both aggressive/positional players. Do not be fooled by its appearance, many great players have fallen victim to it :@@EndBracket@@. Erwin's epic course was one of my earliest relationships with Chessable. Although I loved it with all my heart, I had to fight my personal feelings to find a clear way to advantage. In the end, I think I managed to do the impossible and cracked Erwin's bulletproof analysis! }
2. Nf3 d5 { This was the point of playing 1...c6 after all :@@EndBracket@@! }
3. Nc3
{ The Two Knights defense! In this line, we give priority to piece play instead of building a pawn center! After many hours of research on literally most of the course lines, I finally made my conclusion that this was indeed the ideal way to fight for advantage! }
3... dxe4 { One of the topical ways to fight for equality. } 4. Nxe4
{ I found it surprising that most of the lines which are possible in the mainline arising from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2p5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  d5  3.Nc3  dxe4  4.Nxe4  just don't work here! I guess it is the power of the 'Two knights' defense where piece play is the main factor! }
4... Bf5
{ The following is a sample line of how things could develop if Black is not careful. }
5. Ng3 Bg6
{ This line is completely playable... if we put the pawn on d4 instead of the knight on f3. }
6. h4
{ Since we have skipped on the usual d4 move, this line becomes very dangerous for Black. }
6... h6 7. Ne5 { GO BACK! } 7... Bh7 8. Qh5
{ Black is forced to play  8...g6  which can be met by the sexy  9.Bc4  or the normal  9.Qf3  with a big advantage in both cases. }
