1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... d6
{ The primitive 'Philidor Defence'. Black literally doesn't care about space and just wants to finish his plans at his own pace with the intention to lash out after all the preparations are complete. I had to make sure I got a good position out of the positions recommended by Pepe in his Chessable course.I would also add not to be fooled by the passive nature of this line, many lines contain a lot of venom and we must act with precision to stop all of Black's counterplay. In this line we necessarily don't need to show any plans, just controlling Black's idea is enough to guarantee a stable advantage. }
2. d4
{ The best move, I had also tried the enterprising  2.Nc3  with the idea to meet  2...e5  3.f4  taking the game to King's Gambit type positions which many of the Philidor fans won't like. I think it is a good alternative to research for interested readers! }
2... Nf6 3. Nc3
{ Although  3.Bd3  was a tempting option to continue with  3...e5  4.d5  .  In the end, I decided we needn't avoid the mainstream theory and go for the mainlines with my guided approach! }
3... e5 4. Nf3
{ Supporting the center, the endgame arising after  4.dxe5  dxe5  5.Qxd8  Kxd8  is a very good alternative for people who like slightly better endgames. In my personal opinion having White's pieces and more space advantage, it is better to avoid a lot of exchanges which might reduce our advantage by a tiny bit. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4
{ We have achieved a static advantage due to the superior center pawn on e4 compared to its counterpart on d6. }
5... Be7
{ Black's strategy is similar to the 'Compressed spring' method, where he hopes one day when the position opens up all his pieces will come to life with renewed power and purpose. @@StartBracket@@SPOILER ALERT: This will never work against a well prepared and cautious person armed with our course :@@EndBracket@@ }
6. g3
{ This setup involving the fianchetto is one of the soundest replies to the Philidor and steers the game into positional territories where Black needs to find creative ways to create counterplay to avoid getting completely bamboozled by White. }
6... O-O 7. Bg2
{ The bishop is very well placed on g2, overprotecting the e4-pawn keeping an eye on the safety of the kingside while also preventing any future ideas from Black. }
7... Re8
{ Black is preparing the retreat of the bishop to f8, though in principle such a slow plan can hardly bother us. }
8. O-O Bf8
{ Black's plan consists of c6-b5 and trying to create play against the e4-pawn. }
9. Re1
{ Always remember that in this fianchetto edition of the Philidor over protecting the e4-pawn is always a good idea to destroy Black's hopes of counterplay and for the fact that we can release any of the piece's duty of passively defending the e4-pawn with a sudden shift of roles to aggressively attacking Black's weakness. }
9... Nbd7
{ The knight is coming to c5 to put pressure on the e4-pawn.   9...c6  transposes to 8...c6lines covered inchapter 9. }
10. a4
{ Already starting to fight against Black's aforementioned expansion plans with c6-b5. }
10... a5
{ Fixing the pawn structure like this can only benefit us because we can now calmly proceed with improvement of our position without having to worry about the c6-b5 break which doesn't exist anymore! }
11. b3
{ Followed by Bb2 with a solid position and full control of the game. We can continue with Qd2, Rad1 and then eventually start to expand with h3-g4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Pirc: 1...d6 with 3...g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... d6
{ Black is keeping all his options open with this 'Philidor style' move order. }
2. d4
{ The best move, I had also tried the enterprising  2.Nc3  with the idea to meet  2...e5  3.f4  taking the game to King's Gambit type positions which many of the Philidor fans won't like. I think it is a good alternative to research for interested readers! }
2... Nf6
{ Black attacks the e4-pawn and makes sure that we can't go to lines involving c4 or c3 systems. }
3. Nc3
{ Supporting the center and the knight could come under future threats like a6-b5 or c6-b5 threatening to win the e4-pawn with b4. }
3... g6 4. Bg5
{ Staying very principled and aggressive! Being a loyal fan of 4.Be3 for all these years, I must say that I am surprised that this move is the 4th most popular move. }
4... Bg7
{ The bishop makes its grand appearance on the g7-square. We are well-advised to take precautions against tricks along the a1-h8 diagonal. }
5. Nf3
{ Deviating from Sethu's direction. He has recommended 5.Qd2 followed by f4, while I am more in favor of quick kingside development with Nf3. Practically this feels more dangerous as we are not making any weakness and preparing the central e5 advance if Black is not careful. }
5... O-O
{ Braveheart! Black is castling into the line of fire! He is hoping that his center/queenside counterplay will be in time to save him! }
6. Qd2 { Time to go for the kingside attack with Bh6 followed by h4-h5! } 6...
Nbd7
{ Here we would like to achieve h4-h5, but for that the knight on f6 is a small hurdle...so we proceed to remove that hurdle with brute force! }
7. e5 { Kicking the knight to the depths of the sea! } 7... dxe5
{ 7...Ne8  is too passive.  8.h4!  followed by h5 with a powerful AlphaZero style attack. }
8. dxe5 Ng4 { Black is hoping that the pressure on e5 will distract us. } 9.
O-O-O { Domination is more important than petty material gain. } 9... Ngxe5
{ I have heard the saying 'If you are anyway gonna be worse, might as well be a pawn up!'. }
10. Nxe5 Bxe5 11. h4
{ The pawn deficit is highly irrelevant in this position where the attacking potential along the h-file with h5 next move takes center stage. Comp already shows +2 eval for us which shows the dire situation Black is in.   This line can be found in thePirc chapter. }
