[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Modern Defense: 1...g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... g6
{ TheModern defense... The name was derived from Wikipedia as the author was too lazy to find the origin story :@@EndBracket@@. Black wants to give up the center and wants to finish his development with the hope that one day when he strikes back, White won't be in a position to control the outcome of the center battle.I have played it myself with good results in shorter time controls as I feel it is very easy to handle and many times White players end up underestimating the latent potential of this system. This is something we won't be doing! I think the approach I suggest is bulletproof and will make sure that you will get an easy advantage doesn't matter in what time control you will face this! }
2. d4
{ NO NEED TO ASK AGAIN! We happily take the center and will have the final laugh :@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Bg7
{ The sniper is ready from g7 to put maximum pressure on d4 and along the h8-a1 diagonal. }
3. Nf3
{ This is the second most popular move that has been outlasted by 3.Nc3 for no apparent reason. I think in principle people don't want to allow 3...d5 options for Black and want to have the option of going the English Attack style ideas like Be3-Qd2-f3 which in my opinion gives Black the necessary time to create his counterplay.In this course, I would like to endorse the approach with 3.Nf3 which is mainly aimed against a6 systems which can be brutally met with c4 killing Black's entire setup involving b5-Bb7. I am reminded of the quote 'People often fear what they don't understand', I feel it is fitting for 3.Nf3. }
3... d6
{ Black controls the center and prepares ideas like Bg4 and e5, when the time is right. }
4. Be3
{ Continuing to toy with the move orders and asking Black to decide on his queenside plans. }
4... Nd7
{ Although this is a typical knight move, it seriously weakens the e6-square. }
5. Bc4 { Immediately pointing out the drawback of Black's last move. } 5... e6
{ Black is forced to stop our threats with this unnatural move which ruins Black's entire strategy. }
6. Nc3 { Getting our army ready for the middlegame. } 6... a6
{ Black is desperately trying to gain some play with b5 followed by Bb7. } 7.
a4
{ Putting an end to Black's feeble ambitions. The future looks quite depressing for him due to less space and lack of active play for his pieces while our center looks stable. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Alekhine's Defense: 1...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... Nf6
{ Alekhine's Defense. An opening that was popularised by one of my favorite world champions, Alexander Alekhine who used this as part of his hypermodern approach to chess where the emphasis is on piece activity more than anything else! As much as I love this line... unfortunately I had to find the best way to end its career once and for all! }
2. e5
{ Bullying the knight and creating a strong pawn hook on e5 which cuts into Black's plans! }
2... Ng8
{ I would have loved to laugh at this move and ignore it... But it has been played by the World Champion to troll and to defeat people :@@EndBracket@@, Hence it wouldn't hurt to know what to do against it. }
3. d4 { Step 1: Capture the center! } 3... d6 4. Nf3
{ Step 2: Develop your pieces! } 4... dxe5 5. Nxe5
{ The knight is well placed on the central square and coordinates with the rest of the pieces nicely. }
5... Nd7
{ This line has been tried by Mamedyarov, Edouard, and Martirosyan, so let's see how to deal with it. }
6. Qf3
{ Object of the game is to deliver checkmate, so why not try to do that at the earliest possible juncture :@@EndBracket@@? }
6... Nxe5 7. dxe5
{ The pawn on e5 cuts into Black's piece development and is a good attacking hook for us. }
7... c6
{ Black's queen is preparing to win the e5-pawn with a check on a5.   7...Qd4  is a funny greedy plunge to win the e5-pawn  8.Bb5+  Suddenly Black is in big trouble since c6 is met by Bxc6+. }
8. Nc3
{ Having achieved a profitable transaction, we can chill and continue with our development. }
8... Qa5
{ Black is trying to be greedy and goes for the e5-pawn without finishing his development. }
9. Be2 { We literally don't care... } 9... Qxe5 10. Bf4
{ Thank you, your Highness! } 10... Qa5 11. b4
{ Giving away more material to open the files and to destroy the Black king on e8! }
11... Qxb4 12. Rb1 { The mighty rook joins the fun party! } 12... Qa5
{ 12...Qc5  13.Nb5  cxb5  14.Bxb5+  Kd8  Any check on the d-file would prove to be disastrous for Black :@@EndBracket@@! }
13. Rb5 { This is one of the most epic ways to sacrifice the rook! } 13... Qd8
{ Taking the rook is very dangerous, hence Black is better off not capturing it.   If Black is a greedy boy and takes the rook with  13...cxb5  14.Bxb5+  he will soon get checkmated! }
14. O-O
{ Just cooly finishing Step 3: Getting the king to safety and unleashing chaos against Black's king. We have a decisive advantage as our idea is to play Rd1 next which would prove to be very nasty for Black who has no hope nor development to compete with our superior army! }
*

