{ It is a fight for the honor of center, we capture the pawn and ask Black to choose between two branches:   One - Bring the queen out early and get embarrassed by White's army.   Two - Continue in the spirit of a gambiteer and get a worse position. }
2... Qxd5 3. Nc3
{ The strongest direction! Attacking the queen and asking her majesty to choose a wise direction :@@EndBracket@@. This is officially the beginning of the Scandinavian! The Black queen could go to a5 @@StartBracket@@The first@@EndBracket@@, d6 @@StartBracket@@The trendy@@EndBracket@@ and finally the d8 @@StartBracket@@The lame@@EndBracket@@.   Other queen retreats are too lame like  3...Qe5+  which can be met with  4.Be2  followed by d4 with a big advantage due to the huge lead in development and the queen will continue giving us more momentum by attacking her.   The other tries like @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  or  3.d4  allow Black very good chances to equalize. }
3... Qd6
{ This retreat saw a huge rise in popularity as it was employed by Magnus Carlsen, Caruana, and Ivanchuk with a lot of success in classical time control. Hence people had to take it seriously and soon destructive countermeasures were created. }
4. Nf3
{ A very sneaky move order! The g1-knight's destined place is on f3, but we can delay d4 for one more move and wait to see how Black will react :@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Nf6 5. d4
{ Switching back and returning to the mainlines. Taking control of the center and e5-square, asking Black to show compensation for giving up the center without a fight. }
5... a6
{ A very nice prophylactic move stopping Nb5/ c4 ideas. Black prefers to keep the option of Nc6, hence he delays c6 with the idea to put pressure on d4-pawn with Bg4. This was very trendy at some time with amazing results for Black. To this day it remains a very decent option in shorter time controls. }
6. g3
{ The strongest move, also recommended by Wesley and Sethu. So you can be convinced that this is the right direction and gives Black very little hope against a prepared opponent. I couldn't find a good alternative for White and decided to continue in the direction chosen by my fellow Chessable colleagues.With this move, we kill off any b5 ideas from Black and also prepare the fianchetto bishop on g2... Black also needs to watch out for Bf4 ideas. }
6... Bg4
{ Black doesn't have many directions here. This is the only way that doesn't make the eval go completely crazy :@@EndBracket@@.   6...b5  7.Bg2  Bb7  8.O-O  followed by Ne5-Qf3 after the exchange of the light-squared bishop taking control of the long diagonal along the h1-a8 which cements our advantage. }
7. h3
{ Black always get annoyed when we play this as now he has to take a big decision... give up the bishop pair or allow a lot of tempi for White and concede the initiative to us. Sethu and yours truly recommend this moving away from Wesley's direction of 7.Bg2. }
7... Bh5
{ Black has to try for this. The alternative will be a depressing middlegame dictated by the bishop pair.   7...Bxf3  8.Qxf3  followed by Be3 and O-O-O @@StartBracket@@irrespective of how Black reacts@@EndBracket@@ with the bishop pair advantage, we can follow it up with kingside expansion with g4-g5 leading to a clear advantage. }
8. Bg2
{ The bishop looks so mighty controlling the h1-a8 diagonal like a boss! } 8...
Nc6
{ Black wants to play queenside castling or Rd8 to put pressure on the d4-pawn. }
9. d5
{ Not giving Black any time to chill and going on the offensive before he can finish his development. In the upcoming fight, we will see who comes out on top! }
9... Nb4
{ Black's situation is already becoming very dangerous and the other knight might make things even more difficult.   9...Ne5  10.g4!  followed by O-O preparing Bf4 ideas with a killer advantage due to Black's poor development and limited space for his pieces. }
10. Bf4 { Continuing to attack our enemy ruthlessly! } 10... Qc5
{ Hoping that his difficult times will pass...   A@@EndBracket@@  10...e5  11.Bxe5!  Entering a forced sequence where we will end up with an extra pawn.  11...Bxf3  12.Bxd6  Bxd1  Black has to go for this, any other alternatives would give White the advantage without any challenge.  13.Bxf8  Rxf8  14.Rxd1!  with the extra pawn and if Black is greedy by playing  14...Nxc2+  15.Ke2  The knight on c2 will meet an untimely death as we are going a3 next trapping him forever!   B@@EndBracket@@  10...Qd8  11.g4!  Breaking the pin  11...Bg6  12.O-O!  Leaving en prise not one but two pawns! Thanks to Black's sleeping army Ra8, Bf8, and Rh8... also the fact that his king is on e8 will give us a very strong attack despite losing one or two pawns!   C@@EndBracket@@  10...Bxf3  11.Qxf3!  The attack on d6 leaves Black no time to take on c2 with a powerful position. }
11. Be3
{ Not so fast! We are not done yet. Black has two directions... both are equally bad : @@EndBracket@@. }
11... Qa5 { HURRAY! Finally, the queen can't be bullied anymore! } 12. O-O
{ Now that our mobilization is almost complete, we just get the king to safety even at the cost of sacrificing the d5-pawn. Black is forced to accept our gift as he can never hope to finish his development without winning the d5-pawn. As a result, both the d-file and h1-a8 diagonal are opened to our advantage. }
12... Nbxd5 { 12...Rd8  13.Qe2  will lead to a similar fate. } 13. Nxd5
{ After this exchange, Black has to watch out for ideas involving c4. } 13...
Qxd5
{ At least exchanging the queen to reduce our attacking potential.   13...Nxd5  will be met by a cool retreat.  14.Bd2!  Gaining another tempo attacking the queen to be continued with g4 and c4 leading to a winning attack using our better-mobilized forces. }
14. Qe2
{ Sorry! We are not gonna exchange the queens after all... The idea is to play g4 followed by destruction along the d-file with Rad1 or Rfd1 and the moment we move the knight from f3 it will unleash the power of the fianchetto bishop on g2 attacking the b7-pawn. All these factors give us a decisive advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Scandinavian: 1...d5 2.exd5 Qxd5 3.Nc3 Qd8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... d5
{ The Center Counter Defense is one of the coldest recorded openings as it was played between Francesc de Castellví and Narcís Vinyoles in Valencia in 1475. Analysis by Scandinavian masters in the late 19th century didn't change its status and it remained an unplayable opening for Black. Although theScandinavian Defense has never enjoyed widespread popularity among top-flight players, I mean why should it? It gives up the center and helps White to develop his army with tempo. - Sethu's LTR  @@StartBracket@@source@@EndBracket@@.Just when all hope had been lost for this opening... one crazy guy decided to play it against the reigning World Champion Magnus Carlsen in Tata Steel 2017 and even managed to achieve a winning position... What more do you want from this opening? Abandoning the usual cautious approach exhibited by the Black side, here the strongest piece is brought into the battle in the very first opportunity with the hope to singlehandedly annoy White's army and his coordination. }
2. exd5
{ It is a fight for the honor of center, we capture the pawn and ask Black to choose between two branches:   One - Bring the queen out early and get embarrassed by White's army.   Two - Continue in the spirit of a gambiteer and get a worse position. }
2... Qxd5 3. Nc3
{ The strongest direction! Attacking the queen and asking her majesty to choose a wise direction :@@EndBracket@@. This is officially the beginning of the Scandinavian! The Black queen could go to a5 @@StartBracket@@The first@@EndBracket@@, d6 @@StartBracket@@The trendy@@EndBracket@@ and finally the d8 @@StartBracket@@The lame@@EndBracket@@.   Other queen retreats are too lame like  3...Qe5+  which can be met with  4.Be2  followed by d4 with a big advantage due to the huge lead in development and the queen will continue giving us more momentum by attacking her.   The other tries like @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  or  3.d4  allow Black very good chances to equalize. }
3... Qd8
{ This lame retreat is not to be underestimated as it has been used by Magnus Carlsen to defeat Fabiano Caruana in the Olympiad at Tromso 2014. This was mainly due to Fabi over-extending his position, someone who is armed with our course there shouldn't be any problem achieving the advantage and an easy game. }
4. d4 { What could be more natural than capturing the center? } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3
{ Getting the knights into position for the next phase. } 5... Bg4
{ This is by far the most popular move which is just ridiculous as I feel it is the weakest according to comp :@@EndBracket@@.   A@@EndBracket@@  5...e6  6.Bd3!  The best square for the bishop pointing at the kingside as other locations aren't so juicy for the light-squared bishop. Follow up is O-O, Qe2 and Bg5 with Rad1 next. It is also possible to throw in Ne4 ideas to decrease Black's defenses on the kingside.   B@@EndBracket@@  5...c6  Black's motto is simple: Passive but solid. Our motto is the opposite: Aggressive but solid.  6.Bc4!  Going for the f7 weak spot. If we force Black to play e6, then his whole opening concept can be called a complete joke :@@EndBracket@@. The moves c6 and e6 don't go well with each other as both of them are getting in the way of the c8-bishop's activation.   B1@@EndBracket@@ Black's only challenging option with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/8/2BP4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...b5  can be met with  7.Bd3!  A change of plans intending to play Ne4 and gain a good advantage using Black's overstretched/weak queenside pawn structure.   B2@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/8/2BP4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bf5  7.Ne5  will transpose to 5...c6 lines. }
6. h3
{ Giving Black the usual unpleasant choice - Take on f3 losing the bishop pair or go back to h5 and allow g4. }
6... Bxf3 7. Qxf3 { With literally zero effort, we have got the bishop pair! }
7... c6
{ This was Black's concept. He wants to create an impregnable fortress with his pawns on c6 and e6 followed by Nbd7 with the hope of getting play on the queenside with ideas like Qa5, Bb4, or Qb6. }
8. g4
{ A very nice direction shown by Wesley which has been seen in only one correspondence game so far! Sethu also recommends this and now I am also joining the club :@@EndBracket@@ since I feel practically this is the best way for White, I couldn't find an alternative path that guarantees our advantage like this line. }
8... e6
{ Black is trying to be solid...but in this case, it won't work for him. } 9.
g5 { This was the point behind our last move... } 9... Nd5 10. Ne4
{ White was clearly superior, thanks to the bishop pair and the strong initiative on the kingside due to the pawn on g5  @@StartBracket@@Paul-Ian ICCF 2020@@EndBracket@@. We can continue with Bg2-h4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Scandinavian: 1...d5 2.exd5 Qxd5 3.Nc3 Qa5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... d5
{ The Center Counter Defense is one of the coldest recorded openings as it was played between Francesc de Castellví and Narcís Vinyoles in Valencia in 1475. Analysis by Scandinavian masters in the late 19th century didn't change its status and it remained an unplayable opening for Black. Although theScandinavian Defense has never enjoyed widespread popularity among top-flight players, I mean why should it? It gives up the center and helps White to develop his army with tempo. - Sethu's LTR  @@StartBracket@@source@@EndBracket@@.Just when all hope had been lost for this opening... one crazy guy decided to play it against the reigning World Champion Magnus Carlsen in Tata Steel 2017 and even managed to achieve a winning position... What more do you want from this opening? Abandoning the usual cautious approach exhibited by the Black side, here the strongest piece is brought into the battle in the very first opportunity with the hope to singlehandedly annoy White's army and his coordination. }
2. exd5
{ It is a fight for the honor of center, we capture the pawn and ask Black to choose between two branches:   One - Bring the queen out early and get embarrassed by White's army.   Two - Continue in the spirit of a gambiteer and get a worse position. }
2... Qxd5 3. Nc3
{ The strongest direction! Attacking the queen and asking her majesty to choose a wise direction :@@EndBracket@@. This is officially the beginning of the Scandinavian! The Black queen could go to a5 @@StartBracket@@The first@@EndBracket@@, d6 @@StartBracket@@The trendy@@EndBracket@@ and finally the d8 @@StartBracket@@The lame@@EndBracket@@.   Other queen retreats are too lame like  3...Qe5+  which can be met with  4.Be2  followed by d4 with a big advantage due to the huge lead in development and the queen will continue giving us more momentum by attacking her.   The other tries like @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  or  3.d4  allow Black very good chances to equalize. }
3... Qa5
{ The most popular queen retreat, This formed the basis for the creation of the Scandinavian defense. Black has given up the center and also managed to lose some tempi in the process... What for? The queen has gotten out and feels like she can influence many things in the queenside by making use of the pin along the a5-e1 diagonal and not to mention the fact that she can quickly switch to h5 in just one move to generate play in the kingside.Tiviakov is one of the biggest pioneers of the Scandi and has used it for many years against the strongest opposition with a lot of success! That being said, I feel I have found the way to advantage using our superior army and central control which can never be compensated by Black's sole queen. }
4. d4
{ Capturing the center and taking control of the important e5-square which will prove to be an attacking hook by placing a knight there controlling Black's position. I also tried to make the exciting 4. b4 work, but it was not to be and we don't get enough compensation for the pawn. }
4... Nf6
{ Black develops his knight and prepares to develop his c8-bishop to f5 or g4, he can also play Ne4 trying to use the pin along the a5-e1 diagonal.   4...c6  5.Nf3  Nf6  will transpose to 4...Nf6 lines. }
5. Nf3
{ This feels like a better move order than 5.Bc4 as getting the knight to e5 is the top priority! And I will keep repeating this until the readers are completely bored of this saying and it becomes drilled into their bloodstream 'knights before bishops' in the opening stages :@@EndBracket@@! }
5... Bg4
{ This move which gives an almost +1 advantage for White has been played in 1300 games. I have no comments and I am just speechless... }
6. h3 { Asking the usual questions, 'To be or not to be'. } 6... Bh5
{ Black is going down with the ship :@@EndBracket@@.   6...Bxf3  7.Qxf3  followed by Bd2 and O-O-O with the bishop pair advantage and we can continue expanding on the kingside with g4-h4. It is also very useful to include Kb1 which is aimed against any threats against the a2-pawn. }
7. g4 { Gaining the momentum required to get the initiative on the kingside. }
7... Bg6 { Simon is unaware of the danger which is about to come! } 8. Ne5
{ The knight occupies the central location with a dual-threat - h4-h5 to target the g6 bishop and Nc4 to go after the queen. }
8... c6
{ Black needs to spend a tempo on this move to ensure a safe return for the queen to d8 since we were threatening to embarrass her majesty with Nc4.   8...e6  doesn't change much and we stick to our usual kingside antics.  9.h4  with a dominating advantage thanks to the fact that he has to exchange his light-squared bishop for our c3-knight. }
9. h4
{ With a big advantage as the bishop on g6 is in trouble. If he tries to escape with Be4 we can just play Nc4 breaking the pin along the a5-e1 diagonal and then take the bishop with the knight winning the bishop pair. }
