[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Owen's Defense: 1...b6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... b6
{ There was a time when I was so happy with my 1.b3 course direction that I believed it was possible to make theOwen Defense work from the black side! Unfortunately, I had to face the sad reality when I took an objective look and there were at least 3 ways to gain a clear advantage with White. }
2. d4
{ I think the system with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  b6  2.c4  might be still tenable from Black, but capturing the center with 1.e4 and 2.d4 is just too much to take for Black and he can't hope to equalize anymore... }
2... Bb7 3. Nc3
{ The most natural way to protect the pawn, forcing Black to make a useful developing move before continuing with the attack on our strong center. }
3... e6 4. Bd3
{ The entire fight revolves around the e4-square, hence it makes a lot of sense to overprotect it! }
4... Bb4 { Slowly bringing the fight to the e4-square. } 5. Nf3
{ The most natural form of development for the knight, we needn't worry about the doubling of our pawn structure after Bxc3...as it only helps us to solidify our center control on d4 and opens up a new life for the c1-bishop along the a3-f8 diagonal if at all he is bored with his life in the c1-h6 diagonal :@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Nf6
{ Finally Black has managed to make his first real threat against us by continuing to put pressure on the central e4-point. }
6. Nd2
{ The stunning retreat which put a big question mark over Black's entire opening concept! We simply protect the e4-pawn again and also break the pin along the a5-e1 diagonal! This was also Shankland's recommendation, but it was reached via 1.d4 b6 2.e4 move order. }
6... d5 { Creating a stronghold on e4. } 7. e5
{ Wherever the knight goes, Qg4 shall follow :@@EndBracket@@. } 7... Ne4 8. Qg4
{ with a double attack on e4 and g7. } 8... Qg5
{ Exchanging the queens is the lesser evil. } 9. Qxg5 Nxg5 10. O-O
{ With a more pleasant endgame due to our space and Black's pieces are still struggling to find their purpose in the game. Just look at Bb7 @@StartBracket@@stuck due to his pawn on d5@@EndBracket@@, Bb4 @@StartBracket@@has no idea why he is on b4@@EndBracket@@, Ng5 @@StartBracket@@He is just dancing around with no control of his future@@EndBracket@@. }
