[Black "Nimzowitsch Defense: 1...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... Nc6
{ This, theNimzowitsch Defense, feels like a lame imitation of the Alekhine defense :@@EndBracket@@. Black is not even threatening anything :@@EndBracket@@. That being said, 'Let's take an objective look at how to continue with White'. }
2. d4 { Capturing the center and asking Black to choose between two options. }
2... e5 { I think 1...e5 players would be inclined to aim for this. } 3. dxe5
{ This seems the clearest way to advantage. } 3... Nxe5 4. Nf3
{ Continuing to develop at full speed! } 4... Nxf3+
{ Other moves also don't offer any relief for Black. } 5. Qxf3
{ Sethu feels 5.gxf3 is stronger, but I think this is stronger and more natural. }
5... Qf6
{ Black has to aim for a worse endgame as the normal means would put him in a precautious situation. }
6. Nc3
{ Now we are fine to go for gxf3 structures as we have gained a nice extra tempo. }
6... Qxf3
{ What else to do with the queen on f6?   6...Bb4  7.Bd2  Breaks the pin and doesn't change much leading to a solid endgame advantage due to better central control with potentially more active major/minor pieces. }
7. gxf3
{ Due to the disappearance of the queens, Black has to worry about ideas like Nb5 or Nd5 attacking the weak pawn on c7. }
7... c6 { Preventing both the knight jumps. } 8. Rg1
{ was very clearly better for White in @@StartBracket@@Wesley-Vachier Rapid 2020@@EndBracket@@. }
