[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) The Petroff Pipelines"]
[Black "3...Nxe4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... e5
{ To date, this is one of the most solid responses intended to put an end to our attacking ambitions! Black wants to copy our central pawn push and wants to believe that it is enough to neutralize our first move advantage. If you are looking for a cool repertoire with 1...e5 from the Black side, I would recommend Sethuraman's 1...e5 Lifetime Repertoires, which is definitely one of the best LTR's out there and raised the standard of opening theory forever! }
2. Nf3
{ We begin the fight for the center, developing our knight and increasing the influence over e5, d4, g5, and h4-squares.   Since our repertoire is Italian based, we can also play  2.Bc4  Nf6  3.d3  If Black is not careful he can run into a transposition after  3...Nc6  4.Nf3  leading to our mainlines.   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/2B1P3/3P4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c6!  is the right way for a Petroff player, leading to an equal and comfortable game for Black. }
2... Nf6
{ And so it begins! This is one of the oldest and most reliable defenses used by almost all the top players from time to time. It was used successfully in the Candidates 2018 by Fabiano Caruana, who went on to win the event and even used the Petroff twice in the World Championship match in 2018, forcing the reigning World Champion to temporarily abandon  1.e4! }
3. Nxe5
{ Apart from this,  3.d4  remains to be the only challenging attempt to try for an advantage and this has been recommended by Anish Giri in his 1.e4 Lifetime Repertoires. I feel that the line I give is more annoying and quite depressing for the Black side compared to 3.d4 where you can survive by being well equipped with engine lines and trusting in correspondence players who have managed to exhaust most of White's tries. }
3... Nxe4
{ This is a silly sideline which might only work as a surprise weapon in shorter time controls... and when I say short, I mean really short like bullet or ultra bullet! }
4. Qe2
{ The key point! Black is in a dangerous X-ray on the e-file, which makes sure that the knight on e4 can't make it out alive! }
4... Qe7
{ The best option, the alternatives will be subjected to higher material losses.   4...d5  5.d3  is a simple pin  5...Qe7  , which is the best way to regain the piece,  6.dxe4  Qxe5  7.exd5  with a healthy extra pawn.   4...d6  5.Nxf7!  Forcing the king to lose his castling rights  5...Kxf7  6.Qxe4  With an extra pawn and a winning position thanks to Black's weak king. }
5. Qxe4 d6 { Winning back the piece, thanks to the same pin along the e-file! }
6. d4
{ Since the knight on e5 can't be saved, it makes sense to at least win a pawn for it. }
6... dxe5 7. dxe5
{ Black has to play energetically to get compensation for the pawn. } 7... Nc6
{ Here we mustn't be greedy and give back the pawn to gain a stable endgame advantage thanks to our superior minor/major pieces. }
8. Nc3 Qxe5
{ The recapture with the knight  8...Nxe5  would spell immediate disaster after  9.Nd5  . }
9. Qxe5+ { The simplest way to advantage. } 9... Nxe5 10. Bf4
{ I like this deviation from Sethu's LTR where he recommends  10.Nb5  which is also very strong, but allows Black some simplifications after  10...Bb4+  .  Our option is designed to keep more pieces to utilize our better development. }
10... Bd6
{ The ideal way to protect the knight, thanks to a tactical detail.  10...f6  11.O-O-O  Bd6  can transpose to our lines, but we needn't go there anymore.  12.Be3!  is a stronger retreat with a nice advantage thanks to the threat of Nb5 which will win the bishop pair. }
11. Bg3
{ A cool retreat preventing any Nd3+ ideas which was Black's main point if we had rushed with  11.Nb5  . }
11... f6
{ Since the threat of Nb5 was a real threat, Black takes countermeasures against it by protecting the e5-knight.   11...h5  is an empty move  12.O-O-O  with a big advantage since Black can't play  12...h4  because of  13.Bxe5  followed by Re1 winning a piece due to the pin along the e-file.   11...Bd7  fighting against Nb5  12.Ne4  The knight finds another route to target the bishop leading to a better position since Black has to allow Nxd6 or Bxe5 both of which will ruin Black's pawn structure permanently. }
12. Nb5
{ This feels more forcing than  12.O-O-O  which also guarantees a stable advantage. }
12... Bb4+
{ Black uses the fact that the king is still on e1 to transfer the bishop to a different defensive position where he won't be bullied by our knight. }
13. c3 Ba5 { Just in time to protect c7. } 14. O-O-O
{ We can take on e5 whenever we want! At the moment, it is more advantageous to finish our development while keeping more options open. }
14... O-O
{ This looks like the most human move.   14...a6  does seem natural, but comp gives White a huge advantage.  15.Nd4  followed by f4.   14...Bb6  14.f4  followed by Bc4 leading to similar positions using the weak a2-c4 diagonal and the open d- & e-lines. }
15. f4
{ Kicking the knight and preparing Bc4 next, followed by Rhe1 with a solid advantage thanks to the control over the d- and e-files. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) The Petroff Pipelines"]
[Black "3...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... e5
{ To date, this is one of the most solid responses intended to put an end to our attacking ambitions! Black wants to copy our central pawn push and wants to believe that it is enough to neutralize our first move advantage. If you are looking for a cool repertoire with 1...e5 from the Black side, I would recommend Sethuraman's 1...e5 Lifetime Repertoires, which is definitely one of the best LTR's out there and raised the standard of opening theory forever! }
2. Nf3
{ We begin the fight for the center, developing our knight and increasing the influence over e5, d4, g5, and h4-squares.   Since our repertoire is Italian based, we can also play  2.Bc4  Nf6  3.d3  If Black is not careful he can run into a transposition after  3...Nc6  4.Nf3  leading to our mainlines.   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/2B1P3/3P4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c6!  is the right way for a Petroff player, leading to an equal and comfortable game for Black. }
2... Nf6
{ And so it begins! This is one of the oldest and most reliable defenses used by almost all the top players from time to time. It was used successfully in the Candidates 2018 by Fabiano Caruana, who went on to win the event and even used the Petroff twice in the World Championship match in 2018, forcing the reigning World Champion to temporarily abandon  1.e4! }
3. Nxe5
{ Apart from this,  3.d4  remains to be the only challenging attempt to try for an advantage and this has been recommended by Anish Giri in his 1.e4 Lifetime Repertoires. I feel that the line I give is more annoying and quite depressing for the Black side compared to 3.d4 where you can survive by being well equipped with engine lines and trusting in correspondence players who have managed to exhaust most of White's tries. }
3... Nc6
{ The famous Stafford Gambit is being singlehandedly popularized by its chief advocate, Eric Rosen, who has managed to win many nice games with it during the pandemic. }
4. Nxc6 { The best way to refute a gambit is to accept it! } 4... dxc6 5. d3
{ This is more sound than 5.Nc3, it is better to focus on the kingside development and stop any evil threats from the Rosen Army. }
5... Bc5 { Black threatens the deadly Ng4 move. } 6. Be2
{ Stopping it and hoping to laugh at Black's concept with our extra pawn. }
6... h5
{ This is the main idea behind the nonsense :@@EndBracket@@!   After  6...Ng4  7.Bxg4  Qh4  With a double attack on f2 and g4. Now White can claim the advantage with either  8.Qf3  or  8.g3  I leave the choice with you! }
7. c3
{ Preparing d4 putting an end to Black's unrealistic attacking ambitions. I noticed that Sethu stops here, and I decided to do the same... since analyzing this silly line any more would be disrespecting our noble sport :@@EndBracket@@. }
*

