{ White has tried other knight retreats to d3 and c4, but frankly it can hardly challenge Black...If he knows what he is doing! }
4... Nxe4 5. Nc3
{ Don Fabi was pretty much unstoppable during Berlin Candidates 2018...there was only one person who could stop him delivering him the only defeat in the event, It was none other than Sergey Karjakin - the previous challenger for the World Championship. He used this line and created an absolute masterpiece! }
5... Nxc3 { This is Black's best move and that's already saying something! } 6.
dxc3
{ Let's take a headcount: We have doubled our pawns on the c-file which makes sure that our king will have a haven on the queenside, also the d-file can be used for our domination purposes, and finally, the pawns will help us control the central squares to move forward with c4-c5 should the need arise. These combined factors make this line a complete nightmare and a depressing line with minimal winning chances for Black. }
6... Be7
{ Black's best move! Keeping both options of castling. Meanwhile 6...Nc6 would be too committal as it means he wants to castle queenside since it doesn't go well with kingside castling.  6...Nc6  7.Bf4  Be7  will transpose back to 6...Be7 lines. }
7. Bf4
{ Together, let's make 7. Bf4 great again! Although this was the old mainline, it has been overtaken in popularity by 7.Be3, where, in my opinion, most of the lines have been worked out to a draw. The idea is to keep an eye on e5 and d6 while fighting against Black's main concept of gaining central control with c6 and d5. }
7... Nc6
{ The solid and reliable approach with the idea to go for queenside castling. Black's position is without any structural defects, so he shouldn't worry much here. }
8. Qd2 { Preparing to castle long. } 8... Be6
{ The other alternatives seem to give an easy advantage, so this is Black's best bet. }
9. O-O-O { Finishing the daily routine and getting ready for Phase 2. } 9...
Qd7
{ Black needs just one more move to finish his development and tuck the king to safety. }
10. h4
{ Threatening Ng5 to win the bishop pair and improve the pawn structure. Black can't afford to give the light-squared bishop, so his next move is more or less forced. I like this move since it cuts down Black's options and forces him to go via a narrow path. }
10... h6
{ It was necessary to prevent Ng5 which would guarantee White an easy advantage due to the bishop pair. }
11. Kb1
{ The calm before the storm! A useful prophylactic move waiting for queenside castling from Black... }
11... O-O-O
{ The safest way as castling kingside would be asking for trouble and would lead to immediate collapse after Bxh6 leading to a winning attack. }
12. Nd4
{ Once again Black can't allow Nxe6 which would allow us to dominate on the light-squares using our f1 bishop and hence he has to agree to enter the tactical fight! }
12... Nxd4 13. Qxd4 { A cool double attack on a7 and g7. } 13... a6
{ The only other alternative which is decent. } 14. Qxg7
{ Breaking the pawn structure and not fearing the loosely placed f4 bishop which gives rise to many tactical threats. }
14... Bxa2+
{ The right way to make use of the f4-bishop, the other attempt with  14...Qa4  would be rudely met with  15.c4!  leading to a big advantage due to the better pawn structure. }
15. Kc1
{ Although  15.Kxa2  might also give some edge, I feel this is more complex and better suited in our never-ending fight to get an advantage! }
15... Be6
{ The bishop has had his fun and it was time to return before we trap it with b3. That's right people, everyone fears b3 :@@EndBracket@@! }
16. g3
{ Protecting the f4-bishop freeing the f1-bishop from its lazy duty of protecting the g2-pawn and preparing ideas like Bh3 if the black queen leaves her place on d7. We have the better position due to our pawn structure. }
