12. Nd4
{ Once again Black can't allow Nxe6 which would allow us to dominate on the light-squares using our f1 bishop and hence he has to agree to enter the tactical fight! }
12... Nxd4 13. Qxd4 { A cool double attack on a7 and g7. } 13... c5
{ The combative way of fighting against the double attack, but after this committal decision both the black pawns on c and d-files will need constant supervision. Additionally, the black king also becomes very weak due to our strong bishop on f4, which is cutting into Black's position via the h2-b8 diagonal. }
14. Qe3
{ The strongest retreat, leaving the d-file for the rook to put pressure on the d-pawn while the queen wishes to go to g3 to keep an eye on the g7-pawn and the h2-b8 diagonal assisting our dark-squared bishop. }
14... Rhe8
{ Black has to play with a lot of restraints here! Natural moves might give the edge to White.   14...d5  is the human reaction, but it has a flaw.  15.Be5!  The bishop continues to find new ways to annoy Black leading to a cool edge, thanks to the weakened h2-b8 diagonal long diagonal and the potential long-term target on the d5-pawn for our f1-bishop after we do Be2-f3. }
15. Qg3
{ The queen has found the most annoying location for our opponent, waiting like a predator to go after her prey. }
15... Bf6
{ Protecting the important pawn on g7 and the d6-pawn is saved due to our poor development and tactical ideas involving Qa4.   15...Qa4  Hoping for the cowboy move.  16.a3  .  It pains my heart to say this, but I have to accept the truth here and recommend the move which is better than 16.b3 @@StartBracket@@I am sorry everyone...@@EndBracket@@  16...d5  Black hopes to create some play in the center.  17.Re1!  with nice pressure along the e-file and the h2-b8 diagonal. We continue with Bd3 next, Black's situation is unenviable.   15...g5  Black attempts to break free with this move.  16.hxg5  hxg5  17.Bc1!  I like the fact that our bishops are ideally placed on the first rank ready to be unleashed at a moment's notice! The rooks are putting pressure on their respective files. Black is unable to equalize here due to our lasting pressure on the d6/g5 pawns. }
16. a3 { Stopping any Qa4 threats and threatening to take on d6. } 16... d5
{ Whenever Black plays this provocative move, the f4-bishop smiles mischievously to himself :@@EndBracket@@. }
17. Bd3
{ Finishing our development to go Rhe1 next, followed by good pressure along the d- and e-files backed by superior bishops in comparison to their counterparts. I think we have a nice and annoying pull. }
