{ I will borrow the sayings of a famous philosopher and futurist: 'There are two sets of Petroff players, one who goes for the kingside castling braving the kingside assaults of the White players to survive and live to see another day  @@StartBracket@@though they also get checkmated occasionally :@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@ like Kramnik, Gelfand & co...   While the second set of Chinese players like Wang Yue, Yu Yangyi, Bu Xiangzhi prefer to go for the solid @@StartBracket@@but depressing@@EndBracket@@ queenside castling to suffer @@StartBracket@@for the entire game :@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@ and make a draw without having to worry about any pawn storms! I have personally been part of both sides! - Anish Giri.' @@StartBracket@@The following dialogue is purely based on the memory of the author, it wasn't edited to annoy my lord in any way...@@EndBracket@@ }
8. Qd2 { Signalling the start of the war by preparing queenside castling. }
8... Nd7
{ 8...Re8  9.O-O-O  and Black doesn't have any option but to transpose back to the mainlines  9...Nc6  transposing to @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/3p4/8/5B2/2P2N2/PPPQ1PPP/R3KB1R b KQ - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nd7  9.O-O-O  Re8  . }
9. O-O-O
{ As mentioned earlier, the king is going to enjoy a safe game while he can watch his counterpart run for his life :@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Nf6 { This is the 3rd most popular move, so I decided to cover it. } 10.
h4
{ Once again, our concept is the same: h4 with the intention of either h5-h6 or Ng5 and letting the knight stay there to create attacking ideas. }
10... Bg4
{ Pinning the knight and hoping to destroy our pawn structure, but we needn't be bothered by it...since taking on f3 would give us the bishop pair and play along the g-file. }
11. Re1
{ A strong novelty preparing the deadly Ng5 move followed by a kingside pawn storm with f3 and g4. We have strong attacking chances on the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) The Petroff Pipelines"]
[Black "3...d6 with 5...Nxc3 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... e5
{ To date, this is one of the most solid responses intended to put an end to our attacking ambitions! Black wants to copy our central pawn push and wants to believe that it is enough to neutralize our first move advantage. If you are looking for a cool repertoire with 1...e5 from the Black side, I would recommend Sethuraman's 1...e5 Lifetime Repertoires, which is definitely one of the best LTR's out there and raised the standard of opening theory forever! }
2. Nf3
{ We begin the fight for the center, developing our knight and increasing the influence over e5, d4, g5, and h4-squares.   Since our repertoire is Italian based, we can also play  2.Bc4  Nf6  3.d3  If Black is not careful he can run into a transposition after  3...Nc6  4.Nf3  leading to our mainlines.   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/2B1P3/3P4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c6!  is the right way for a Petroff player, leading to an equal and comfortable game for Black. }
2... Nf6
{ And so it begins! This is one of the oldest and most reliable defenses used by almost all the top players from time to time. It was used successfully in the Candidates 2018 by Fabiano Caruana, who went on to win the event and even used the Petroff twice in the World Championship match in 2018, forcing the reigning World Champion to temporarily abandon  1.e4! }
3. Nxe5
{ Apart from this,  3.d4  remains to be the only challenging attempt to try for an advantage and this has been recommended by Anish Giri in his 1.e4 Lifetime Repertoires. I feel that the line I give is more annoying and quite depressing for the Black side compared to 3.d4 where you can survive by being well equipped with engine lines and trusting in correspondence players who have managed to exhaust most of White's tries. }
3... d6
{ A necessary inclusion before restoring the material balance by taking on e4. }
4. Nf3
{ White has tried other knight retreats to d3 and c4, but frankly it can hardly challenge Black...If he knows what he is doing! }
4... Nxe4 5. Nc3
{ Don Fabi was pretty much unstoppable during Berlin Candidates 2018...there was only one person who could stop him delivering him the only defeat in the event, It was none other than Sergey Karjakin - the previous challenger for the World Championship. He used this line and created an absolute masterpiece! }
5... Nxc3 { This is Black's best move and that's already saying something! } 6.
dxc3
{ Let's take a headcount: We have doubled our pawns on the c-file which makes sure that our king will have a haven on the queenside, also the d-file can be used for our domination purposes, and finally, the pawns will help us control the central squares to move forward with c4-c5 should the need arise. These combined factors make this line a complete nightmare and a depressing line with minimal winning chances for Black. }
6... Be7
{ Black's best move! Keeping both options of castling. Meanwhile 6...Nc6 would be too committal as it means he wants to castle queenside since it doesn't go well with kingside castling.  6...Nc6  7.Bf4  Be7  will transpose back to 6...Be7 lines. }
7. Bf4
{ Together, let's make 7. Bf4 great again! Although this was the old mainline, it has been overtaken in popularity by 7.Be3, where, in my opinion, most of the lines have been worked out to a draw. The idea is to keep an eye on e5 and d6 while fighting against Black's main concept of gaining central control with c6 and d5. }
7... O-O
{ I will borrow the sayings of a famous philosopher and futurist: 'There are two sets of Petroff players, one who goes for the kingside castling braving the kingside assaults of the White players to survive and live to see another day  @@StartBracket@@though they also get checkmated occasionally :@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@ like Kramnik, Gelfand & co...   While the second set of Chinese players like Wang Yue, Yu Yangyi, Bu Xiangzhi prefer to go for the solid @@StartBracket@@but depressing@@EndBracket@@ queenside castling to suffer @@StartBracket@@for the entire game :@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@ and make a draw without having to worry about any pawn storms! I have personally been part of both sides! - Anish Giri.' @@StartBracket@@The following dialogue is purely based on the memory of the author, it wasn't edited to annoy my lord in any way...@@EndBracket@@ }
8. Qd2 { Signalling the start of the war by preparing queenside castling. }
8... Nd7
{ 8...Re8  9.O-O-O  and Black doesn't have any option but to transpose back to the mainlines  9...Nc6  transposing to @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/3p4/8/5B2/2P2N2/PPPQ1PPP/R3KB1R b KQ - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nd7  9.O-O-O  Re8  . }
9. O-O-O
{ As mentioned earlier, the king is going to enjoy a safe game while he can watch his counterpart run for his life :@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Nc5
{ The knight finds an active location where it keeps an eye in the center and can also influence the queenside actions.   9...Re8  10.h4  Nc5  will transpose back to our mainline from 9...Nc5. }
10. h4
{ AlphaZero would approve of this move! The intention is to put the knight on g5 next, followed by Bd3 or Bc4, and Black will start questioning all his life decisions, starting with the idea to play Petroff against us!   Of course, comp gives his favorite eval 0.00, but practically we are up against a human opponent, which is what the World Champion Magnus Carlsen continues to show...Let us be inspired by him and not just look at the engine evaluations. We should remember we are playing chess aimed against a human who is fully capable of making mistakes! }
10... Bg4
{ Optically this move looks very nice since we just weakened the g4-square by playing h4 and Black would immediately like to seize that opportunity by placing a piece there... Sadly for Black, things are never that simple when opposite-side castling is on the board. We literally don't care about sacrificing pawns, pieces, or weakening our pawn structure if it means we are opening a file that will help us attack the enemy king! }
11. Re1 { 'Please take on f3, give me the bishop pair, and open the g-file!' }
11... Re8
{ Hoping to exchange a pair of rooks to reduce our attacking potential. } 12.
Nd4
{ Followed by f3-g4 with the typical pawn storm which will give us very good attacking chances. }
*

