8... Nd7
{ 8...Re8  9.O-O-O  and Black doesn't have any option but to transpose back to the mainlines  9...Nc6  transposing to @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/3p4/8/5B2/2P2N2/PPPQ1PPP/R3KB1R b KQ - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nd7  9.O-O-O  Re8  . }
9. O-O-O
{ As mentioned earlier, the king is going to enjoy a safe game while he can watch his counterpart run for his life :@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Nc5
{ The knight finds an active location where it keeps an eye in the center and can also influence the queenside actions.   9...Re8  10.h4  Nc5  will transpose back to our mainline from 9...Nc5. }
10. h4
{ AlphaZero would approve of this move! The intention is to put the knight on g5 next, followed by Bd3 or Bc4, and Black will start questioning all his life decisions, starting with the idea to play Petroff against us!   Of course, comp gives his favorite eval 0.00, but practically we are up against a human opponent, which is what the World Champion Magnus Carlsen continues to show...Let us be inspired by him and not just look at the engine evaluations. We should remember we are playing chess aimed against a human who is fully capable of making mistakes! }
10... c6
{ An old-line which has been completely shelved, since Black has to enter an endgame where he has to suffer to make a draw. }
11. Bxd6
{ Entering a forcing sequence where both sides can't deviate much. Other moves don't offer much for us. }
11... Qxd6
{ The only option as Ne4 can be met with Bxe7.   11...Bxd6  12.Qxd6  Qxd6  13.Rxd6  will transpose to the mainlines. }
12. Qxd6 Bxd6 13. Rxd6
{ At the moment we have an extra pawn, hence Black's next move is forced to maintain material equality. }
13... Ne4
{ Black's entire concept starting with 10...c6 works due to this cute knight fork on d6 and f2. }
14. Rd4 { The only way not to lose material! } 14... Nxf2 15. Rg1
{ Although the pawn structure doesn't favor us, since Black has the pawn majority on the kingside while our pawns are doubled on the queenside...The activity of our pieces and firm control of the d-file tips the balance to our side. }
15... Ng4
{ The mission has been accomplished, hence it was time to return.   15...c5  only helps us.  16.Rf4  followed by Bc4 next with a nice advantage thanks to the pressure on f7. }
16. Bc4 { Putting pressure on Black's main vulnerable spot - the f7-pawn. }
16... Bf5
{ Black has finished his development and has high hopes in the upcoming endgame thanks to the kingside pawn majority. }
17. Bd3
{ A surprising change of pace! We use the fact that the bishop is overloaded on f5 and change our pawn structure advantageously! }
17... Bxd3 { Other moves should give us a simple advantage. } 18. cxd3
{ Finally! Our days of being stuck with the doubled c-pawns are over. It is important to remember that in middlegames these pawns are better doubled to give protection to our king, whereas in the endgame, they are better off as mobile/undoubled pawns. }
18... Nf6
{ The knight returns to prevent the penetration along the 7th rank with Rd7. }
19. g4
{ Gaining space on the kingside and preparing to annoy the f6-knight with g5 next. We have a slight advantage thanks to the queenside majority which seems more potent than the kingside which will be not easy to use for Black. }
*

