12. Bc4
{ The beginning of the 'Crisis on the kingside'. The target is locked onto f7. }
12... Bxg5
{ Another thing I like about my recommendation is that Black can't deviate without the risk of running into a worse position and has to dance to our tunes! }
13. hxg5
{ The h-file has been opened and Black has to follow the greedy path to survive! }
13... Ne4
{ The knight joins the defense department and hopes to confuse us with the double attack on d2 and g5. }
14. Bxf7+
{ Blasting open Black's position and getting the king out into the open where he will be a constant source of worry for our enemy! }
14... Kxf7 15. Qd5+
{ A beautiful check which is difficult to answer for Black, since he needs to keep protecting the knight on e4. }
15... Re6 { Only move, other moves will lose instantly. } 16. gxh6
{ Slowly but surely getting rid of Black king's protective shelter. } 16... Bd7
{ A move which is difficult to understand :@@EndBracket@@...I guess Black just wants to finish his development and also prevent us from queening the h-pawn after all, it is just two steps away from becoming a new queen!   16...Qf6  was seen before.  17.Be3  was clearly better for White and he won in @@StartBracket@@Santhosh-Ornek ICCF email 2008@@EndBracket@@. }
17. h7 { One step away! } 17... Qf6
{ A forced reaction, tactically stopping h7-pawn from queening by attacking the f4-bishop. }
18. Be3 { The bishop and the h-pawn is worth more than a rook! } 18... Rh8 19.
Qxb7 { Time to take back the invested material. } 19... Qd8
{ Only way to defend c7-pawn. } 20. Qxa7
{ We have four pawns @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ for the piece and a weak king. I think this is a good alternative to our mainline. }
