{ 5.Nc3  O-O  6.a3!?  Trying to keep the game very similar to our mainline.  6...d6  7.h3!  Preventing Bg4 ideas.  7...Be6   7...h6  8.g4!  is an idea, Black has to be careful about.  8.Nd5  with a slight pull. I think this is a very good and simple alternative to our mainline. }
5... O-O { Black wants to keep both d5 and d6 as options. } 6. Re1
{ The most straightforward way with the idea to stop d5 from Black. } 6... d6
{ Black hopes to play either Be6 which is very reliable and solid or the adventurous Bg4 which might be possible in lines where we go for Nc3.   6...h6  is the second-best alternative, but it can't pose any challenge to us.  7.c3  d6  8.b4  with a good advantage thanks to the space control on the queenside. }
7. a3
{ This is more restrained than  7.a4  and keeps the idea of expanding on the queenside with b4 while at the same time restricting Black's ideas involving Nb4. }
7... Kh8
{ Black is embarking on a very ambitious plan which involves the f5-break to open the f-file and create some play on the kingside. }
8. Nc3 { Time to be very forceful and fight against Black's plan. } 8... Bg4
{ Black threatens Nd4 next, so we need to take precautions against it. } 9. h3
{ A memory pointer - h3 is always useful for us and we should automatically play it before proceeding for the next plan. }
9... Bh5 { Black doesn't want to take on f3 and give the bishop pair. } 10. Be3
{ The main threat with Nd4 has been neutralized. } 10... Qd7
{ Stopping g4 which will be met with Nxg4 winning two pawns! } 11. Nd5
{ Exchanging the important f6-knight after which g4 becomes a possibility ending the reign of the bishop on h5. Black can't equalize here. }
