[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... e5
{ To date, this is one of the most solid responses intended to put an end to our attacking ambitions! Black wants to copy our central pawn push and wants to believe that it is enough to neutralize our first move advantage.If you are looking for a cool repertoire with 1...e5 from the Black side, I would recommend Sethuraman's 1... e5 Lifetime Repertoires which is definitely one of the best LTR's out there and raised the standard of opening theory forever! }
2. Nf3
{ We begin the fight for the center, developing our knight and increasing the influence over e5, d4, g5, and h4-squares. }
2... Nc6
{ Protecting the things which are important... like the e5-pawn. Petroff players will never understand this feeling :@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Bc4
{ The Italian Game is one of the biggest revelations of the 21st century as it saw itself rise in popularity giving a tough fight to the undisputed mainline which is Ruy Lopez with 3.Bb5. I am more fond of this line since I have nice memories of winning many games... sometimes ending the game with a mating attack and occasionally torturing my opponents in a positional game.It is the perfect opening for both dynamic and positional players as I feel 'The opening doesn't define who you want to be!'. I would also like to quote the best saying ever said about the Italian 'Everyone pretends to understand the subtleties of the Italian game, but nobody really does!'- MVL. }
3... Nf6
{ The beginning of the Two Knights Defense. We have three interesting options here:1@@EndBracket@@  4.Ng5  as recommended in Wesley's 1.e4 LTR which is a fighting weapon, but I think White is on the defensive having taken the greedy path.2@@EndBracket@@  4.d4  seen in Jones's Coffeehouse repertoire book, but I think Sethu's  1...e5  LTR does a very good job of putting an end to this line.3@@EndBracket@@  4.d3  which is what I and Anish Giri recommend, taking the fight to positional waters! @@StartBracket@@Just kidding :@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@ }
4. d3
{ Simply protecting the e4-pawn and preparing the transposition to Bg5 territory should Black play 4...Bc5. }
4... d5
{ Black strikes in the center to achieve some control over it...but this can hardly work as he is just too underdeveloped to be getting involved in such affairs. }
5. exd5 Nxd5
{ If Black gets the time to castle and protect the e5-pawn comfortably, then he will be doing fine... This only works in the dreamland! }
6. O-O
{ Re1 is coming next and Black has to choose between many worse continuations! }
6... Be7 { Closing the e-file and preparing to castle into safety. } 7. Re1
{ Attacking e5-pawn and forcing Black to make some unpleasant decisions to weaken the a2-g8 diagonal or embark on a dodgy pawn sacrifice with Bg4. }
7... f6 { Saving the e5-pawn even at the cost of weakening the long diagonal. }
8. c3
{ An useful move preparing d4 and Qb3 ideas. I am not sure about Anish's recommendation with 8.d4 since I feel Black has good chances to equalize there. In my opinion Black has taken some liberties by prematurely opening the position, weakening the e5-pawn in the process without fully finishing his development...hence the punishment shouldn't be easy going! }
8... Nb6
{ Black has had enough of the pressure along the a2-c4 diagonal and completely abandons it for our Italian bishop :@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Bb3 Bg4
{ Black has the slow and steady plan with Bh5 and Bf7 hoping to neutralize our mighty bishop on b3. }
10. a4 { A cool pawn thrust to annoy Black's knight on b6 with a5. } 10... a5
{ Better to prevent it, but this weakens the b5-square which can be used as an outpost with Na3-b5 for our b1-knight. }
11. h3 { It might seem like we are helping Black by forcing Bh5 and Bf7... }
11... Bh5
{ Black is happy to play Bf7 next to exchange our bishop and then do 'Artificial castling' with Rf8-Kg8 after the eventual Bxf7+. }
12. d4
{ The most energetic response making Black regret his opening concept! Opening the e- and d-files. }
12... exd4 { No other go for Black. } 13. Na3
{ Not wasting time on material things and going for the kill with an epic double pawn sacrifice! }
13... dxc3 14. Qe2
{ Avoiding the queen exchange and keeping the pressure! Black can't escape without serious damage due to the pressure exhibited by the Italian bishop on b3 stopping Black king from castling. Black also can't escape with Nd4 since that would allow Qxe7+ Qxe7 Rxe7+ followed by Nxd4 with an advantageous two pieces vs rook endgame. }
*

