{ The beginning of the Two Knights Defense. We have three interesting options here:1@@EndBracket@@  4.Ng5  as recommended in Wesley's 1.e4 LTR which is a fighting weapon, but I think White is on the defensive having taken the greedy path.2@@EndBracket@@  4.d4  seen in Jones's Coffeehouse repertoire book, but I think Sethu's  1...e5  LTR does a very good job of putting an end to this line.3@@EndBracket@@  4.d3  which is what I and Anish Giri recommend, taking the fight to positional waters! @@StartBracket@@Just kidding :@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@ }
4. d3
{ Simply protecting the e4-pawn and preparing the transposition to Bg5 territory should Black play 4...Bc5. }
4... d5
{ Black strikes in the center to achieve some control over it...but this can hardly work as he is just too underdeveloped to be getting involved in such affairs. }
5. exd5 Nxd5
{ If Black gets the time to castle and protect the e5-pawn comfortably, then he will be doing fine... This only works in the dreamland! }
6. O-O
{ Re1 is coming next and Black has to choose between many worse continuations! }
6... Be7 { Closing the e-file and preparing to castle into safety. } 7. Re1
{ Attacking e5-pawn and forcing Black to make some unpleasant decisions to weaken the a2-g8 diagonal or embark on a dodgy pawn sacrifice with Bg4. }
7... f6 { Saving the e5-pawn even at the cost of weakening the long diagonal. }
8. c3
{ An useful move preparing d4 and Qb3 ideas. I am not sure about Anish's recommendation with 8.d4 since I feel Black has good chances to equalize there. In my opinion Black has taken some liberties by prematurely opening the position, weakening the e5-pawn in the process without fully finishing his development...hence the punishment shouldn't be easy going! }
8... Be6
{ Paravyan the main shareholder of this line has put his hope in this move. }
9. Bb3
{ An epic retreat preparing d4 next using the pressure along the e-file and unprotected bishop on e6. It is important to note that the direct  9.d4  will be met by  9...Nxc3  utilizing the unprotected bishop on c4 leading to lots of simplifications! }
9... Bf7 { Hoping to discourage us from playing d4... } 10. d4
{ We stay on course and open the position! This is the only way to retain the advantage, so we must be energetic! }
10... exd4
{ Other moves will either win us the e-pawn or at least keep an annoying isolated pawn on e5 after dxe5. }
11. Nxd4 { The d4-knight wishes to go e6 or f5! } 11... Nxd4
{ Obviously Black can't allow that to happen. } 12. Qxd4
{ With a solid advantage since Black can't castle immediately due to Bxd5 followed by Rxe7 winning two pieces for a rook and he has to waste a tempo with c6 after which we can continue with Qe4 continuing to stop him from castling! }
*

