{ The typical Italian move, controlling the central squares with the idea to go b4 at the right time and also prepare a safe return for our light-squared bishop. Black has many interesting directions here, but luckily for us most of them have a lot of transpositional qualities, and as long as we understand the concepts which we should execute, we will end as the better-prepared player knowing what to do while our opponents will be confused in a complicated labyrinth! }
7... g5
{ This is possibly the most popular reaction in shorter time controls. } 8. Bg3
Nh5
{ This is a big blunder! I was very surprised that it featured in the classical game between @@StartBracket@@Zubov-Ganguly 2018@@EndBracket@@ and @@StartBracket@@Blanco-Shirov Rapid 2019@@EndBracket@@... both times White missed the chance to get a winning advantage. }
9. Nxe5 { Using the discovered attack on h5! } 9... Nxg3
{ Otherwise, Black will be a pawn down. } 10. Bxf7+
{ The key move without which, this line wouldn't work. } 10... Kf8 11. Ng6+
{ Another important point reaching a position with a material imbalance that will favor us. }
11... Kxf7
{ Forced since  11...Kg7  doesn't change anything after  12.hxg3  and the rook on h8 is still trapped :@@EndBracket@@. }
12. Nxh8+
{ It is important that everything must happen with check without giving Black any chance to play Nxh1 or Bxf2+. }
12... Qxh8 13. hxg3
{ The dust has settled, though materially Black is doing fine having two pieces for a rook and two pawns, the weak king on f7 has a 'Wanted' title on his head tipping the balance in our favor. We continue with O-O, d4, and Nd2 with a nice advantage. }
