7... g5
{ This is possibly the most popular reaction in shorter time controls. } 8. Bg3
Bg4
{ The bishop is misplaced here and gets in the way of his pawns in the kingside. }
9. h3
{ Forcing the bishop to h5 where it will look even worse than on g4 :@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Bh5 10. Nbd2
{ Cooly continuing our development and not deciding about the fate of our king. He might just chill in the center :@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Qd7
{ Black is also not sure what to do with his king and develops his queen to enable queenside castling :@@EndBracket@@.   10...a6  11.b4  Ba7  12.a4  Qd7  will transpose back to the mainlines with 10...Qd7. }
11. a4 { Before Black can even think about O-O-O, we start the assault! } 11...
a6
{ The alternative way with  11...a5  weakens the b5-square and allows us to gain the advantage with  12.Bb5  followed by d4 in the future. }
12. b4 { Showing no restraints! } 12... Ba7 13. Rb1
{ Preparing to continue our queenside expansion, we will only castle kingside after our opponent does it. We can continue with b5 if Black refuses to budge by not castling kingside. }
