9... g5
{ Black is not going to chicken and ready is for a full-fledged fight! } 10.
Bg3
{ The bishop plays the overprotective brother role for our king keeping him safe and also puts pressure on e5 which will become crucial when we breakthrough in the center with d4. }
10... O-O
{ Since we have also castled, Black feels he is quite safe to do the same. }
11. a4 { Protecting the bishop on c4 and not allowing Na5 ideas. } 11... Kg7
{ Some players have felt that it is essential to make this move before deciding on the next plan...But I think it is just slow and not required to spend a tempo on this move. }
12. Re1 { The winter is coming via d4 :@@EndBracket@@. } 12... Nh7
{ Black protects the g5-pawn, preparing both h5 and f5. } 13. d4
{ Before Black can do something evil on the kingside, It was time to take over the center with a nice pawn sacrifice which is actually poisoned and Black shouldn't take it immediately. }
13... g4
{ The ever solid Peter Leko also couldn't withstand the pressure and went for this greedy pawn grab. }
14. Nh4
{ The knight can jump to f5 at the right moment forcing the exchange of the c8-bishop which in turn weakens the g4-pawn. }
14... exd4
{ @@StartBracket@@Jorden van Foreest-Leko Douglas 2016@@EndBracket@@ Although Jorden won a fantastic game, I think we could learn from his game and go for the much stronger continuation. }
15. Kh1
{ A cool prophylactic move to enable the terrifying f4 break which will split Black's defenses apart leading to a solid advantage for us! Black is already in big trouble and looking for good advice. After f4 we can also go back with Rf1 since the rook might be more useful there than on e1. }
