13... h5
{ Black begins his kingside pawn storm to distract our forces from the center.   13...exd4  this greedy move is just horrible.  14.e5!  @@StartBracket@@Fedoseev-Nakamura Blitz 2020@@EndBracket@@ lead to a huge winning advantage for White due to the opening of the position which will end in the hunt of the black king whose weak kingside will be the reason for his demise. }
14. h3
{ In this specific situation it is better to play h3 to keep some control over the d4-square. }
14... g4 { Black continues to insist! } 15. Nh4
{ Duda-Nakamura continued with 15.Bh4, but this feels stronger. } 15... exd4
{ We have been following @@StartBracket@@Kuhne-Misericordia LSS email 2017@@EndBracket@@ and here we make the deviation. }
16. Rc1
{ Improving over the forementioned correspondence game. The a1-rook was missing out on the central and queenside conflict, so it was time to bring in the heavy artillery! }
16... dxc3 { Other moves will give us the edge. } 17. Rxc3
{ The rook joins the fight via the 3rd rank and the Black king is already starting to sweat a bit looking at the concentration of the White forces... all of them getting ready for the final attack! }
17... Bd4 { Only move otherwise Black is toast after hxg4 or Nf5 ideas. } 18.
Rd3
{ I think this is a good time to stop since our initiative is starting to reach deadly proportions and Black needs to make many only moves to neutralize our pressure. I feel Black can only survive this position in correspondence with difficulty, but definitely not in a human game, and also nobody wouldn't want to reach this position as Black! }
