{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... e5
{ To date, this is one of the most solid responses intended to put an end to our attacking ambitions! Black wants to copy our central pawn push and wants to believe that it is enough to neutralize our first move advantage.If you are looking for a cool repertoire with 1...e5 from the Black side, I would recommend Sethuraman's 1... e5 Lifetime Repertoires which is definitely one of the best LTR's out there and raised the standard of opening theory forever! }
2. Nf3
{ We begin the fight for the center, developing our knight and increasing the influence over e5, d4, g5, and h4-squares. }
2... Nc6
{ Protecting the things which are important... like the e5-pawn. Petroff players will never understand this feeling :@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Bc4
{ The Italian Game is one of the biggest revelations of the 21st century as it saw itself rise in popularity giving a tough fight to the undisputed mainline which is Ruy Lopez with 3.Bb5. I am more fond of this line since I have nice memories of winning many games... sometimes ending the game with a mating attack and occasionally torturing my opponents in a positional game.It is the perfect opening for both dynamic and positional players as I feel 'The opening doesn't define who you want to be!'. I would also like to quote the best saying ever said about the Italian 'Everyone pretends to understand the subtleties of the Italian game, but nobody really does!'- MVL. }
3... Bc5
{ I think this is officially the beginning of the Giuoco Piano system. Black would like to develop his bishop in a similar way to ours and claim that he will have sufficient resources to outbalance the first move advantage. I have had pleasant memories with this line since I managed to invent a line that briefly shifted the balance of power to the Black side thanks to my victories against Jordan van Foreest and Amin Bassem two very strong exponents of the Italian from the white side. }
4. d3
{ This has been dubbed as the Giuoco Pianissimo: 'Very Quiet Game' a name given by Adolf Andersson, one of the masters of the Romantic era! White aims for a slow buildup, deferring the push to d4 until it can be prepared. By avoiding an immediate confrontation in the center, White prevents the early release of tension through exchanges and enters a positional maneuvering game. At least this is what has been given in Wikipedia.I would like to challenge these notions and prefer to name my chapter as the 'Fast and the Furious' not because I am a fan of the movie series, but to show that we are not in a charity business and we play this line to destroy our opponents with maximum brute force! }
4... Nf6 5. Bg5
{ The beginning of the end... This is a famous expression of 'my uncle' Lev Psakhis since he always used to passionately call me as 'nephew' during his tenure as the trainer for the Indian Olympic team.We are raising the stakes with this move and Black won't have his usual easy life of exchanging pieces and being solid! Anton Demchenko is one of the leading exponents of this line and it will be worth studying his games to understand the intricacies of our line.WARNING: COPYRIGHT VIOLATION! The following extract has been shamelessly copied word to word from Jan Gustafsson's 1...e5 Lifetime repertoires. 'This seems to be becoming a bit of a thing, both directly and after 5. c3 d6 or a6. It is another set of ideas I have had to change longheld beliefs while writing this: I used to argue that Bg5 makes no sense before black plays d6, as we will just go h6 Bh4 Be7, then d6, then Nh5 at a suitable moment, then face a bright future. I still consider this a reasonable plan, but silly engines and their willingness to go for an early Bg3, sometimes even h3 Bh2, has made me understand things are not that simple. My adjustment was going Be7 without h6, so no more Bg3. But that allows the bishop to drop back to e3 when needed and it's far from clear who benefitted from that little dance.So, phase 3 @@StartBracket@@current@@EndBracket@@: We meet Bg5 with our standard plan, d6, a6, Ba7 @@StartBracket@@after going h6.@@EndBracket@@ Then we will hopefully be well-positioned to go for g5-Nh5. Our argument shall be that the bishop on a7 is a powerhouse and would have wasted his best years by going back to e7.' - Gusti.I can't think of a better way to explain the Bg5 systems :@@EndBracket@@! I hope he forgives me for this violation of privacy and security! }
5... h6
{ Always a useful inclusion.   5...d6  6.c3  and Black can't do without the h6 move which will transpose back to 5...h6 lines. }
6. Bh4
{ The bishop will continue to annoy Black with the h4-d8 diagonal pin and force him to play g5 or Be7 at some point. }
6... d6
{ Opening the bishop's path, aimed against a future c3-d4 from White.   6...O-O  7.Nc3  willtranspose to 5...O-O Shankland's line. }
7. c3
{ The typical Italian move, controlling the central squares with the idea to go b4 at the right time and also prepare a safe return for our light-squared bishop. Black has many interesting directions here, but luckily for us most of them have a lot of transpositional qualities, and as long as we understand the concepts which we should execute, we will end as the better-prepared player knowing what to do while our opponents will be confused in a complicated labyrinth! }
7... a6
{ Black is also preparing a safe return for his bishop by copying us :@@EndBracket@@. }
8. Nbd2
{ I think it is better not to commit O-O before Qe7. Though it doesn't make much difference since anyway we want to castle into the danger zone :@@EndBracket@@.   8.O-O  Ba7  9.Nbd2  will transpose to the same lines. }
8... Ba7
{ A safe retreat aimed against any d4 or b4 moves and Black is biding his time before defining his setup.   8...Qe7  9.O-O  g5  10.Bg3  Ba7  would also transpose back to the mainlines.   8...g5  9.Bg3  O-O  9.O-O  Ba7  will  lead to transposition to 8...Ba7 mainlines. }
9. O-O
{ Time for some deep explanations, so get ready to sleep :@@EndBracket@@. This is a critical tabiya for the Bg5 line and could arise via various move orders @@StartBracket@@all roads do lead to Rome@@EndBracket@@. As a general rule, we shouldn't be afraid of Black's pawn storm with g5-h5 and it can be put to a permanent stop with h4 after which Black has many ways to continue:1@@EndBracket@@ g4 giving in to the pressure and making sure that he can't attack on the kingside anymore, the only thing we should be slightly concerned about is some knight maneuver to g6 to win the h4-pawn... but this is highly time-consuming and can be dealt with central breaks like d4 or Kh1 followed by f3 or f4 not giving Black the leisure time to attack our h-pawn.2@@EndBracket@@ gxh4 although this does open the g-file, after Bh4 Black is under a nasty pin along the h4-d8 diagonal and any threats with Rg8 can be neutralized with either Kh1 or g3 putting an end to Black's attacking ambitions.3@@EndBracket@@ Keeping the tension with Bg4. Please note that the automatic recapture with hxg5 might allow Nh7 followed by Nxg5. So we have to be precise here and only take on g5 when the time is right! Ideally, If we don't take on g5 and simply move the queen from the pin with Qe1 or Qb3 then White is doing well.4@@EndBracket@@ Nh7 also keeping the tension like Bg4, but here the kingside pawn storm has come to a standstill and we can break in the center with d4 or go for the long term queenside assault with b4-a4 followed by b5 loosening the support on the e5-pawn keeping the d4-break for the season finale :@@EndBracket@@.I think armed with these ideas, we can face any kingside pawn storms with a 'Brave Heart'. }
9... g5
{ Black is not going to chicken and ready is for a full-fledged fight! } 10.
Bg3
{ The bishop plays the overprotective brother role for our king keeping him safe and also puts pressure on e5 which will become crucial when we breakthrough in the center with d4. }
10... O-O
{ Since we have also castled, Black feels he is quite safe to do the same. }
11. a4 { Protecting the bishop on c4 and not allowing Na5 ideas. } 11... g4
{ Nakamura @@StartBracket@@in shorter time controls@@EndBracket@@ and Howell @@StartBracket@@Classical@@EndBracket@@ have fallen for this trap :@@EndBracket@@. I think Naka we can forgive, but Howell is not to be forgiven for playing this in a classical game :@@EndBracket@@. }
12. Bh4
{ A brilliant piece sacrifice for a mere pawn! After this Black is going to suffer whether he takes the piece or not! }
12... Kg7
{ This move doesn't change anything and will most likely transpose to the mainline. }
13. Kh1
{ A cool move forcing Black to take the piece as we are threatening to save the knight with Ng1 followed by the opening of the f-file with f4. }
13... gxf3 { Might as well take a piece :@@EndBracket@@. } 14. Qxf3
{ We havetransposed to the mainline from @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/bpp2p2/p1np1n1p/4p3/P1B1P1pB/2PP1N2/1P1N1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...gxf3  . }
*

