[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) 1.e4 e5 2nd & 3rd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "2...f5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... e5
{ To date, this is one of the most solid responses intended to put an end to our attacking ambitions! Black wants to copy our central pawn push and wants to believe that it is enough to neutralize our first move advantage. If you are looking for a cool repertoire with 1...e5 from the Black side, I would recommend Sethuraman's 1...e5 Lifetime Repertoires which is definitely one of the best LTR out there and raised the standard of opening theory forever! }
2. Nf3
{ We begin the fight for the center, developing our knight and increasing the influence over e5, d4, g5, and h4-squares. }
2... f5
{ The Latvian Gambit. It was invented just to confuse or scare people as early as possible. }
3. Nxe5
{ Both Sethu and Anish have also gone here. We are threatening the deadly Qh5+ next. }
3... Qf6 { Attacking the knight and then proceeding to win back the pawn. } 4.
d4
{ Capturing the center, but importantly protecting the knight on e5 :@@EndBracket@@. }
4... d6
{ It was still premature to take on e4 as that would allow Nc3 with a big advantage. }
5. Nc4
{ The ideal place for the knight and it can be sent to e3 later on to blockade the e4-pawn. If the situation demands it. }
5... fxe4
{ Black wins back the lost material, but his position looks horrible. } 6. Nc3
{ Attacking the e4-pawn and also preventing d5. } 6... Qg6
{ Black didn't have many ways to support the pawn. } 7. Ne3
{ I feel this is stronger than f3 which is the recommendation of our fellow 1.e4 LTR guys. }
7... Nf6 { Reinforcing the support of the weak e4-pawn. } 8. Be2
{ The idea is to finish our development, get the king to safety, and only then proceed to open the position with f3. }
8... c6
{ A necessary waste of time! We were threatening the nasty Ncd5 with the idea that Black can't take on d5 due to the threat of Bh5 winning the queen thanks to the pin along h5-e8 diagonal. }
9. O-O { Everything is ready, let the show begin! } 9... Be7
{ Black is hoping that he will be in time to finish castling. } 10. f3
{ Breaking the position and thanks to our well-placed minor pieces, we have a clear advantage.  10...exf3  can be met with  11.Bd3  attacking the queen on g6 followed by Rf3. }
