1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... e5
{ To date, this is one of the most solid responses intended to put an end to our attacking ambitions! Black wants to copy our central pawn push and wants to believe that it is enough to neutralize our first move advantage. If you are looking for a cool repertoire with 1...e5 from the Black side, I would recommend Sethuraman's 1...e5 Lifetime Repertoires which is definitely one of the best LTR out there and raised the standard of opening theory forever! }
2. Nf3
{ We begin the fight for the center, developing our knight and increasing the influence over e5, d4, g5, and h4-squares. }
2... d5
{ This variation is known as the Elephant Gambit. I have no idea why it is called that :@@EndBracket@@, I guess we were running out of good opening names! I have used it sometimes in bullet when I get bored :@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Nxe5
{ Anish and Sethu have recommended 3. exd5 which might be slightly stronger than the move I give, but I feel my move takes away the spirit of 2... d5 and forces Black to suffer in a worse endgame instead of getting any dynamic positions! }
3... Bd6
{ One of the main points of the gambit. Black develops his f8-bishop with tempi by attacking our knight on e5. }
4. d4 { No way we are retreating our central hero! } 4... dxe4
{ Others moves are depressing for Black. } 5. Bc4
{ This powerful move has been used by Sevian and Aravindh @@StartBracket@@in Blitz!@@EndBracket@@. It looks like they don't even give stupid openings a chance to survive! }
5... Bxe5 { Shamelessly hoping for the queen exchange via the d-file. } 6. Qh5
{ Threatening the typical 'Scholars's mate' before recapturing the hanging bishop on e5. }
6... Qe7 { The ideal way to prevent Qxf7 and Qxe5+. } 7. Qxe5
{ Now we are ready to exchange the queens under favorable circumstances. } 7...
Qxe5 8. dxe5
{ We have the bishop pair and soon both the e-pawns will disappear from the board. }
8... Nc6
{ Attacking the e5-pawn and wishing that we will waste a tempo protecting it. }
9. Nc3
{ The last memory pointer! We mustn't concern ourselves with the protection of the e5-pawn, since that reduces our advantage and gives Black good chances to equalize the game. }
9... Nxe5 10. Bb3
{ The triple threat of Nxe4, Bf4, and Nb5 makes sure that Black doesn't have the time to protect his extra pawn. }
10... Nf6
{ The most natural move @@StartBracket@@in a blitz/bullet game :@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@ . }
11. Bf4
{ Winning the pawn on c7 with a big advantage due to the bishop pair and queenside majority. }
