[White "3) 1.e4 e5 2nd & 3rd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "2...d6 3.d4 Nd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... e5
{ To date, this is one of the most solid responses intended to put an end to our attacking ambitions! Black wants to copy our central pawn push and wants to believe that it is enough to neutralize our first move advantage. If you are looking for a cool repertoire with 1...e5 from the Black side, I would recommend Sethuraman's 1...e5 Lifetime Repertoires which is definitely one of the best LTR out there and raised the standard of opening theory forever! }
2. Nf3
{ We begin the fight for the center, developing our knight and increasing the influence over e5, d4, g5, and h4-squares. }
2... d6
{ The famous Philidor defence, which has given many amazing victories for the Black side against overambitious players from the White side! The trick is not to underestimate the passive stature by treating the line with some caution, with an open eye for tactical tricks, and stopping Black's ideas with prophylactic moves. }
3. d4 { Winning the fight for the center control and space. } 3... Nd7
{ Protecting the e5-pawn and preparing Nf6-Be7 followed by O-O which might provide a passive, but decent position! }
4. Bc4
{ If we go  4.Nc3  we would allow Black to return to the 'Hanham variation' after  4...Ngf6  I am not saying that we shouldn't do that :@@EndBracket@@, but I feel our game move is much more destructive and denies Black the leisure of a transposition after the weird move order he has chosen. We are immediately highlighting the vulnerable weakness on f7 forcing Black to dissolve the center! }
4... exd4
{ 4...Ngf6  is bad.  5.dxe5  Black is in a pickle as  5...dxe5  loses to  6.Ng5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppn1ppp/3p1n2/4P3/2B1P3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nxe5  loses to  6.Nxe5  dxe5  7.Bxf7+!  Overloading the king.   4...Be7  5.dxe5!  Opening the position before Black finishes his development  5...Nxe5   5...dxe5  is horrible and loses.  6.Qd5  The f7-point collapses!  6.Nxe5  dxe5  7.Qh5  with a winning double attack on f7 and h5. }
5. Nxd4
{ The alternative with 5.Qxd4 also offers a substantial advantage, but this feels slightly stronger than that and brings the knight to a powerful central position where it controls many key squares. }
5... Ngf6
{ Gaining a tempo by attacking the e4-pawn and then proceeding to develop the f8-bishop. }
6. Nc3
{ I think we can delay kingside castling for the time being to keep options of queenside castling. }
6... g6
{ An interesting shift, to fianchetto the bishop on g7 where it will be well placed controlling the long diagonal. }
7. Bg5
{ Many times, I have noticed that provoking h6 helps us since it weakens Black's kingside and allows Qd2, attacking the h6-pawn with a gain of tempo. }
7... h6
{ 7...Bg7  8.Qd2  Preparing O-O-O  .  8...O-O  Black is trying to play without weakening his kingside with h6.  9.O-O-O  followed by h4-h5 with a fiery kingside attack. As Fischer famously quoted for dragon variation 'h4-h5, sac, sac, and mate!'. }
8. Bf4
{ The ideal retreat square where we don't need to worry about annoying knight jumps from the f6-knight. }
8... Nb6
{ 8...Bg7  The bishop feels quite well-placed on  g7  .  9.Qd2  with a space advantage and Black can't castle due to the pressure on the h6-pawn. }
9. Bb3
{ The threat of c5-c4 shouldn't scare as it seriously weakens the d6-pawn and our bishop will go to a4. }
9... Bg7 10. Qd2
{ With good pressure on Black's position, who has to solve a lot of practical issues like king safety due to the inability of kingside castling and fighting against our space advantage. }
