1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... e5
{ To date, this is one of the most solid responses intended to put an end to our attacking ambitions! Black wants to copy our central pawn push and wants to believe that it is enough to neutralize our first move advantage. If you are looking for a cool repertoire with 1...e5 from the Black side, I would recommend Sethuraman's 1...e5 Lifetime Repertoires which is definitely one of the best LTR out there and raised the standard of opening theory forever! }
2. Nf3
{ We begin the fight for the center, developing our knight and increasing the influence over e5, d4, g5, and h4-squares. }
2... d6
{ The famous Philidor defence, which has given many amazing victories for the Black side against overambitious players from the White side! The trick is not to underestimate the passive stature by treating the line with some caution, with an open eye for tactical tricks, and stopping Black's ideas with prophylactic moves. }
3. d4 { Winning the fight for the center control and space. } 3... Nf6
{ Black would like to take inspiration from Petroff :@@EndBracket@@, though this is a pale imitation of it. }
4. dxe5
{ Going for the most ambitious direction,  4.Nc3  would transpose to thePhilidor chapter. }
4... Nxe4 { Otherwise Black's opening concept would make no sense! } 5. Qd5
{ Attacking the e4-knight and using the momentum to take the queen to a dominating central location! }
5... Nc5 { Black is hoping to get Be6 and kick our queen from d5. } 6. Bg5
{ Very energetic play! Preventing Black from getting what he wants nor letting him finish his development peacefully! }
6... Be7 { is the other decent alternative. } 7. exd6
{ Opening the position and protecting the g5-bishop via the 5th rank. } 7...
Qxd6
{ The alternative was to weaken the pawn structure with  7...cxd6  which allows us to retain the advantage with  8.Nc3  . }
8. Nc3
{ White's priority is to finish development and put pressure on Black's position and punish his poorly developed pieces. Anish stops here as better for White and I decided to continue for some more moves... until I was satisfied that we are better with clear plans for our pieces. }
8... Qxd5 { At some point, Black has to accept defeat and take the queen. } 9.
Nxd5 { The double attack on e7 and c7 forces Black's next move. } 9... Bd6
{ 9...Bxg5  It is important that we don't become greedy and take on c7 which reduces our advantage.  10.Nxg5  with an undisputed advantage thanks to the pressure exerted by the two knights on d5 and g5. }
10. Be3
{ Not letting Black any resting time. The threat of Bxc5 forces the c5-knight to retreat to a passive location. }
10... Ne6 { The knight is getting in the way of the c8-bishop. } 11. O-O-O
{ We have a big endgame advantage thanks to our superior minor pieces and the bishop can be developed to Bc4 followed by Rhe1 to increase the intensity of our army! }
