{ Protecting the things which are important... like the e5-pawn :@@EndBracket@@. Petroff players will never understand this feeling :@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Bc4
{ The Italian game is one of the biggest revelations of the 21st century as it saw itself rise in popularity, giving a tough fight to the undisputed mainline, which is Ruy Lopez with 3.Bb5. I am more fond of this line since I have pleasant memories of winning many games, sometimes ending the game with a mating attack, and occasionally torturing my opponents in a positional game.It is the perfect opening for both dynamic and positional players as I feel 'The opening doesn't define who you want to be!'. I would also like to quote the best saying ever said about the Italian 'Everyone pretends to understand the subtleties of the Italian game, but nobody really does!'- MVL. }
3... Nd4
{ This is a very funny, trappy line, and I had to mention it since I don't want our dear readers to fall into the opening with  4.Nxe5  which allowed many players to create nice miniatures with  4...Qg5  5.Nxf7  @@StartBracket@@people were greedy at the beginning of time :@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@  5...Qxg2  6.Rf1  Qxe4+  7.Be2  Nf3#  It is better that we are on the Black side in this line : @@EndBracket@@ }
4. Nxd4 { The simplest reaction avoiding all sorts of traps. } 4... exd4 5. O-O
{ Finishing the castling...after this, we needn't fear any Qg5 jumps : @@EndBracket@@. }
5... Nf6 { Hoping for  6.e5  for which he can reply with  6...d5!  . } 6. Re1
{ It is better to delay 6.d3 since we might have better ways to fight for the advantage. Now we are threatening to play e5. }
6... d6 { Preventing e5 and planning Be7 followed by kingside castling. } 7. c3
{ Fighting for the center control. } 7... dxc3
{ Otherwise, he will end up with a pawn deficit. } 8. Qb3
{ The pressure on f7-pawn doesn't allow Black the time to play Be7 leading to a big development advantage. }
