{ I feel this is the best attempt for advantage. I spent some time analyzing Anish's  4.O-O  eventually transposing to lines from @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Be7  ,  I wasn't happy with a mere transposition! Black is violating the very concept of 'Space and time' by making a passive pawn move before developing his knight or Bishop, hence I feel the punishment should be more severe!Of course, this meant I had to break my head to find the exact way to do it, but it was worth the time spent! We are preparing d4 and also the sneaky Qb3 attacking f7 :@@EndBracket@@. }
4... f5
{ Black reveals his main idea behind the primitive 3rd move. He wants to fight for the kingside initiative with this pawn break.   4...Bg4  Surprisingly this is the most popular move, but it just blunders a pawn!  5.Qb3  with a nice double attack on f7 and b7 winning a pawn with advantage.   4...Nf6  is also horrible  5.Ng5  with an  advantage as the f7-pawn is in big trouble. }
5. d3
{ Since the fight is for the control of the light squares, this makes more sense. Alternatively  5.exf5  might offer good chances for the advantage. }
5... Qf6 6. exf5
{ Asking Black to choose between three options - Bxf5, Qxf5, and Nge7.   Alternatively  6.Qb3  might also offer us a small edge. }
6... Qxf5 { This is not the natural way to recapture! } 7. O-O
{ Getting the king to safety and preparing d4 next. } 7... Nf6 8. d4
{ Before Black can achieve d5! } 8... Be7
{ Keeping the e-file safe.   Note that  8...e4  will be met with  9.Nh4!  Qg4  10.Qxg4  Bxg4  11.Bg5  . }
9. Nbd2
{ The knight joins the party, and Black is struggling with his king stuck in the center due to our powerful bishop stopping him from castling! }
9... d5
{ Either it was this or e4, Black didn't have much choice :@@EndBracket@@! }
10. dxe5
{ Once again, we have to play very energetically to prove our superiority in development. }
10... dxc4
{ The alternative with  10...Nxe5  gives an easy advantage after  11.Bb3  . }
11. exf6 Bxf6 12. Re1+
{ Black's issue will always be his king on e8 :@@EndBracket@@. } 12... Be6 13.
Qe2
{ And here Black's best move is Kd7. You know things aren't going well when your best move is moving the king to the center of the board :@@EndBracket@@! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) 1.e4 e5 2nd & 3rd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "2...Nc6 3.Bc4 d6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... e5
{ To date, this is one of the most solid responses intended to put an end to our attacking ambitions! Black wants to copy our central pawn push and wants to believe that it is enough to neutralize our first move advantage. If you are looking for a cool repertoire with 1...e5 from the Black side, I would recommend Sethuraman's 1...e5 Lifetime Repertoires which is definitely one of the best LTR out there and raised the standard of opening theory forever! }
2. Nf3
{ We begin the fight for the center, developing our knight and increasing the influence over e5, d4, g5, and h4-squares. }
2... Nc6
{ Protecting the things which are important... like the e5-pawn :@@EndBracket@@. Petroff players will never understand this feeling :@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Bc4
{ The Italian game is one of the biggest revelations of the 21st century as it saw itself rise in popularity, giving a tough fight to the undisputed mainline, which is Ruy Lopez with 3.Bb5. I am more fond of this line since I have pleasant memories of winning many games, sometimes ending the game with a mating attack, and occasionally torturing my opponents in a positional game.It is the perfect opening for both dynamic and positional players as I feel 'The opening doesn't define who you want to be!'. I would also like to quote the best saying ever said about the Italian 'Everyone pretends to understand the subtleties of the Italian game, but nobody really does!'- MVL. }
3... d6
{ This tame move is very interesting and could lead to very fresh positions. It is rising in popularity thanks to many GMs adopting it for shorter time controls. }
4. c3
{ I feel this is the best attempt for advantage. I spent some time analyzing Anish's  4.O-O  eventually transposing to lines from @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Be7  ,  I wasn't happy with a mere transposition! Black is violating the very concept of 'Space and time' by making a passive pawn move before developing his knight or Bishop, hence I feel the punishment should be more severe!Of course, this meant I had to break my head to find the exact way to do it, but it was worth the time spent! We are preparing d4 and also the sneaky Qb3 attacking f7 :@@EndBracket@@. }
4... f5
{ Black reveals his main idea behind the primitive 3rd move. He wants to fight for the kingside initiative with this pawn break.   4...Bg4  Surprisingly this is the most popular move, but it just blunders a pawn!  5.Qb3  with a nice double attack on f7 and b7 winning a pawn with advantage.   4...Nf6  is also horrible  5.Ng5  with an  advantage as the f7-pawn is in big trouble. }
5. d3
{ Since the fight is for the control of the light squares, this makes more sense. Alternatively  5.exf5  might offer good chances for the advantage. }
5... Qf6 6. exf5
{ Asking Black to choose between three options - Bxf5, Qxf5, and Nge7.   Alternatively  6.Qb3  might also offer us a small edge. }
6... Nge7
{ Black is making preparations to win back the f5-pawn under favorable circumstances.   6...Bxf5  is a big blunder and gives us a big advantage.  7.Qb3  with a winning double attack on b7 and g8. }
7. O-O d5 { Other moves will allow us to break the center with d4. } 8. Bb5
{ Followed by Re1 with cool pressure on the e5-pawn leading to our advantage. Black's development problems continue to be a pain. }
