{ Retreating the bishop before it might be exchanged to the d7-knight after Nb6. I don't think Black can equalize anymore! }
8... Nb8
{ A very deep maneuver of the knight to help it gain control of the d4-square from the more active location on c6. On d7 it was just a misplaced piece and it is fine to spend two tempi to improve the knight's power since the position is closed. }
9. O-O { A natural move deviating from  9.Be3  which was played in 2021. } 9...
Bd7
{ A necessary exchange to prepare Nc6.   9...Nc6  would be a big mistake.  10.Bxc6  Getting rid of the knight to prepare our next move.  10...bxc6  11.e5!  Opening the position favorably with a structural advantage and we have the jumping knights compared to the bishop pair as they will be more powerful in closed positions. }
10. Rb1
{ Followed by a3-b4 with a decent play on the queenside, our position is more comfortable due to the better control of the light-squares and space control. }
