{ The Sicilian Defense: The answer for all the living beings who aren't satisfied with just equalizing and want to fight for the full point against any form of opposition! }
2. Nf3
{ Although I have had my fair share of fun with the Alapin and the Closed Sicilian with 2. Nc3...When I want to decimate my opponents this is the move I resort to! }
2... d6
{ The most popular move outlasting the other alternatives by a huge margin. Black gives the invitation to enter the complex lines of Najdorf, Classical, Scheveningen, and the last but not the least - Dragon. }
3. Bb5+
{ Before you completely lose interest in my course and reject it, just hear me out :@@EndBracket@@! My entire life I have been playing 3.d4 and was never a big fan of the Moscow system from both sides. I would hate it when people play it against me from White, but that didn't stop me from gaining a good score from Black as I put a lot of effort into making creative lines work and surprising opponents!Slowly but surely I realized that there were not many lines where Black can hope to equalize and he is forced into a rigid path where he has to memorize very precise lines to neutralize White's initiative. Trying to get 0.00 by playing accurate chess is not what Black players envisioned when they choose to play the Sicilian Defense! If they want to equalize with Black, I would say that 1...e5 is the way to do it as it is very solid and reliable with many good lines to choose from, like the Petroff and the Berlin!Now moving on to the main point of why I recommend the Moscow system... Our play is very straightforward with so many interesting systems to choose from! Black has only three main options and I will try to break it down as simply as possible.A@@EndBracket@@ Bd7 - The most solid and also boring :@@EndBracket@@. I think we can achieve a concrete advantage against the best play from the Black side. I found a novel direction that hasn't been tested heavily and I couldn't equalize from the Black side. I noticed that both Anish Giri and Shankland have missed this direction in their Lifetime Repertoires.B@@EndBracket@@ Nd7 - This is the most ambitious attempt to play for a fighting game. Once again I found an interesting way missed by my lord Mr. Najdorf- Anish Giri. Frankly, it is a pain to play this line from Black as there are many move order deviations with people messing it up from time to time @@StartBracket@@including myself@@EndBracket@@ , not understanding the subtleties of each move order. With my direction, I feel we can gain the advantage by force! Trust me, I was as surprised as you!C@@EndBracket@@ Nc6 - I was a big fan of this line as it was suggested to me by my 'Uncle' Lev Psakhis, playing it to confuse opponents during my childhood! But unfortunately, those dreamy days are over and now I have to accept the reality that it is just a bad line leading to a better position... if white knows what he is doing. I am very happy with my find as I feel it is the right way to play for the advantage, but for some reason not very popular! }
3... Nc6
{ This has been played by both Magnus Carlsen and Garry Kasparov in classical time control, so it might be a decent surprise to catch an unsuspecting opponent. That being said, I don't think it works under the objective scrutiny of modern computers. }
4. O-O { Getting our king to safety before implementing our strategy. } 4...
Bd7
{ Black stops the wrecking of the pawn structure with Bxc6.   4...Nf6  5.Re1  Bd7  will transpose to 4...Bd7 lines. }
5. Re1
{ Making sure that the bishop on b5 has a safe place on f1 after the eventual a6 from Black. }
5... Nf6 6. h3
{ This second most popular move feels like a better attempt to fight for the advantage. We put a stop to Bg4 ideas and only then proceed to prepare c3-d4 to capture the center. }
6... Qb6 { A funny queen move to annoy our bishop. } 7. a4
{ Supporting the bishop and involving the a1-rook in the game. } 7... a6
{ Forcing us to give us the bishop or retreat to f1.   7...e6  8.c3  Preparing d4 with a strong center and moves like a6 can be met with Bf1 followed by d4. }
8. Bxc6 { Giving up the bishop pair to keep the momentum of the initiative. }
8... Bxc6 9. d3
{ Protecting our e4-pawn dulling Black's light-squared bishop. } 9... e6
{ Black prepares to finish his kingside development with Be7 followed by O-O. }
10. c4
{ Continuing our Maroczy concept even in this line :@@EndBracket@@. The pawns on a4, c4, d3, and e4 seriously restrict the power of the bishop on c6 making sure that the bishop pair doesn't have any merit in this closed position. }
10... Be7 11. Nc3 O-O
{ Black has done everything right, but unfortunately for him... it is not sufficient to equalize due to the lack of space/active plans. }
12. d4 { After dominating the bishop on c6, finally we open the game. } 12...
cxd4 13. Nxd4
{ We have the edge thanks to the space advantage, Black will find it hard to find some play in this position. We can also reinforce our Maroczy bind with b3 next making sure that Black won't have targets. }
*

