Bd7
{ Black stops the wrecking of the pawn structure with Bxc6.   4...Nf6  5.Re1  Bd7  will transpose to 4...Bd7 lines. }
5. Re1
{ Making sure that the bishop on b5 has a safe place on f1 after the eventual a6 from Black. }
5... Nf6 6. h3
{ This second most popular move feels like a better attempt to fight for the advantage. We put a stop to Bg4 ideas and only then proceed to prepare c3-d4 to capture the center. }
6... Ne5 { Simplying the position with some exchanges. } 7. Nxe5 Bxb5
{ Black is happy to get the bishop pair, though it won't matter so much due to his poor development.   7...dxe5  8.a4!  followed by Na3-c4 ideas with the advantage due to the better pawn structure and doubled pawns on the e-file. }
8. a4
{ A lovely move keeping the initiative and forcing the bishop to a passive place. }
8... Ba6
{ The only way to retain the bishop.   8...Bd7  9.Nxd7  Qxd7  The alternative recapture with the knight will also lead to the same concept.  10.d4!  Capturing the center with a solid space advantage.   8...Bxa4  Trying to win a pawn due to the attacked knight on e5.  9.Nxf7!  Two can play at this game.  9...Kxf7  10.Rxa4  with a big advantage due to the weakened king on f7. }
9. Nf3 { Preparing to open the position advantageously with d4. } 9... e5
{ Otherwise we just capture the center with d4. } 10. d3
{ The bishop on a6 looks sad after this move. } 10... Be7 11. Nh4
{ An annoying move that gives us the advantage as it forces Black to weaken his kingside with g6 or allow the knight to f5. }
