7. Bf1
{ A cool retreat avoiding any pitfalls involving the loose bishop on b5. } 7...
Be7 8. c3 { The typical preparation for achieving a strong center with d4. }
8... O-O 9. d4 { Black's situation looks unenviable. } 9... d5
{ Black hopes to exchange a pair of knights to reduce the tension. } 10. e5
{ Our strong center gives us easy play and the opportunity to create some play in the kingside using the pawn hook on e5. }
10... Ne4 { Given the time, Black can prepare f6 next. } 11. Nbd2
{ Of course we are not going to tolerate the strong knight on e4. } 11... cxd4
12. cxd4
{ This looked simplest though  12.Nxe4  is a tempting alternative worth mentioning. }
12... Nxd2 13. Bxd2
{ We have the advantage thanks to the stable center which can be easily protected with Bc3. We can bring the f1-bishop to d3 and the rook to e3 to prepare some play on the kingside. }
