{ A necessary exchange to gain a tempo later on. } 9... Bxe4 10. Re1
{ This move screaming to be played to target the weak king on e8. } 10... Bf5
{ Trying to hold on to the mighty bishop pair. } 11. Bg5
{ The most annoying location where it puts pressure on Black's main vulnerable spot - the e7-pawn. }
11... Qb6 12. Qd2 { Connecting the rooks and improving the queen's position. }
12... h6 { Other moves are bad and don't bring any relief to Black. } 13. Bf6
{ The bishop looks stunning on f6 getting on the nerves of the Black king. }
13... Rg8 { The safe place for the rook, on h7 it would be misplaced. } 14. d5
{ We have very strong compensation for the pawn thanks to the pressure along the e-file. }
14... g5
{ Black was running out of useful moves to make :@@EndBracket@@ due to the monstrous bishop on f6. Moves like Kd7 can be met with Bc3 followed by Qf4 and g4 going after the bishop on f5. }
15. Re3 { Time to bring in the reserve rook to the e-file. } 15... O-O-O
{ Black is better off giving back the pawn and trying to hold on in the following slightly inferior position. }
16. Bxe7 Bxe7 17. Rxe7
{ Restoring the material balance and keeping a slight edge due to the control of the e-file and the superior combo of Q+N vs Q+B. }
