4... Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ This has the stamp of approval as the best line for Black.   5...Nc6  will transpose to 4...Nc6 lines.   5...a6  6.Bxd7+  Nbxd7  7.O-O  will transpose to 4...a6 lines. }
6. Bxd7+
{ The right time to take on d7 and then choose our plans depending on how Black will recapture the bishop. }
6... Nbxd7 7. d3
{ I prefer this restrained approach playing aiming for positional torture instead of opening the game with d4. }
7... Bg7
{ The bishop is looking very pretty on the long diagonal despite lacking a useful objective on it :@@EndBracket@@. }
8. h3
{ A satisfying prophylactic move stopping Ng4-e5 ideas which might help Black in achieving control over the d4-square. }
8... O-O 9. Be3
{ I noticed that in this line, we delay castling many times to achieve more important positional goals. }
9... Nb8
{ A typical maneuver improving the knight's location to a place where it will control the central squares. }
10. d4
{ I think it was necessary to break in the center before Black can fully control the square as we can see that the last few moves like h3 @@StartBracket@@preventing Ng4 ideas@@EndBracket@@ and Be3  @@StartBracket@@increasing control over d4@@EndBracket@@ were all slowly preparing this d4 move! }
10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nc6 { Black has to prepare either the b5 or d5 break. } 12.
Rc1
{ Delaying castling for one last move to prevent any future problems from Black by targetting our c4-pawn. We have a slight space advantage and Black needs to find a way to neutralize our superiority in the center. }
