[Round "?"]
[White "4) The Moscow Variation 3.Bb5+"]
[Black "3...Bd7 4.c4 Nf6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense: The answer for all the living beings who aren't satisfied with just equalizing and want to fight for the full point against any form of opposition! }
2. Nf3
{ Although I have had my fair share of fun with the Alapin and the Closed Sicilian with 2. Nc3...When I want to decimate my opponents this is the move I resort to! }
2... d6
{ The most popular move outlasting the other alternatives by a huge margin. Black gives the invitation to enter the complex lines of Najdorf, Classical, Scheveningen, and the last but not the least - Dragon. }
3. Bb5+
{ Before you completely lose interest in my course and reject it, just hear me out :@@EndBracket@@! My entire life I have been playing 3.d4 and was never a big fan of the Moscow system from both sides. I would hate it when people play it against me from White, but that didn't stop me from gaining a good score from Black as I put a lot of effort into making creative lines work and surprising opponents!Slowly but surely I realized that there were not many lines where Black can hope to equalize and he is forced into a rigid path where he has to memorize very precise lines to neutralize White's initiative. Trying to get 0.00 by playing accurate chess is not what Black players envisioned when they choose to play the Sicilian Defense! If they want to equalize with Black, I would say that 1...e5 is the way to do it as it is very solid and reliable with many good lines to choose from, like the Petroff and the Berlin!Now moving on to the main point of why I recommend the Moscow system... Our play is very straightforward with so many interesting systems to choose from! Black has only three main options and I will try to break it down as simply as possible.A@@EndBracket@@ Bd7 - The most solid and also boring :@@EndBracket@@. I think we can achieve a concrete advantage against the best play from the Black side. I found a novel direction that hasn't been tested heavily and I couldn't equalize from the Black side. I noticed that both Anish Giri and Shankland have missed this direction in their Lifetime Repertoires.B@@EndBracket@@ Nd7 - This is the most ambitious attempt to play for a fighting game. Once again I found an interesting way missed by my lord Mr. Najdorf- Anish Giri. Frankly, it is a pain to play this line from Black as there are many move order deviations with people messing it up from time to time @@StartBracket@@including myself@@EndBracket@@ , not understanding the subtleties of each move order. With my direction, I feel we can gain the advantage by force! Trust me, I was as surprised as you!C@@EndBracket@@ Nc6 - I was a big fan of this line as it was suggested to me by my 'Uncle' Lev Psakhis, playing it to confuse opponents during my childhood! But unfortunately, those dreamy days are over and now I have to accept the reality that it is just a bad line leading to a better position... if white knows what he is doing. I am very happy with my find as I feel it is the right way to play for the advantage, but for some reason not very popular! }
3... Bd7
{ Black is ready to accept a slightly worse position with the hope that one day that he will be able to equalize by preparing the d5 or b5 break. }
4. c4
{ Changing the character of the game. Surprisingly this move is not so well researched compared to the mainline with 4.Bxd7+. As a former Bogo-Indian player I do have a soft spot for lines involving the existence of a pawn on the 5th rank as it severely restricts his pieces and a strong pawn ready to become a queen in just three steps :@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ This has the stamp of approval as the best line for Black.   5...Nc6  will transpose to 4...Nc6 lines.   5...a6  6.Bxd7+  Nbxd7  7.O-O  will transpose to 4...a6 lines. }
6. Bxd7+
{ The right time to take on d7 and then choose our plans depending on how Black will recapture the bishop. }
6... Qxd7
{ In the fianchetto systems, it is better to recapture with the queen to develop the b8-knight to c6 fighting for the central square on d4. }
7. d4 { Just in time before Black can play Nc6 stopping our main concept. }
7... cxd4 8. Qxd4
{ This has been featured in 8 games, while the mainline with Nxd4 has been played in more than 1100 games! The knight on f3 is quite decently placed, so why not improve the activity of the queen? The queen always has a nice retreat square on d3 where it keeps an eye on both the e4 and c4 pawns. }
8... Nc6 { Avoiding some options for us. } 9. Qd3
{ The best place for the queen where it protects the c4 and e4 pawn. } 9... Bg7
10. O-O Ng4 { To be followed by f5 ideas gaining some play on the kingside. }
11. b3 f5
{ Black fights for the initiative with this typical, but slightly weakening break.   11...O-O  This feels natural.  12.Bb2  We have the superior space advantage which gives us straightforward play using the semi-open e- and d-files. }
12. Bd2
{ This seems like a good place to keep the bishop where it won't get in the way of our coordination. }
12... O-O
{ Black would like to do something using the f-file, but we are too solid for something like that to work!   12...Nge5  13.Nxe5  dxe5  This doesn't make a good impression doubling the pawns, but it is a necessary evil as Black is worse after  13...Nxe5  14.Qe2  .  14.Qxd7+  Kxd7  15.Rad1  with the endgame advantage due to the queenside majority and the passive bishop on g7 who lacks a good future. }
13. h3 { Provoking the following knight exchange. } 13... Nge5
{ 13...fxe4  14.Qxe4  is just bad for Black with no compensation for our space advantage and loose pawn structure on d6/e7. }
14. Nxe5 Nxe5
{ 14...Bxe5  15.f4!  Gaining more control over the kingside.  15...Bd4+  16.Kh1  followed by Rae1 with a solid advantage due to the slightly weakened king on g8 and better space control for us. }
15. Qg3
{ Black's temporary activity has been neutralized leaving our positional trumps like space advantage, a potential outpost on d5 for the knight, and last but not the least - safer king in our favor. We can continue with Rad1-Rfe1 with a play on the d- and e-files. }
*

