{ The only place where the bishop can't be attacked with a discovered attack using the battery along the h8-a1 diagonal. Alternatively  11.Bxf6  Bxf6  12.Qe3  Bg7  13.Rad1  followed by b3 and Nd5 might also offer a decent edge. }
11... Rc8
{ Retaining ideas involving a different pathway for the b8-knight with Na6-c5. }
12. b3 { Overprotecting our dear pawn on c4. } 12... a6
{ Black has to play actively to fight against our space domination. } 13. Rac1
{ Forecasting the future opening of the c-file. } 13... b5
{ When you say A... } 14. Nd5
{ A fantastic intermezzo threatening the lethal Nb6 triple fork. } 14... Nxd5
{ Black is forced to get rid of our mighty knight on d5. } 15. Qxd5 Ra7
{ A novel rook maneuver to prepare Rac7 to increase the intensity on the c-file.   15...Nc6  16.Rc2  followed by Rfc1 with strong pressure along the c-file and we will eventually end up with the queenside majority which will assure us the advantage. }
16. cxb5
{ In my last course one guy commented that he wouldn't want to play an endgame against a higher rated player...So I decided to keep this as an alternative :@@EndBracket@@. }
16... Rxc1
{ Taking on b5 with the pawn would lose to Rxc8 followed by Qxb5 with a winning advantage due to Rc1 next. }
17. Rxc1 { We have won the fight for the control of the c-file. } 17... axb5
{ Black's last two moves were forced. } 18. Rc2
{ Protecting our precious a2-pawn. } 18... Na6
{ Black will activate his knight via c7-e6. } 19. h4
{ With a messy late middlegame due to the outside passer on the queenside. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Sicilian 2…Nc6 3.Bc4 Jorden's Italian Gambit"]
[Black "3...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense: The answer for all the living beings who aren't satisfied with just equalizing and want to fight for the full point against any form of opposition! }
2. Nf3
{ Although I have had my fair share of fun with the Alapin and the Closed Sicilian with  2.Nc3  , when I want to decimate my opponents, this is the move I resort to! }
2... Nc6
{ This was always the respected choice for many years, but I feel it remained a very dangerous weapon in the hands of Magnus Carlsen who was practically unstoppable with it during his fantastic 2019 run where he was using this exclusively and went on to beat everyone who stood in his path! }
3. Bc4
{ Sometimes, it's not a bad idea to be very stubborn in our opening principles :@@EndBracket@@. To be honest, my original plan was to cover the mainlines arising from 3.d4 which gives Black a huge variety of options to choose from like the Sveshnikov/Pelikan, Taimanov, Accelerated Dragon, Paulsen/ Kan, Four Horsemen, and many other lines.I was inspired by this fantastic invention of Jorden who managed to win in great style against Prag in the Tata Steel Masters 2022, that I have decided to keep it as my main recommendation. It has the surprise value since it is fresh and unexplored while at the same time leads to very interesting play where the better-prepared player will have the edge!I can tell you that this will remain a wonderful surprise weapon, and black players will have to find things out on their own without the use of any existing Chessable course or books! I'm glad we can develop our bishop to c4 regardless of our opponent's opening choice! The best part about this line is that finding a clear equalizer for Black was difficult! In a classical game against Antipov in 2017, Fedoseev was the first super grandmaster to employ this line. }
3... Nf6
{ Play takes a challenging stance after this direct attempt at provocation by Black. }
4. e5
{ Never back down!! We are fearless people after all :@@EndBracket@@, no need for another invitation to engage in a tactical skirmish! }
4... d5
{ A nice shot, though this allows us to gain the better pawn structure with easy targets for our minor pieces. }
5. Bb5 { Black can say goodbye to his stable pawn structure. } 5... Nd7
{ Other knight retreats are worse. } 6. Bxc6
{ Not giving another chance for Black to save his pawn structure. } 6... bxc6
7. d3
{ The structures are very similar to positions arising from the Rossolimo, but the fact that Black has committed with d5 works in our favor as it is going to be difficult to defend the c5-pawn, which can be targetted by b3-Ba3 and Nc3-a4. This is already fresh territory with no games. }
7... e6 8. Qe2
{ We must delay castling to avoid giving Black any evil kingside attacking ideas like Be7-g5 or even Rg8-g5! This is a useful move controlling the c4-square and overprotecting our guy on e5. }
8... Be7 { Black is getting ready for g5. } 9. Nbd2
{ Continuing to play the cat & mouse game and not defining the king's final location. }
9... g5 10. h3
{ Putting an end to the g4 plan, in case Black does want to prepare it in the future, he can't do it without the permission of our h1-rook, who will get activated via the h-file. Once the tactical ideas are stopped, Black's strategic problems with the doubled c-pawns shall remain, giving us the advantage, and it will be ideal for us to castle on the queenside. Our queenside development can be finished via b3-Bb2. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Sicilian 2…Nc6 3.Bc4 Jorden's Italian Gambit"]
[Black "3...Nf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense: The answer for all the living beings who aren't satisfied with just equalizing and want to fight for the full point against any form of opposition! }
2. Nf3
{ Although I have had my fair share of fun with the Alapin and the Closed Sicilian with  2.Nc3  , when I want to decimate my opponents, this is the move I resort to! }
2... Nc6
{ This was always the respected choice for many years, but I feel it remained a very dangerous weapon in the hands of Magnus Carlsen who was practically unstoppable with it during his fantastic 2019 run where he was using this exclusively and went on to beat everyone who stood in his path! }
3. Bc4
{ Sometimes, it's not a bad idea to be very stubborn in our opening principles :@@EndBracket@@. To be honest, my original plan was to cover the mainlines arising from 3.d4 which gives Black a huge variety of options to choose from like the Sveshnikov/Pelikan, Taimanov, Accelerated Dragon, Paulsen/ Kan, Four Horsemen, and many other lines.I was inspired by this fantastic invention of Jorden who managed to win in great style against Prag in the Tata Steel Masters 2022, that I have decided to keep it as my main recommendation. It has the surprise value since it is fresh and unexplored while at the same time leads to very interesting play where the better-prepared player will have the edge!I can tell you that this will remain a wonderful surprise weapon, and black players will have to find things out on their own without the use of any existing Chessable course or books! I'm glad we can develop our bishop to c4 regardless of our opponent's opening choice! The best part about this line is that finding a clear equalizer for Black was difficult! In a classical game against Antipov in 2017, Fedoseev was the first super grandmaster to employ this line. }
3... Nf6
{ Play takes a challenging stance after this direct attempt at provocation by Black. }
4. e5
{ Never back down!! We are fearless people after all :@@EndBracket@@, no need for another invitation to engage in a tactical skirmish! }
4... Ng4
{ Black's main argument remains that we are not fully equipped to support the lonely advance of the e-pawn. }
5. Qe2
{ Protecting our main guy on e5 and asking Black to choose his next plan of attack. }
5... Qc7
{ This looks very natural attacking the e5-pawn, which can't be protected by us anymore. }
6. Bxf7+ { Thanks to this tactical trick, we can retain our initiative. } 6...
Kxf7 7. Qc4+ { Winning back the piece. } 7... Ke8
{ Playing e6 would end up losing a pawn as he can't take back on e5 after Qxg4 due to Qf4+. }
8. Qxg4 Nxe5
{ Hurrying to win the pawn could be counter-productive as it gives a big advantage to us. }
9. Qh5+ { Forcing the knight to retreat passively. } 9... Nf7
{ Another retreat to g6 can be calmly met with d3 with a huge advantage due to future Ng5 ideas. }
10. Nc3
{ Developing the knight and threatening to jump to d5/b5 in the future. } 10...
g6 11. Qh4
{ The best place for the queen where it keeps an eye on the e7-pawn and let's not forget that Black has already lost his castling rights :@@EndBracket@@. }
11... b5 12. Nxb5
{ After comparing many options, I realized that if we want the undisputed advantage... we have to take the pawn and survive the onslaught. }
12... Qc6
{ The queen looks nice on this square keeping watch over the long diagonal. }
13. Nc3 { Black needs to act fast to compensate for the missing pawn. } 13...
g5
{ This is Black's best chance to open up the position for the utilization of the bishop pair.   13...Bg7  14.d3  Black doesn't have enough compensation for the pawn. }
14. Qg3 h5 { Black has to continue in the same  energetic fashion! } 15. Nxg5
{ And we are continuing in the same greedy manner :@@EndBracket@@. } 15... h4
{ Black doesn't have any option and has to follow a long sequence. } 16. Qf4
{ The threat on f7 doesn't give Black the time to take on g2. } 16... Nxg5 17.
Qxg5 h3 { The culmination of Black's aggressive concept. } 18. Rg1
{ Breaking the pin and getting for the endgame. } 18... hxg2 19. Qxg2
{ Although Rxg2 is a decent option, I think it is better to exchange the queens and steer the game towards the endgame where it will be easier to convert the extra pawn. }
19... Qxg2 20. Rxg2 Bb7
{ The bishop is looking mighty on the long diagonal, though it can hardly bother us in any way. }
21. Rg1 { Keeping control over the 8th rank. } 21... Rxh2 22. d3
{ Followed by Be3 and O-O-O with a clear advantage due to the extra pawn. Moves like d5 would allow Bf4 to control the e5-square. }
*

