3... d6
{ The second most popular move preventing e5 ideas and preparing Nf6 under safer conditions. }
4. O-O
{ Our main concept in this line is to achieve c3-d4 and Re1, if we can achieve we can boast of a slight advantage. }
4... Nf6
{ A key move attacking e4-pawn before continuing to formalize the development scheme of the f8-bishop. }
5. Re1 g6
{ In the current position, the fianchetto of the dark-squared bishop might be the most challenging solution for Black.   5...e6  transposes to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  lines. }
6. c3 { d4 is coming! } 6... Bg7
{ Black is getting ready for Nxe4 which might end in a favorable knight for the bishop trade.   6...Nxe4  looks tempting but runs into a concrete refutation.  7.Qb3!  The dual-threat of Bxf7 and Rxe4 makes this position hopeless for Black. }
7. Bb3 { Aimed against Ne4/d5 ideas that will break our beautiful center. }
7... O-O 8. h3
{ The last prophylactic measure before d4, since direct capture of center with 8.d4 would allow Black good play against our pawns thanks to Bg4 using the pin along the h5-d1 diagonal to put pressure on d4. }
8... e5
{ Black stops it manually, but this does permanently weaken the d5-square. } 9.
d3
{ Changing our strategy, the idea is to continue with Be3-Nbd2 followed by a4 with nice pressure on the queenside, and we can prepare d4 at our leisure.   It is imperative to note that the direct  9.d4  allows Black to equalize.  9...cxd4  10.cxd4  exd4  11.Nxd4  Nxd4  12.Qxd4  Be6  with equal play thanks to the simplifications. }
