{ This was always the respected choice for many years, but I feel it remained a very dangerous weapon in the hands of Magnus Carlsen who was practically unstoppable with it during his fantastic 2019 run where he was using this exclusively and went on to beat everyone who stood in his path! }
3. Bc4
{ Sometimes, it's not a bad idea to be very stubborn in our opening principles :@@EndBracket@@. To be honest, my original plan was to cover the mainlines arising from 3.d4 which gives Black a huge variety of options to choose from like the Sveshnikov/Pelikan, Taimanov, Accelerated Dragon, Paulsen/ Kan, Four Horsemen, and many other lines.I was inspired by this fantastic invention of Jorden who managed to win in great style against Prag in the Tata Steel Masters 2022, that I have decided to keep it as my main recommendation. It has the surprise value since it is fresh and unexplored while at the same time leads to very interesting play where the better-prepared player will have the edge!I can tell you that this will remain a wonderful surprise weapon, and black players will have to find things out on their own without the use of any existing Chessable course or books! I'm glad we can develop our bishop to c4 regardless of our opponent's opening choice! The best part about this line is that finding a clear equalizer for Black was difficult! In a classical game against Antipov in 2017, Fedoseev was the first super grandmaster to employ this line. }
3... e6
{ Black is preparing a quick d5 to punish and utilize our early bishop sortie. }
4. O-O a6
{ This is the most popular move trying to bully our light-squared bishop with b5. }
5. d4 { Getting the center. } 5... d5
{ Black's best bet for trying to equalize the situation.   5...b5  is just bad, but it is worth knowing how to deal with it.  6.d5!  Crashing through in the center, leading to a depressing position where the poor development of Black will be deciding factor that guarantees our advantage. }
6. exd5 exd5
{ The position is similar to the French Tarrasch version. I wouldn't be pleased with such a change in openings as a full-fledged Sicilian player! After all, I could play 1...e6 instead of 1...c5 if I wanted to play French! }
7. Re1+
{ Using the time to deliver a check and prepare the retreat of the light-squared bishop to f1. }
7... Be7 8. Bf1
{ The bishop will be safe here and can come back to the game when the time is right and after the dust has settled in the center. }
8... cxd4 9. Nxd4
{ A better pawn structure is sometimes enough to win the game! I think studying Karpov's games might be a useful way to master playing such positions, he is very ruthless in executing White's plan to perfection, while at the same time stopping Black from getting any form of counterplay. }
9... Nf6
{ Black's main hope lies in creating an active play using the isolated pawn on d5. }
10. Be3
{ Overprotecting the blockading piece on d4. This is an essential part of the Isolani strategy. }
10... O-O 11. h3
{ Stopping Ng4 ideas and preparing to stabilize our blockade on d4 with Nd2 and N2f3 with full control over the position.I will just repeat Nimzowitsch's saying about Isolani pawns; 'Control, blockade, and destroy!' We have already done the first two and I will believe that the readers will do the final one: Destroy!! }
*

