3... e6
{ Black is preparing a quick d5 to punish and utilize our early bishop sortie. }
4. O-O Nf6 { Black is trying to provoke us into playing e5. } 5. Re1
{ The most natural move, developing the rook and fighting against Black's d5-break. I feel this is more challenging than  5.d3  . }
5... d6
{ Black is playing very cautiously and hopes he will be in time to equalize. }
6. Bb5 { An important move gaining a tempo targetting the c6-knight. } 6... Bd7
{ Black can't allow both Bxc6+ and e5 ideas which would permanently ruin his pawn structure. }
7. c3
{ The typical Ruy Lopez style move preparing d4 getting the center rolling. }
7... Be7
{ Black gives up the fight for the center and confines himself to finishing his development. }
8. d4
{ I think this is a dream for any White player and a nightmare for Sicilian players as his position resembles a horrible edition of the Ruy Lopez. }
8... cxd4
{ Black could also maintain the tension, but it is not going to change matters much as we can continue with Bf1, Nbd2 with good play in the center and kingside. }
9. cxd4 O-O 10. Nc3
{ is ideal for us because we have the center with good attacking opportunities on the kingside once we prepare e5. }
