Bf4
{ Occupying the strongest diagonal where the bishop cuts into many key squares in Black's camp. }
10... cxd4
{ So far we have been following @@StartBracket@@Cruz-Demuth 2018@@EndBracket@@ and here White missed the chance to gain a substantial advantage with the most natural move.   10...O-O  11.d5  Looks very nasty for Black as our pieces are brimming with explosive energy. }
11. Nxd4 f5
{ We shouldn't be scared of this distracting move which wins an exchange, as we can't protect the d4-knight and also keep the rook. }
12. Nxc6
{ An exchange sacrifice in the spirit of Petrosian who is known for his famous positional sacrifices. }
12... Qxd1+ 13. Rxd1 fxe4
{ The fact that the black king is in the center offers more than enough compensation for the rook. }
14. Nxe7
{ Getting rid of the last enemy for our f4-bishop, after this exchange nobody can oppose our mighty dark-squared bishop! }
14... Kxe7 15. Nxe4
{ All of our minor pieces are superior to their counterparts. } 15... e5
{ An important pawn sacrifice without which Black would be seriously worse due to the 'Dark clouds' gathering over the king.   15...h6  Stopping  Bg5+  16.Bd6+!  Forcing the king to f7.  16...Kf7  17.Be5!  With the idea of continuing with Rd3 next followed by Rf3+, and Black will be in big trouble as he is helpless against the attack on the dark-squares. }
16. Bxe5
{ The bishop looks strong in the center of the board, and I feel that it is worth more than a rook, as it can't be challenged! }
