3. Bc4
{ Sometimes, it's not a bad idea to be very stubborn in our opening principles :@@EndBracket@@. To be honest, my original plan was to cover the mainlines arising from 3.d4 which gives Black a huge variety of options to choose from like the Sveshnikov/Pelikan, Taimanov, Accelerated Dragon, Paulsen/ Kan, Four Horsemen, and many other lines.I was inspired by this fantastic invention of Jorden who managed to win in great style against Prag in the Tata Steel Masters 2022, that I have decided to keep it as my main recommendation. It has the surprise value since it is fresh and unexplored while at the same time leads to very interesting play where the better-prepared player will have the edge!I can tell you that this will remain a wonderful surprise weapon, and black players will have to find things out on their own without the use of any existing Chessable course or books! I'm glad we can develop our bishop to c4 regardless of our opponent's opening choice! The best part about this line is that finding a clear equalizer for Black was difficult! In a classical game against Antipov in 2017, Fedoseev was the first super grandmaster to employ this line. }
3... e6
{ Black is preparing a quick d5 to punish and utilize our early bishop sortie. }
4. O-O d5 5. Bb5
{ This was the brainwave of Jorden! I think this is the move that has high rewards in a practical game as Black needs to be very precise to defend against our threats. }
5... dxe4
{ The greedy approach is Black's best chance to neutralize our initiative. } 6.
Ne5 { The most fighting move starting the assault on Black's position. } 6...
Ne7 { This is Black's second-best way to protect the c6-point. } 7. Bxc6+
{ We don't need the bishop anymore while we might want to keep the knight on e5 in case Black gets ambitious with bxc6. Additionally, Nxc6 allows Black to get a crucial tempo with bxc6 attacking our bishop on b5. }
7... Nxc6 8. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Black's bishop pair is compensated by his ridiculous pawn structure.   8...Qc7  Trying to keep the structure intact :@@EndBracket@@.  9.Nxa7!  A nice trick to win a pawn.  9...Rxa7  10.Nc3  We will win the e4-pawn leading to a position with an extra pawn. Black can't protect the pawn with f5 as it would seriously weaken his position and his king is still in the center. }
9. Re1
{ A very tricky move provoking Black into defending the e4-pawn with f5. } 9...
Bd6
{ Black has to give up the center pawn and will have to rely on his bishop pair to create a play on the kingside.   9...f5  is very greedy and wrong.  10.d3!  Crashing through with his pawn sacrifice, leading to a big advantage due to Black's horrible development and weak king. }
10. Nc3
{ If we can take on e4 with the knight, we can boast of a slight pull due to the weak c5-pawn which can't be protected so easily. }
10... Qc7 { Attacking the h2-pawn and trying to distract us. } 11. Qh5
{ I like this move which provokes Black into weakening his kingside. } 11... g6
{ It is never a good sign for Black, when he is forced to commit this weakening. }
12. Qh6
{ Black has a difficult choice here, either he has to give up the e4-pawn or play f5 weakening his position further which will allow us to open the position powerfully with d3. }
