{ Black needs to tread carefully as he has given preference to material grabbing over piece development. }
10... Bd6
{ Black bishop retreats to his origin location.   A@@EndBracket@@  10...Nf6  is bad as we can get a huge advantage by trapping the bishop.  11.g3  The bishop on  h2  meets a similar like from the famous Spassky-Fischer game :@@EndBracket@@.  11...Bxg3  12.fxg3  Qxg3  13.Qe2  Preventing the perpetual check and assuring a big advantage since the pieces will have their say.   B@@EndBracket@@  10...Bf4  gives an extra tempo for free.  11.g3  with good chances to gain some pull and attacking chances.   C@@EndBracket@@  10...h5  It is important that we shouldn't be greedy and try to win the poisoned bishop.  11.Nxe4  and Black will have to retreat with his bishop at some point giving us the initiative. }
11. Nxe4 { The knight looks very powerful on e4 eyeing many juicy targets. }
11... Nf6
{ Black can't tolerate such a powerful knight on e4 and wishes to eliminate it even at the cost of ruining his pawn structure.   11...Ne7  12.Qh5  followed by b3-Bb2 with a big advantage due to our terrifying army ready to go for an all-out attack! }
12. d3
{ Asking Black to improve our pawn structure, if he wishes to get rid of our knight. }
12... Be7
{ Black continues his cautious play aimed against our attacking ideas.   12...Nxe4  As a rule this capture is always bad for Black as it improves our position.  13.dxe4  followed by f4-Qg4/ Qh5 ideas with a strong initiative for the pawn. }
13. b3
{ There are many ways to continue our play, but I feel this is the most challenging #1b3Cowboy : @@EndBracket@@. }
13... O-O { At some point in life, Black has to castle. } 14. Bb2
{ Comp gives the usual 0.00, But I like our attacking chances on the kingside due to the bishop pair pointing at Black's kingside. }
