3... Nc6 4. Bb2 { Our bishop is gearing up for battle. } 4... a6
{ A useful preventive move aimed against Bb5 ideas. } 5. c4
{ Fighting for the control of the d5-square and stopping Black from easily achieving his d5-break. }
5... Qc7
{ The queen is controlling the key e5-square and prefers to treat the position like a Taimanov player.   5...d6  Trying to play e5 next.  6.d4!  Opening up the position advantageously and thanks to the pawns on e4/c4 we have a solid bind in the center which guarantees our advantage. }
6. g3
{ Beginning the journey of the second sniper. The light-squared bishop didn't have a great role on the f1-a6 diagonal hence it was time to change careers :@@EndBracket@@! }
6... Nf6
{ Black has to play provocatively to fight against our central dominance since passive moves would allow us to play Bg2 followed by O-O with a solid advantage thanks to the space/center control. }
7. e5 Ng4
{ So far we have been following existing theory and frankly nothing special... }
8. Bg2
{ A strong pawn sacrifice played only by Antipov so far! We give up the e5-pawn to quickly finish our development and not waste time in protecting it with 8.Qe2 was the main choice of everyone. }
8... Be7
{ In the origin game Black didn't want to take on e5 and went for this safe move. }
9. O-O
{ Giving one last chance to take the pawn under much less advantageous circumstances. }
9... O-O
{ Black takes the passive way out.   9...Ngxe5  Other knight capture will also lead to the same.  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.f4!  Forcing the knight to move from e5 will allow Bxg7 with a clear advantage due to the poor development of Black and worse pawn structure. We have ideas like Qh5 later on which could prove to be very nasty to defend against by Black. }
10. Re1
{ Was slightly better for White in @@StartBracket@@Antipov-Tsolakidou Rapid 2021@@EndBracket@@ thanks to the now powerful pawn hook on e5. Our idea is to play Nc3 followed by Qe2 with easy play. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Sicilian 2...e6 3.b3 Return of the Cowboy"]
[Black "3...Nc6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense: The answer for all the living beings who aren't satisfied with just equalizing and want to fight for the full point against any form of opposition! }
2. Nf3
{ Although I have had my fair share of fun with the Alapin and the Closed Sicilian with  2.Nc3  , when I want to decimate my opponents this is the move I resort to! }
2... e6
{ Black prefers to keep the diagonal of the f8-bishop open compared to the usual d6 systems where Black's priority is the light-squared bishop. Hence we can conclude that Black is adopting a dark-squared strategy. }
3. b3
{ Throwing caution to the winds! This Cowboy move is sure to throw your opponents off balance as they will be expecting  3.d4  ,  3.c3  , or even  3.g3  but they will never be ready for this :@@EndBracket@@ !!With this, I am paying homage to my very first Chessable course where I managed to pull off a Lifetime Repertoire with 1.b3. One of the biggest advantages of systems involving b3 is that Black players can never take it seriously which gives us very good chances to gain the advantage or a fighting initiative. Just put on the classic cowboy theme from ' The good, the bad and the ugly' when working on this line and everything will work fine :@@EndBracket@@! }
3... Nc6 4. Bb2 { Our bishop is gearing up for battle. } 4... a6
{ A useful preventive move aimed against Bb5 ideas. } 5. c4
{ Fighting for the control of the d5-square and stopping Black from easily achieving his d5-break. }
5... Qc7
{ The queen is controlling the key e5-square and prefers to treat the position like a Taimanov player.   5...d6  Trying to play e5 next.  6.d4!  Opening up the position advantageously and thanks to the pawns on e4/c4 we have a solid bind in the center which guarantees our advantage. }
6. g3
{ Beginning the journey of the second sniper. The light-squared bishop didn't have a great role on the f1-a6 diagonal hence it was time to change careers :@@EndBracket@@! }
6... Nf6
{ Black has to play provocatively to fight against our central dominance since passive moves would allow us to play Bg2 followed by O-O with a solid advantage thanks to the space/center control. }
7. e5 Ng4
{ So far we have been following existing theory and frankly nothing special... }
8. Bg2
{ A strong pawn sacrifice played only by Antipov so far! We give up the e5-pawn to quickly finish our development and not waste time in protecting it with 8.Qe2 was the main choice of everyone. }
8... Ngxe5
{ The ideal capture of the pawn.   8...Ncxe5  is not accurate.  9.O-O  Gaining more than enough compensation for the pawn due to the misplaced knight on g4. Our play is very natural like Re1, Nc3 followed by Nd5 ideas utilizing the power of the two sniper bishops on b2 and g2. }
9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. O-O
{ With the pawn alive on e5, only one our of our Bishop could be happy, but now thanks to the pawn sacrifice both of our bishops have become powerhouses who can't be tamed or controlled :@@EndBracket@@! }
10... Nd3
{ An interesting knight move to mess up our coordination.   10...d6  11.d4!  Always the opening of the position leads to a better position with fine compensation for the pawn.   10...Nc6  Preventing d4 ideas.  11.Re1  followed by Nc3-d5 also gives very good compensation for the pawn with Black having to tread his path carefully due to his sleeping army. }
11. Bc3
{ Our idea is to kick the annoying knight on d3 with Qe2 followed by d4 to open the position to make use of our better development and show the power of a fully mobilized army. I think nobody would want to play this position from the Black side. }
*

