[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense: The answer for all the living beings who aren't satisfied with just equalizing and want to fight for the full point against any form of opposition! }
2. Nf3
{ Although I have had my fair share of fun with the Alapin and the Closed Sicilian with 2. Nc3, when I want to decimate my opponents this is the move I resort to! }
2... g6
{ 'Hyper Accelerated Dragon' - Black is aiming for fianchetto systems. } 3. Bc4
{ We are continuing to pretend like Italian players and sticking to lines where we can develop our bishop to c4 irrespective of the line Black chooses :@@EndBracket@@. Our main idea is to prepare c3-d4, but the immediate  3.c3  @@StartBracket@@recommendation of Wesley@@EndBracket@@ allows  3...d5  after which Mr. Equalizer @@StartBracket@@Anish Giri@@EndBracket@@ managed to find a way to make this line also work for Black :@@EndBracket@@. Hence we are stopping d5 ideas and only then go for the capture of the center. }
3... Nf6
{ Black is planning to meet our  4.e5  advance with the counter-shock with  4...d5! }
4. Nc3
{ Time to return to the mainlines of Dragon because Black just messed up his move order and bit off more than what he can chew :@@EndBracket@@! }
4... Bg7 5. e5 { Black is poorly placed to meet this central advance. } 5...
Ng4 { Black has to go for this active move as the alternatives are too dumb. }
6. Bxf7+ { A satisfying shot making use of the knight on g4. } 6... Kxf7 7.
Ng5+ { Winning the piece back thanks to the double attack. } 7... Kg8
{ The king is safer on g8. } 8. Qxg4
{ Black's weak king gives us the advantage. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Sicilian: 2nd Move Deviations"]
[Black "Hyper-Accelerated Dragon: 2...g6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense: The answer for all the living beings who aren't satisfied with just equalizing and want to fight for the full point against any form of opposition! }
2. Nf3
{ Although I have had my fair share of fun with the Alapin and the Closed Sicilian with 2. Nc3, when I want to decimate my opponents this is the move I resort to! }
2... g6
{ 'Hyper Accelerated Dragon' - Black is aiming for fianchetto systems. } 3. Bc4
{ We are continuing to pretend like Italian players and sticking to lines where we can develop our bishop to c4 irrespective of the line Black chooses :@@EndBracket@@. Our main idea is to prepare c3-d4, but the immediate  3.c3  @@StartBracket@@recommendation of Wesley@@EndBracket@@ allows  3...d5  after which Mr. Equalizer @@StartBracket@@Anish Giri@@EndBracket@@ managed to find a way to make this line also work for Black :@@EndBracket@@. Hence we are stopping d5 ideas and only then go for the capture of the center. }
3... Nf6
{ Black is planning to meet our  4.e5  advance with the counter-shock with  4...d5! }
4. Nc3
{ Time to return to the mainlines of Dragon because Black just messed up his move order and bit off more than what he can chew :@@EndBracket@@! }
4... Nc6 { Aimed against e5 ideas. } 5. d4
{ Change of concept! We go for the direct kill by opening the center before Black can safely finish his development. }
5... Nxe4
{ An interesting change of pace. Black is trying to equalize using concrete means. }
6. Nxe4 d5 { We have many ways to get the advantage here. } 7. Bxd5 Qxd5 8. Qe2
{ Threatening the devastating Nf6+ using the pin along the e-file. } 8... Bg7
{ Best way to defend against the threat while also developing the bishop. } 9.
Bh6
{ Continuing to play with the feelings of our opponent :@@EndBracket@@ and trying to distract the bishop from the defense of the f6-square. }
9... Nxd4
{ Only move! Otherwise Black will end up in a horrible position.   9...O-O  10.Bxg7  Kxg7  11.c4  followed by d5 with a clear advantage due to the weak king and good attacking chances on the kingside using the dark squares. }
10. Nxd4 { We don't have an option either :@@EndBracket@@. } 10... Bxd4 11.
O-O-O { Renewing the threat of Nf6+ using the double pin on d- and e-files. }
11... Qc6
{ Moves like Be6 would allow us to win the bishop using the X-ray of the rook and the queen on the d-file with 12.c3. }
12. Rhe1
{ The last hero joins the battle and the Black king is starting to feel uncomfortable. }
12... Be6
{ Blocking the e-file and threatening to castle queenside with O-O-O. } 13. c3
{ Kicking the bishop off the powerful d4-square. } 13... Be5 14. Qe3 Bd5
{ The only move for Black.   14...b6  15.f4  leads to a winning advantage since the bishop on e5 has no good retreating place and the Black king will be stuck in the center. }
15. Nxc5
{ We have the attack continuing and the material has been restored! Black has to accept going into a worse endgame where our queenside majority will prove to be an important asset in our favor. }
