1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense: The answer for all the living beings who aren't satisfied with just equalizing and want to fight for the full point against any form of opposition! }
2. Nf3
{ Although I have had my fair share of fun with the Alapin and the Closed Sicilian with 2. Nc3, when I want to decimate my opponents this is the move I resort to! }
2... g6
{ 'Hyper Accelerated Dragon' - Black is aiming for fianchetto systems. } 3. Bc4
{ We are continuing to pretend like Italian players and sticking to lines where we can develop our bishop to c4 irrespective of the line Black chooses :@@EndBracket@@. Our main idea is to prepare c3-d4, but the immediate  3.c3  @@StartBracket@@recommendation of Wesley@@EndBracket@@ allows  3...d5  after which Mr. Equalizer @@StartBracket@@Anish Giri@@EndBracket@@ managed to find a way to make this line also work for Black :@@EndBracket@@. Hence we are stopping d5 ideas and only then go for the capture of the center. }
3... Nf6
{ Black is planning to meet our  4.e5  advance with the counter-shock with  4...d5! }
4. Nc3
{ Time to return to the mainlines of Dragon because Black just messed up his move order and bit off more than what he can chew :@@EndBracket@@! }
4... Nc6 { Aimed against e5 ideas. } 5. d4
{ Change of concept! We go for the direct kill by opening the center before Black can safely finish his development. }
5... cxd4 6. Nxd4
{ Ideally Black would like to achieve both Bg7 and d6... but unfortunately in chess, Black can make only one move per turn :@@EndBracket@@. }
6... d6 { Preventing e5 ideas... or at least that's what Black thinks! } 7.
Nxc6 { Freeing the d-file for the following tactic. } 7... bxc6 8. e5
{ A fine central thrust using the poor development of Black's pieces. } 8...
Ng4
{ 8...dxe5  loses the queen.  9.Bxf7+!  Distracting the king and forcing him to abandon his beloved queen on d8. }
9. exd6
{ Ruining Black's pawn structure as he can't recapture with the e-pawn due to kingside castling with O-O followed by Re1+ leading to a disastrous position for Black. }
9... Qxd6 { Black hopes to find salvation in the worse endgame. } 10. h3
{ We shouldn't take on d6 as it improves his pawn structure, one of the major points tipping the balance in our favor is the better pawn structure. }
10... Ne5 { Gaining a nice tempo attacking the bishop on c4. } 11. Bb3
{ The bishop looks active on the a2-g8 diagonal. } 11... Qxd1+ 12. Nxd1
{ We have the advantage in the endgame thanks to the pawn structure. Black's pawn on a7 and c6 will need constant supervision and protection. Our plan is to continue with Bd2, Nc3 or Ne3 followed by O-O-O with a nice play. }
