[White "7) Sicilian: 2nd Move Deviations"]
[Black "O’Kelly Variation: 2…a6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense: The answer for all the living beings who aren't satisfied with just equalizing and want to fight for the full point against any form of opposition! }
2. Nf3
{ Although I have had my fair share of fun with the Alapin and the Closed Sicilian with 2. Nc3, when I want to decimate my opponents this is the move I resort to! }
2... a6
{ The famous trappy line is known as 'O'Kelly variation' which is very popular at the lower level where many tend to go for 3.d4 after which Black can get a decent game... If White is not careful enough. }
3. c4
{ The strongest option taking a lot of space in the center before going for the d4 break. For some reason, both Wesley and Sethu chose to give 3.c3 when our main move is the top recommendation of the engine. }
3... e6 { Paulsen players would prefer to play this way. } 4. Nc3
{ This is slightly preferable over direct 4.d4 which transposes to mainlines of Paulsen with Maroczy type structures. }
4... Nf6 { Black is playing the provocative game. } 5. e5
{ We happily oblige. } 5... Ng8
{ The knight would be harassed by our pawns, If it goes to g4. } 6. d4
{ Thanks to the advanced e-pawn, we can gain a better position in the center. }
6... cxd4
{ Black doesn't have an option as we were threatening both dxc5 followed by Ne4 or d5 advancing our pawns to demoralize Black. }
7. Qxd4
{ I like this move as we are bringing our strongest piece into the fight without any delay. }
7... Nc6
{ Generally because of this tempo... people tend to prefer 7. Nxd4, but we don't mind giving Black illusionary gains. }
8. Qe4 { The superlative square for the queen! } 8... d6
{ Black desperately wants to get rid of our central pawn hook on e5. } 9. Bf4
{ Continuing to develop our pieces and not helping Black to develop his pieces with exd6. }
9... dxe5 10. Nxe5
{ After the central exchange, we have the queenside majority and the initiative due to our better-developed pieces. }
10... Nf6 { Other moves can't dispute our authority in the position. } 11. Nxc6
{ The following exchange operation ends in our favor, so there is no need to shy away from it. }
11... Nxe4 12. Nxd8 Nxc3
{ Black might have seen till here and felt he must be doing fine... } 13. Nxf7
{ Sometimes when you are calculating a long line, try to push yourself and go one move deeper! It might make the difference between a win and a draw. }
13... Kxf7 { Since the h8-rook was attacked, Black didn't have a choice. } 14.
bxc3
{ with a healthy extra pawn in the endgame where Black also has an isolated pawn on e6 to add to his troubles. We continue with Be2 followed by O-O with a clear advantage. }
