[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Sicilian: 2nd Move Deviations"]
[Black "O’Kelly Variation: 2…a6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense: The answer for all the living beings who aren't satisfied with just equalizing and want to fight for the full point against any form of opposition! }
2. Nf3
{ Although I have had my fair share of fun with the Alapin and the Closed Sicilian with 2. Nc3, when I want to decimate my opponents this is the move I resort to! }
2... a6
{ The famous trappy line is known as 'O'Kelly variation' which is very popular at the lower level where many tend to go for 3.d4 after which Black can get a decent game... If White is not careful enough. }
3. c4
{ The strongest option taking a lot of space in the center before going for the d4 break. For some reason, both Wesley and Sethu chose to give 3.c3 when our main move is the top recommendation of the engine. }
3... d6 { This is too lame and can hardly bother us. } 4. d4
{ Winning the fight for the center. } 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4
{ We already have a big advantage thanks to the central control having achieved c4 before playing Nc3. }
5... Nf6
{ Black is trying to pretend that life is still fine and everything is going according to plan :@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Nc3 e6 { The typical Scheveningen move. } 7. Be3
{ Let's delay the development of the f1-bishop for one more move. } 7... Be7
{ Black can't fianchetto the dark-squared bishop due to the pawn weakness on d6. }
8. Rc1 { Continuing to toy with the placement of the light-squared bishop. }
8... O-O 9. Bd3
{ Finally we reveal our cards! The bishop is much more actively placed on d3 than on e2, this was the reason why we were delaying the development of the bishop. It was also possible to play Bd3 on the previous, but it feels more aesthetically pleasing to play this after Rc1 to be able to retreat Bb1 in the future. }
9... b6 { Reaching Black's main setup of the Hedgehog system. } 10. O-O Bb7
{ The bishop shall put pressure on the long diagonal and we always have to watch out for both d5/b5 breaks! Black's concept is called the "Coiled Spring Method" as he is waiting for the right time to break through in the center or the queenside. }
11. Bb1 { Clearing the d-file to keep the d5-break under check. } 11... Nbd7
12. b3
{ Protecting the c4-pawn with a nice space advantage. In this position, it is more important that we keep restricting Black's ideas than to create our play! I would suggest the following plan with h3, Qd2, and Kh1 slowly but surely improving our position on both fronts with a4, f3. I would recommend studying the "Complete Hedgehog" by Shipov to understand how to play these positions as this pawn structure is a recurring theme from many Sicilians. }
