6. Nf5 { Of course the d6-square is the target for our knight! } 6... d6
{ Preventing Nd6+ and preparing g6 next to kick our brave knight from f5.   6...Nf6  7.Nc3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p1n5/8/2PNP3/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Nc3  e5  7.Nf5  . }
7. Nc3 { Giving Black the chance to give up his bishop pair with Bxf5. } 7...
g6
{ Black is not planning on tolerating our knight on f5 any longer.   7...Bxf5  is just horrible and hands the fight for the light-square to us on a silver platter.  8.exf5  with a big advantage and can be continued with Bd3 followed by O-O. }
8. Ne3 Bh6
{ This was Black's point attempting to exchange his bad bishop to its superior counterpart on c1. }
9. Be2
{ This strong yet simple developing move was not played by the elite players... }
9... Nge7 { Artemiev's choice. } 10. Nc2
{ Halting any Nd4 ideas and exchanging the dark-squared bishop. } 10... Bxc1
11. Rxc1
{ Although Black has achieved his main aim of getting rid of the dark-squared bishop, this by no means has reduced his problems as the d6-pawn will always remain a target for our pieces and his kingside is very weak due to the disappearance of the main guardian which was the h6-bishop! }
11... O-O { Black would like to create his counterplay with f5. } 12. Qd2
{ Threatening Rd1 to attack the d6-pawn with a clear advantage due to the grip on the position. Only after asserting our dominance on the d-file, we castle kingside! }
