[White "7) Sicilian: 2nd Move Deviations"]
[Black "Katalymov Variation: 2...b6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense: The answer for all the living beings who aren't satisfied with just equalizing and want to fight for the full point against any form of opposition! }
2. Nf3
{ Although I have had my fair share of fun with the Alapin and the Closed Sicilian with 2. Nc3, when I want to decimate my opponents this is the move I resort to! }
2... b6
{ Black can't afford to take such leisure time to fianchetto without fighting for the center. }
3. d4 { Best way to punish Black's silly concept. } 3... cxd4
{ 3...Bb7  4.d5  leads to a horrible position with no breathing space for Black. }
4. Nxd4 Bb7 { Black develops the bishop to the appointed fianchetto diagonal. }
5. Bg5
{ Almost 1000 have been featured with the natural 5.Nc3... but in my opinion, this is more exciting! We are giving up the e4-pawn which Black would be well-advised not to take. }
5... Bxe4
{ Expecting 6.Nc3 to which he can reply Bb7. This greedy pawn grab is a big mistake! }
6. Nb5
{ Going for the kill by threatening the devastating Nd6+ using the pinned pawn on e7 thanks to our powerful dark-squared bishop on the h4-d8 diagonal. }
6... Nf6 7. Qe2
{ The Bishop on e4 is untouchable due to Nd6 checkmate :@@EndBracket@@ and moves to protect the bishop can be cooly met with the developing N1c3 leading to a big winning advantage due to Black's poor development. }
7... d5 8. N1c3
{ Once again the bishop can't retreat due to Bxf6 followed by Nxd5 with a deadly fork incoming on the c7-square. }
8... a6
{ Going after the b5-knight is Black's best chance in this worst position :@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Bxf6 { Facilitating our capture on e4. } 9... gxf6 10. Nxe4
{ Hoping Black will take on  b5  because of the pretty  10...axb5  11.Nxf6#  :@@EndBracket@@. }
10... dxe4 11. Qxe4
{ With a clear advantage attacking the a8-rook to be followed by Rd1 next... }
