6. exd6 Bxd6 7. Bb5+
{ Asking Black to ruin his position further by weakening his pawn structure also :@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Nc6 { Otherwise Black will lose his castling rights. } 8. Bxc6+
{ Black will regret his opening choice after seeing this move :@@EndBracket@@. }
8... bxc6 9. Nxd6+ { Removing the main defender of the c5-pawn. } 9... Qxd6 10.
O-O
{ We have a solid advantage thanks to Black's weak doubled pawns on c6/ c5 which are an easy target for our c1-bishop and the f3-knight. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Sicilian: 2nd Move Deviations"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch Variation: 2...Nf6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense: The answer for all the living beings who aren't satisfied with just equalizing and want to fight for the full point against any form of opposition! }
2. Nf3
{ Although I have had my fair share of fun with the Alapin and the Closed Sicilian with 2. Nc3, when I want to decimate my opponents this is the move I resort to! }
2... Nf6
{ Black is trying to copy us :@@EndBracket@@. This is known as Sicilian Defense: Nimzowitsch Variation. I tried to make the titles related to the horrible covid era! }
3. e5
{ The most challenging as 3. Nc3 would allow Black the option to revert back to Najdorf or Sveshnikov type position with d6 or Nc6 respectively. }
3... Nd5 4. Nc3
{ Developing with tempo and asking Black to improve our pawn structure with Nxc3. }
4... e6
{ The main move in this line, Black is ready to weaken his pawn structure to quickly finish his development. }
5. Ne4 { Eyeing the juicy target on d6. } 5... f5
{ A weapon used exclusively by Le Tuan Minh in the pandemic era.   5...Nc6  is the second most popular move, but it is inferior to the alternatives.  6.c4  followed by d4 next with a big advantage due to the grip exhibited by the e5-pawn on the d6-square. }
6. Nc3 Ne7
{ Black's attempt to manoeuver the knight to g6 will not go unpunished! } 7.
Nb5
{ Threatening a deadly mate in one on d6 made possible by Black's last move. }
7... Ng6 { Other moves also don't bring any relief to Black. } 8. b4
{ A brilliant pawn sacrifice to gain the necessary momentum to unleash the wrath of our pieces using the weakened dark-squares. This looks very strong and much more deadly than Sethu's recommendation with b3 @@StartBracket@@It does break my heart a bit, that he gives b3 while I give b4...@@EndBracket@@. 'The price of freedom is always high, but it is a price I am willing to pay :@@EndBracket@@' - A random and pointless quote for the current situation. }
8... cxb4
{ Black has to accept the gambit since we would just take on c5 followed by d4 capturing the center and the key dark squares. }
9. h4
{ For a while, the comp was recommending 8.h4, but then it understood that it is advantageous to include the pawn sacrifice with b4 to open the bishop's path to b2. The h1-rook joins the fight energetically! }
9... a6
{ Due to the looming threat of h5, Black is forced to attack our b5-knight. }
10. Nd6+
{ Winning the bishop pair and the fight for the dark squares :@@EndBracket@@. Black can only watch in horror as our c1-bishop takes up his designated location on b2 to wreak havoc via the a1-h8 diagonal. }
10... Bxd6
{ I don't think Black was mentally ready for the Bong cloud with Ke7 :@@EndBracket@@. }
11. exd6
{ The pawn on d6 is a major asset and we must fight with everything we have got to make sure that Black can't win it without suffering serious consequences! }
11... O-O
{ At least Black can pretend he got mated only after castling and not before :@@EndBracket@@! }
12. h5 { The h-pawn is going for the kill! } 12... Nh8
{ Black's pieces deserve the honorary award for being in the 8th rank :@@EndBracket@@. }
13. Bb2
{ The combo of the b2-bishop, h5-pawn, and the h1-rook makes for a fearsome team! Our threat is to play Bd3 followed by Qe2 and g4 with a mating attack via the g-file. Comp already gives a more than +2 eval. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Sicilian: 2nd Move Deviations"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch Variation: 2...Nf6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense: The answer for all the living beings who aren't satisfied with just equalizing and want to fight for the full point against any form of opposition! }
2. Nf3
{ Although I have had my fair share of fun with the Alapin and the Closed Sicilian with 2. Nc3, when I want to decimate my opponents this is the move I resort to! }
2... Nf6
{ Black is trying to copy us :@@EndBracket@@. This is known as Sicilian Defense: Nimzowitsch Variation. I tried to make the titles related to the horrible covid era! }
3. e5
{ The most challenging as 3. Nc3 would allow Black the option to revert back to Najdorf or Sveshnikov type position with d6 or Nc6 respectively. }
3... Nd5 4. Nc3
{ Developing with tempo and asking Black to improve our pawn structure with Nxc3. }
4... e6
{ The main move in this line, Black is ready to weaken his pawn structure to quickly finish his development. }
5. Ne4 { Eyeing the juicy target on d6. } 5... f5
{ A weapon used exclusively by Le Tuan Minh in the pandemic era.   5...Nc6  is the second most popular move, but it is inferior to the alternatives.  6.c4  followed by d4 next with a big advantage due to the grip exhibited by the e5-pawn on the d6-square. }
6. Nc3 Nb4
{ Black is dancing around with his knight to avoid taking on c3 which makes sure that we don't have very easy play via the d-file.   6...Nxc3  Capturing on c3 is always a sign of defeat for Black as it opens the d-file and gives us the space advantage.  7.dxc3  followed by Bf4-Qd2 and queenside castling with a solid advantage, while Black's pieces are suffering from limited play due to the lack of space. }
7. a3 { Preparing a cool pawn sacrifice. } 7... N4c6 8. b4
{ A strong concept giving up a pawn to win the fight for the control of the dark squares. }
8... d6
{ Black prefers to fight against our central bind than to take the greedy path without finishing the development.   8...cxb4  9.Nb5  A typical shot ignoring the pawn on b4 and aiming to win the bishop pair with Nd6+ at the right moment. }
9. exd6 Bxd6 10. Bc4
{ We have the initiative and Black's position has weaknesses like e6 and f5 which tip the balance in our favor. }
10... O-O
{ 'Better safe than sorry!'.   10...cxb4  would end up making Black's situation even worse.  11.Nb5!  with an advantage thanks to the initiative offered by our combined army. We can follow it up with O-O and Re1 to put pressure on the e6-pawn and can open the a-file anytime with axb4. }
11. bxc5 Bxc5 { Black seems to be pretty decent so far... } 12. Ne2
{ A fantastic knight retreat preparing d4 next to capture the center and I was very surprised to see that comp gives quite a sizable advantage due to the future backward pawn on e6. We will plan to put pressure via the two open e and b files by placing our rooks on b1 and e1 respectively. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Advance of the French"]
[Black "2...c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... e6
{ 'The unpredictable French Defense' - Most of the time, it is very hard to understand what Black players want with this opening... Do they want to aim for a complicated game? Suffer in a worse endgame? Outprepare us under the huge mage of theoretical lines? I guess in the end, it all comes to the player himself.Compared to the king's pawn opening with 1...e5 or the Sicilian Defense with 1...c5, Black is willing to give up the center to White to organize an attack against our mighty center combined with both pieces and pawn artillery! In this way, I think it resembles the Caro-Kann the most. }
2. d4
{ There are many ways to combat the French, but I feel this is the most principled - taking control of the center and gaining a lot of room for easy development for our pieces. }
2... c5
{ This is a bad sideline and allows us to gain the space advantage and the center control. }
3. d5 { Beginning of our dominating strategy. } 3... exd5
{ The mainline is slightly more challenging. } 4. exd5 d6
{ Black accepts his sad fate and prefers to finish his development. } 5. Nf3
Nf6 6. Be2
{ For now, this is the best place for the bishop and discourages Black from having any Bg4 ideas which can be convincingly met with h3. }
6... Be7
{ Black doesn't have the luxury of preparing for the kingside fianchetto with g6-Bg7 due to O-O followed by Bb5+ with Re1+ incoming leaving Black with no time to castle. }
7. O-O O-O 8. c4
{ Followed by Nc3, Re1 next with a big advantage and Black doesn't have any tricks to compensate for his lack of space. }
*

