6. Be2
{ I felt this was the easiest way to gain the advantage without any hurdles! }
6... Nc6
{ An interesting move order trick! Black returns back to the Nc6 lines after we committed Be2 preventing us from going for the dangerous pawn sacrifice with Bd3... but unfortunately for Black, the move Bd7 is too slow and can't challenge our might in the center. }
7. O-O { We continue as if nothing happened :@@EndBracket@@. } 7... Nge7
{ This is definitely the weakest of alternatives as it closes the bishop's f8-a3 diagonal. }
8. dxc5
{ I was very surprised to find that the most popular option was Na3 which is weaker than our mainline. }
8... Qxc5 9. Be3 { The usual tempo-gaining move. } 9... Qa5
{ Obviously the only square for the queen where it will come under fire with b4 or c4 ideas. }
10. Nbd2
{ Finishing the development and preparing to open the center with c4. Our piece placement would be Rc1-Re1 and the light-squared bishop can go to d3 or f1 depending on the setup chosen by Black. }
