8... Bxc5 9. b4
{ This is a recurring and typical plan in the Bd7-Qb6 line. We take on c5 followed by b4 to gain a nice tempo attacking the bishop. }
9... Be7 { Black prepares the f6 break. } 10. b5
{ Forcing the knight to go to the rim of the board. } 10... Na5
{ It is funny that we have managed to confine both the knights to the corner :@@EndBracket@@. }
11. a4
{ I think we can boast of a solid edge due to the bind on the queenside and Black hasn't have the strength nor the authority to challenge our central pawn on e5. Our plans consist of Bd3-Re1 and the a1-rook can be skillfully activated with Ra2. As we closed the queenside, our play is based on the kingside where we have good chances to gain something real. }
