7. O-O { We continue as if nothing happened :@@EndBracket@@. } 7... f6 8. dxc5
{ Following the golden rule that play in the center should be met by counter-attack in the flank :@@EndBracket@@. }
8... Bxc5
{ Taking with the queen will met by the same b4 with even worse evals! } 9. b4
{ Attacking the bishop and freeing the pathway for Be3. } 9... Be7 10. Be3
{ Developing with tempo! } 10... Qc7
{ So far its been existing theory and here we have a bomb! } 11. c4
{ Opening up the position with deadly force to make use of the weak king on e8. I think we can safely say that Black players shouldn't enter this line anymore. }
11... fxe5
{ Things are bad for Black if this is his best move :@@EndBracket@@.   11...dxc4  13.Na3  followed by Nc4 with a big advantage as Black is struggling to finish his kingside development. }
12. cxd5 exd5
{ The other capture on  b4  will also most likely transpose;  12...Nxb4  13.dxe6  Bxe6  14.Qa4+!  A strong move forcing the black bishop to retreat since moves like Nc6 would allow Nc3 with a very strong initiative for the pawn.  14...Bd7  15.Qb3!  We have transposed to the mainline from @@StartFEN@@r3k1nr/ppqbb1pp/2n1p3/3Pp3/1P6/4BN2/P3BPPP/RN1Q1RK1 b kq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...exd5  . }
13. Qxd5 { The queen looks dominant in the center of the board. } 13... Nxb4
{ The natural developing move with  13...Nf6  doesn't change anything as Black can't castle kingside after  14.Qb3!  giving us a big advantage due to the many weak light squares around the king. }
14. Qb3 { Bravely allowing Nc2 winning the a1-rook. } 14... Nc2 15. Nc3
{ It is important to note that pinning the c2-knight with  15.Rc1  fails to  15...Nxa1  attacking our queen on b3. }
15... Nxa1 16. Rxa1
{ The threats of Nd5 and Nb5 prove to be very nasty leading to a winning attack for White with big material losses for Black. The a1-rook will find his place on the d-file to put maximum pressure on Black. }
