3. e5
{ With this ambitious move nicknamed the 'The Advance Variation', the standards are set by us. The aim is to go for a kingside attack using the e5-pawn as the battering ram while Black will use everything in his power to distract us from our plans with maximum pressure on the central d4-square where lies the key, the collapse of which could sway the struggle towards the winner of the battle! }
3... c5
{ True to his word, Black starts the assault on the center without any delay! }
4. c3
{ There have been ways to continue the fight by taking on c5, but in my opinion, it is a major concession. We stand our ground and protect the center... at least for the time being :@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Nc6
{ Black is slowly but surely starting to organize his play against the main weakness in White's camp - 'The d4-pawn'. }
5. Nf3
{ Bolstering our center pawn on d4, the whole fight depends on that :@@EndBracket@@...  At least we pretend to let Black into believing so : @@EndBracket@@. }
5... Nge7 { Black is coming for our d4-pawn without any restraints! } 6. Na3
{ For the time being, we take a defensive stance against Black's attacks and protect our darling of the center - the d4-pawn. }
6... Nf5
{ Threatening to take on d4 followed by Bb4+ and Qb6.   6...cxd4  7.cxd4  Nf5  will transpose to the mainline. }
7. Nc2
{ Preventing all nasty threats of Black. The knights are evenly matched... but the balance is in our favor due to the space and our bishop can come to d3 to attack the f5-knight. }
7... cxd4
{ Relaxing the tension in the center.   7...Be7  doesn't change much.  8.Bd3  Preparing O-O next followed by Re1 with a slight advantage due to the central bind on e5. }
8. cxd4 Be7
{ A@@EndBracket@@  8...Nb4  9.Nxb4  Just straightforward chess.  9...Bxb4+  Although Black is exchanging off two sets of minor pieces, the remaining pieces are clearly superior, especially our f1 bishop vs c8 bishop.  10.Bd2  followed by Bd3 with a space advantage. We can play on both queenside and kingside.   B@@EndBracket@@  8...Qb6  can't bother us at all.  9.Bd3  The d4-pawn is immune due to the discovered check on b5 after the exchange of both knights. Black's continuing trouble with less space guarantees our advantage.   C@@EndBracket@@  8...Bd7  Trying to bring the rook to c8 to create some play via the c-file.  9.Bd3  Continuing our main setup.  9...Bb4+!?  Trying to confuse us.  10.Kf1!  N  A very powerful novelty giving up our castling to maintain the tension in the position and we can also include the h1-rook with h4 next with a nice advantage. }
9. Bd3 { Ideally always prefer to develop the bishop to d3. } 9... O-O
{ Many games have reached this position which is just downright losing for Black :@@EndBracket@@! }
10. g4 { Going after the loosely placed knight on f5. } 10... Nh4
{ Black is hoping that he might survive the storm...   10...Nh6  11.Rg1  Protecting the pawn on g4 and laughing at the Black knight on h6. }
11. Nxh4 Bxh4 12. g5
{ Opening the d1-h5 diagonal for Qh5 next and closing the return passage for the h4-bishop. }
12... Bxg5
{ Black is still under some belief that he can somehow hold this... } 13. Qh5
{ Double attack on h7 and g5 forcing Black's next move. } 13... h6
{ Black feels that the worst is over for him... } 14. Rg1
{ Bringing in the main act of the play - our h1 rook! } 14... Bxc1
{ What else? The threat of Bxg5 or Rxg5 was too much to bear for Black. } 15.
Rxc1 { Threatening the deadly Qxh6 leaving Black with minimal options. } 15...
Kh8 { Moving away from the pin on the g-file. } 16. Kd2
{ The devastating Rxg7 is on the cards now with a winning attack. } *

