1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... e6
{ 'The unpredictable French Defense' - Most of the time, it is very hard to understand what Black players want with this opening... Do they want to aim for a complicated game? Suffer in a worse endgame? Outprepare us under the huge mage of theoretical lines? I guess in the end, it all comes to the player himself.Compared to the king's pawn opening with 1...e5 or the Sicilian Defense with 1...c5, Black is willing to give up the center to White to organize an attack against our mighty center combined with both pieces and pawn artillery! In this way, I think it resembles the Caro-Kann the most. }
2. d4
{ There are many ways to combat the French, but I feel this is the most principled - taking control of the center and gaining a lot of room for easy development for our pieces. }
2... d5
{ Black was building up towards this with his first move. The fight for center begins and White has to decide on whether he wants to maintain his center by protecting the pawn on e4, give in to the pressure by taking on d5, or finally the most dangerous attempt - advancing his forces by creating a strong pawn hook in the center. }
3. e5
{ With this ambitious move nicknamed the 'The Advance Variation', the standards are set by us. The aim is to go for a kingside attack using the e5-pawn as the battering ram while Black will use everything in his power to distract us from our plans with maximum pressure on the central d4-square where lies the key, the collapse of which could sway the struggle towards the winner of the battle! }
3... c5
{ True to his word, Black starts the assault on the center without any delay! }
4. c3
{ There have been ways to continue the fight by taking on c5, but in my opinion, it is a major concession. We stand our ground and protect the center... at least for the time being :@@EndBracket@@. }
