{ This safe waiting move is Black's best bet. He wants to see how we will proceed and only then choose his plans.   10...a6  willtranspose to  9...a6 10.h5 h6 lines. }
11. Na3 { Threatening future Nb5 ideas. } 11... Nf5
{ The strongest response opening the a3-f8 diagonal and increasing the influence on the d4-square. }
12. Rb1
{ This looks better than  12.g4  which is more forcing, but one which liquidates into a draw... if Black knows his stuff. }
12... a6
{ Again this unnatural move is not easy to find and natural moves like  12...Be7  gives us the advantage after  13.Bf4  . }
13. c4
{ Starting the forced sequence where Black has to be very precise to survive. }
13... Nb4 { Increasing the support system of the d5-square. } 14. cxd5
{ We didn't have much choice. } 14... Nxd3
{ It is important to get rid of our powerful light-squares bishop.   14...Nxd5  15.g4  with a winning attack since Nfe7 can be met with Nc4 threatening the deadly Nd6+. }
15. Qxd3 { Our center pawns look scary. } 15... Bb4
{ An important tempo gain attacking the rook and preparing the castling to the kingside. }
16. Bd2 Bxd2 17. Nxd2 { Keeping a nasty trap! } 17... O-O
{ Of course, it would be childish of Black to fall into such a cheapo...   17...exd5  would be met by the stunning  18.e6!!  followed by Qxf5 winning the piece due to the pin along the e-file. }
18. d6
{ Although the comp gives the boring 0.00 eval, I feel this is a solid try due to our powerful pawn on d6 compared to the weak d4-pawn. We can continue with Nf3 next threatening g4 winning the f5-knight. }
