{ After a long struggle, I finally managed to find a dangerous path for Black! I feel this is the way, directly going for the kill without any hesitation! }
10... g6 { Black hopes to fight back bravely against our h-pawn. } 11. Nbd2
{ The improvement which will revive this line and I was very proud of my find... Until I realized that Gawain also recommends this move :@@EndBracket@@. On a positive note at least you can be damn sure that this is the best way for White :@@EndBracket@@. Anish had only checked 11.h6 which although interesting doesn't get the job done. We continue developing our pieces leaving another pawn en prise : @@EndBracket@@. Isn't this how you are supposed to play in the Romantic era :@@EndBracket@@? }
11... gxh5
{ Only move! Black has to bite the bullet by further weakening his pawn structure and king safety by taking this greedy computer recommended approach! }
12. Nb3
{ Now that we have given up another pawn to weaken Black's kingside beyond repair, It was time to stop caring about the material and get the party started :@@EndBracket@@. }
12... dxc3
{ Ok now, he doesn't have an option but to take here :@@EndBracket@@. } 13.
bxc3
{ Time to take stock - We are two pawns down @@StartBracket@@seriously stop counting the material @@EndBracket@@, but we have the open b-file and lots of juicy targets for our minor and major pieces. When the time is ripe we will start picking the loosely placed Black's pawns. }
13... Ng6
{ Trying to finish development and hopefully ask us some questions about the e5-pawn.   13...Qc7  will transpose to the mainlines after  14.Rb1  Ng6  . }
14. Rb1
{ With this move, the first phase of basic development is over. The next phase will be to improve our pieces and put them where they will exert maximum pressure against our enemy. }
14... Qc7 { Moving away from any future discovered threats along the b-file. }
15. Nbd4
{ Gawain stops here giving full compensation which is true, but I feel it is still too early to make assumptions and let us take the plunge into the madness! }
15... h4
{ The greedy alternative - Black predicts the futuristic Nxc6 followed by Nd4 threatening to take on h5 and makes safety precautions against it. }
16. Nxc6 { For one knight to rise, the other must perish - AD 2021. } 16...
Bxc6 { The only capture which holds the position together. } 17. Nd4
{ The e5-pawn is tactically protected due to the pin with Bf4 and Qh5-Ne6 ideas making full use of the fact that the enemy king is still on e8. }
17... Bd7 18. Bd2
{ Making a useful developing move protecting c3 to play Qh5 next where the queen will be well placed to put pressure on Black's kingside. Our army is well placed for the middlegame battle and let us take a look at one sample line to show the dangers of Black's position. }
18... Nxe5 { Greedy boy :@@EndBracket@@. } 19. Bf4
{ Pinning and winning :@@EndBracket@@. } 19... Bd6
{ Breaking the pin and this is the only way for Black not to lose immediately. }
20. Qh5
{ The pressure is mounting and Black has to find the only way to survive. }
20... Nf3+ 21. Qxf3
{ Surprisingly  21.Nxf3  Bxf4  22.Qxh4  also offers full compensation with nice attacking chances. }
21... Bxf4 22. c4
{ Beginning the 'Attack on the light squares'. Black has to make a lot of only moves to not end up completely lost, while the game continues even if he pulls off that impossible feat. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Advance of the French"]
[Black "4...Nc6 5.Nf3 Qb6 #16"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... e6
{ 'The unpredictable French Defense' - Most of the time, it is very hard to understand what Black players want with this opening... Do they want to aim for a complicated game? Suffer in a worse endgame? Outprepare us under the huge mage of theoretical lines? I guess in the end, it all comes to the player himself.Compared to the king's pawn opening with 1...e5 or the Sicilian Defense with 1...c5, Black is willing to give up the center to White to organize an attack against our mighty center combined with both pieces and pawn artillery! In this way, I think it resembles the Caro-Kann the most. }
2. d4
{ There are many ways to combat the French, but I feel this is the most principled - taking control of the center and gaining a lot of room for easy development for our pieces. }
2... d5
{ Black was building up towards this with his first move. The fight for center begins and White has to decide on whether he wants to maintain his center by protecting the pawn on e4, give in to the pressure by taking on d5, or finally the most dangerous attempt - advancing his forces by creating a strong pawn hook in the center. }
3. e5
{ With this ambitious move nicknamed the 'The Advance Variation', the standards are set by us. The aim is to go for a kingside attack using the e5-pawn as the battering ram while Black will use everything in his power to distract us from our plans with maximum pressure on the central d4-square where lies the key, the collapse of which could sway the struggle towards the winner of the battle! }
3... c5
{ True to his word, Black starts the assault on the center without any delay! }
4. c3
{ There have been ways to continue the fight by taking on c5, but in my opinion, it is a major concession. We stand our ground and protect the center... at least for the time being :@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Nc6
{ Black is slowly but surely starting to organize his play against the main weakness in White's camp - 'The d4-pawn'. }
5. Nf3
{ Bolstering our center pawn on d4, the whole fight depends on that :@@EndBracket@@...  At least we pretend to let Black into believing so : @@EndBracket@@. }
5... Qb6
{ The best place for the queen in the French defense. Black's queen is keeping pressure on the d4-pawn and the b2-pawn stopping White from developing both the bishops to their dream posts - 'The d3-square for the f1-bishop and e3 for the c1-bishop'. }
6. Bd3
{ It was precisely this move followed by its brilliant attacking concept which made me choose the Advance variation compared to the more popular 3.Nc3 lines. Refusing to budge into Black's pressure, we insist on developing our bishop to the best possible location at any cost! It was with great surprise/ pride that I noticed both Gawain Jones's Coffee house repertoire and Richard/ Simon's Grandmaster Gambits also recommend this epic direction! With Captain Hindsight as my guide, I have tried to find my own path wherever applicable :@@EndBracket@@.   6.a3  is one of the main replies for White  6...c4  After this strong direction mentioned by Anish Giri in his Chessable course, I think Black is already fine as he has put a stop to White's ambition in the queenside thanks to ideas like Bd7-Na5... while at the same time he can continue preparing to open up the kingside with long term ideas like f6 breaking up our center. }
6... cxd4 { 'The best way to refute a gambit is to accept it' } 7. O-O
{ The beginning of the concept! It was still possible to save the pawn with 7. cxd4 but that was never our intention! By sacrificing the pawn we completely turn the situation into an extremely unpleasant one for our opponents. 'The hunter becomes the hunted' after this move, our target becomes singular... 'Go for the king and don't miss!'.Let's take a look at what can Black do after this, he will find it hard to finish his development as our focus is shifted to creating deadly threats on the kingside and from the queenside :@@EndBracket@@. Hard to believe? It might seem like that from the first impression, but delving deeper into the position we will realize that with a simple sacrifice, the safe haven of the black king is in doubt. He can't go to the kingside due to the two bishops and the knight pointing in that direction begging to be involved in some form of dangerous attack! If he tries to go to the queenside then we will go for ideas like Nbd2-Rb1 forcing the opening of the b-file where once again the Black king is going to be hunted by our entire army.With all these crazy concepts in mind, let us try to find out what defensive precautions can be undertaken by Black to stop our attack! }
7... Bd7
{ Black wants to keep the pawn on d4 for long as possible...hopefully without losing a piece or the queen with the cd4 Nd4 Nd4 Bb5+ discovered trick :@@EndBracket@@. }
8. Re1
{ Starting to act like the material is equal and continue to mobilize our forces! Be warned - Black's defensive resources are not to be underestimated! We will need every member of our army to go all out in this fight between Good vs evil :@@EndBracket@@. }
8... Nge7
{ Thanks to the powerful pawn hook on e5, Black's knight can be activated either via e7 or g6. }
9. h4
{ AlphaZero's favorite pawn plunge designed to create another attacking pawn hook! Black is unfortunately faced with a difficult decision of allowing the pawn to h5 or h6 or stop it with h5 which would seriously compromise his king safety and the f7-weak point after an eventual knight jump to g5 followed by Qf3 laying waste to f7. }
9... a6
{ This is Anish's recommendation, biding his time and hoping to stop White's attack with some prophylactic measures. The time has come for us to power through with some explosive ideas! }
10. h5
{ After a long struggle, I finally managed to find a dangerous path for Black! I feel this is the way, directly going for the kill without any hesitation! }
10... g6 { Black hopes to fight back bravely against our h-pawn. } 11. Nbd2
{ The improvement which will revive this line and I was very proud of my find... Until I realized that Gawain also recommends this move :@@EndBracket@@. On a positive note at least you can be damn sure that this is the best way for White :@@EndBracket@@. Anish had only checked 11.h6 which although interesting doesn't get the job done. We continue developing our pieces leaving another pawn en prise : @@EndBracket@@. Isn't this how you are supposed to play in the Romantic era :@@EndBracket@@? }
11... gxh5
{ Only move! Black has to bite the bullet by further weakening his pawn structure and king safety by taking this greedy computer recommended approach! }
12. Nb3
{ Now that we have given up another pawn to weaken Black's kingside beyond repair, It was time to stop caring about the material and get the party started :@@EndBracket@@. }
12... dxc3
{ Ok now, he doesn't have an option but to take here :@@EndBracket@@. } 13.
bxc3
{ Time to take stock - We are two pawns down @@StartBracket@@seriously stop counting the material @@EndBracket@@, but we have the open b-file and lots of juicy targets for our minor and major pieces. When the time is ripe we will start picking the loosely placed Black's pawns. }
13... Ng6
{ Trying to finish development and hopefully ask us some questions about the e5-pawn.   13...Qc7  will transpose to the mainlines after  14.Rb1  Ng6  . }
14. Rb1
{ With this move, the first phase of basic development is over. The next phase will be to improve our pieces and put them where they will exert maximum pressure against our enemy. }
14... Qc7 { Moving away from any future discovered threats along the b-file. }
15. Nbd4
{ Gawain stops here giving full compensation which is true, but I feel it is still too early to make assumptions and let us take the plunge into the madness! }
15... Rg8
{ What could be more natural than to use the recently opened g-file? } 16. Nxc6
{ A necessary exchange to bring the next knight to d4. } 16... Bxc6
{ In this line Black can't afford to think about Qxc6 or bxc6 both have different shortcomings for example Qxc6 is met by Ng5 while bxc6 is met by c4 both giving us the advantage. }
17. Nd4
{ Threatening to take on h5 and reduce our material deficit by one pawn :@@EndBracket@@. }
17... Bd7
{ Attacking c3-pawn and forcing White to waste a tempo defending before he can play Qxh5.   17...h4  18.Qh5  with full compensation and we can continue with ideas like Nf3-Ng5. }
18. Bd2
{ With cool compensation and once again we need to repeat the same idea if Black tries to be very ambitious by taking on e5. }
18... Nxe5 { No guts no glory? - Hammer. } 19. Bf4
{ Same concept as in the previous line. } 19... Bd6 { Forced. } 20. Qxh5
{ The queen occupies the most annoying square for our enemy. } 20... Nf3+
{ The liberation point. } 21. Qxf3 Bxf4
{ Black has the bishop pair, though in this position it doesn't matter one bit! }
22. c4
{ Black needs to show some insane defensive skills to equalize here. The pressure along the h1-a8 diagonal coupled with our active army is going to be a nightmare for Black. }
*

