13. Qe2
{ Due to the looming threat of h5 which would send the g6-knight back to where he came from, Black has to take drastic measures. }
13... f6
{ This ends up being quite risky as now the king's safety is permanently compromised and the extra pawn can't compensate for this defect until the end of the game : @@EndBracket@@. }
14. exf6 gxf6 { Here Anish only considers  15.c4  . } 15. Rb1
{ This is an idea, which I also found independently, only to discover later that Richard/ Simon already recommend this in their Grandmaster Gambits 1.e4 :@@EndBracket@@. I think given a choice I would definitely prefer White as Black needs to be very careful and has to play precisely if he doesn't want to get into trouble due to his weak king, which doesn't have any safe house and the amazing White army who are ready for a fight on all fronts! }
15... Bd6
{ The only move otherwise, the Black king will come under fire on the e-file. Somehow this hasn't been checked by anyone yet.   Also it is important to note that  15...O-O-O  is met by the deadly  16.Bxa6  bxa6  17.Nc5  gaining a huge advantage due to the Qxa6 threat which is very difficult to stop. }
16. Nbd4 Nce5 { Trying to reduce the pressure along e-file. } 17. Nxe5 Nxe5 18.
Qh5+
{ Black loses his castling rights and has to stay on e7 waiting to be smashed along the e-file with an eventual f4 after due preparation. }
