{ I found it surprising that most of the lines which are possible in the mainline arising from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2p5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  d5  3.Nc3  dxe4  4.Nxe4  just don't work here! I guess it is the power of the 'Two knights' defense where piece play is the main factor! }
4... g6
{ This edition of the fianchetto is not the best as White has the opportunity to develop his f1-bishop at the most active location possible! }
5. Bc4
{ Black's only weakness is the f7-point and hence the bishop is ideally placed on c4. }
5... Nf6 6. Nxf6+ { Doubling Black's pawns and creating a central majority. }
6... exf6 7. O-O
{ White has the upper hand, thanks to the fact that Black can't fianchetto his bishop to g7 because of the check on e1. Additionally, I don't think he has sufficient play for giving us an extra pawn in the center/queenside. }
