2. Nf3 d5 { This was the point of playing 1...c6 after all :@@EndBracket@@! }
3. Nc3
{ The Two Knights defense! In this line, we give priority to piece play instead of building a pawn center! After many hours of research on literally most of the course lines, I finally made my conclusion that this was indeed the ideal way to fight for advantage! }
3... dxe4 { One of the topical ways to fight for equality. } 4. Nxe4
{ I found it surprising that most of the lines which are possible in the mainline arising from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2p5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  d5  3.Nc3  dxe4  4.Nxe4  just don't work here! I guess it is the power of the 'Two knights' defense where piece play is the main factor! }
4... Nf6
{ This was the invention of the 21st century! Black doesn't mind doubling his pawn center which helps in the safety of this king and gives rise to active piece play on the open lines. }
5. Qe2
{ We are not gonna allow Black such easy life after all! The fight for initiative continues and Black has to decide about the incoming Nxf6 trade. }
5... Bg4
{ A very natural and active place for the development of the bishop with one minor issue... }
6. h3
{ In this line we love the bishop pair :@@EndBracket@@, hence once again we give Black the dilemma. }
6... Bxf3 { This has been recommended by Logozar in his Chessable course. } 7.
Nxf6+ { Ruining Black's pawn structure before taking on f3. } 7... gxf6
{ Now Black has three pawn islands, while we have only two. The h-pawn especially is Black's main source of concern. }
8. Qxf3 { We have the bishop pair which gives us free rein. } 8... Qd5
{ Black's strategy is starting to take shape. He would like to exchange the queens and hope to defend the slightly worse endgame. Though I am not sure how many players would prefer to do such a boring and difficult task of passive defense for a long time... }
9. Be2
{ Making sure that Black has to give up a tempo and help us with the activation of the light-squared bishop if Black wants to desperately exchange the queens! }
9... Nd7
{ Black continues to believe in his solid plan. The knight protects the f6-pawn and prepares the e6 move which will help to control the light squares. }
10. b3 { The cowboy way to activate the dark-squared bishop. } 10... e6 11. Bb2
{ Black has many ways to continue here, but unfortunately none of them give any relief. }
11... Qxf3
{ Comp feels this is the best way for Black.   11...Bd6  This was featured in one of the online games of my friend Abdulla Murad who managed to win against a higher-rated opponent. This just shows how difficult this line is for Black.  12.d4!  improving over the game and taking the center with a firm hand. We can continue with O-O-O and c4 with a better position, while Black always has to watch out for the d5-break.   11...Rg8  12.g4  with a  slight advantage as Black can't untangle his doubled f-pawns and has to suffer with it for all eternity. }
12. Bxf3
{ In the future, we can elongate the f3-bishop's reach with the queenside b4-b5 pawn storm. }
12... h5 { This artificial way is the idea of the computer. } 13. d4
{ Fighting for the center and slowly, but surely preparing d5 in the future. }
13... Bg7 14. O-O-O
{ We have a nice endgame advantage with two interesting breaks with c4-d5 and b4-b5 with both containing lot of potential. Black has to take up a defensive stance and keep an eye on our plans without having any plan of his own. }
