1... c6
{ The Caro-Kann Defense is one of my personal favorites as I scored a memorable 23-move victory over Kryvoruchko Yuri. This opening is named after the English player Horatio Caro and the Austrian player Marcus Kann, who analyzed it in 1886. It was a significant moment in its history and marked the beginning of this solid opening which can be molded according to the preference of the player!It is an opening that can be played and mastered by both aggressive/positional players. Do not be fooled by its appearance, many great players have fallen victim to it :@@EndBracket@@. Erwin's epic course was one of my earliest relationships with Chessable. Although I loved it with all my heart, I had to fight my personal feelings to find a clear way to advantage. In the end, I think I managed to do the impossible and cracked Erwin's bulletproof analysis! }
2. Nf3 d5 { This was the point of playing 1...c6 after all :@@EndBracket@@! }
3. Nc3
{ The Two Knights defense! In this line, we give priority to piece play instead of building a pawn center! After many hours of research on literally most of the course lines, I finally made my conclusion that this was indeed the ideal way to fight for advantage! }
3... dxe4 { One of the topical ways to fight for equality. } 4. Nxe4
{ I found it surprising that most of the lines which are possible in the mainline arising from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2p5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  d5  3.Nc3  dxe4  4.Nxe4  just don't work here! I guess it is the power of the 'Two knights' defense where piece play is the main factor! }
4... Nf6
{ This was the invention of the 21st century! Black doesn't mind doubling his pawn center which helps in the safety of this king and gives rise to active piece play on the open lines. }
5. Qe2
{ We are not gonna allow Black such easy life after all! The fight for initiative continues and Black has to decide about the incoming Nxf6 trade. }
5... Nxe4
{ Avoiding the doubling of the pawns as taking back with the g-pawn, while weakening the h7-pawn was never in Black's plan! }
6. Qxe4
{ This is an annoying position for Black, he has many ways to fight for equality...but none of them fully does the job! }
6... Nd7
{ Black wants to play Nf6 and then slowly develop his pieces. This is definitely the most challenging attempt and I had tried it myself against Vallejo Pons. }
7. d4
{ At the cost of exchanging one pair of knights, we have managed to gain some control over the center and position. I like this approach more than the tempting  7.Bc4  which is based on a cheapo after  7...Nf6  8.Ne5  .  Although it is a cool idea, I feel objectively Black can equalize there. }
7... Nf6 8. Qf4
{ This is the 3rd most popular move in the position, but in my opinion, it is the strongest and gives the slight advantage without too many hassles. The queen is trying to find a place where she won't be troubled by a future exchange of her counterpart. }
8... g6
{ This form of fianchetto is always decent, but it is something which can never trouble us as we can cooly continue with the mobilization of our forces and can chill due to the potential outpost on e5, followed by play along the e- and d-lines. }
9. Bd3
{ Fighting against Bf5 which might turn out to be a good spot for the outcast on c8. }
9... Bg7 10. O-O
{ Long castling is not advisable here, since the alternative with O-O is just simple and very good. When you have a simple way to get an advantage, it doesn't make sense to break your head with a complicated alternative where the conclusion won't be certain. }
10... O-O 11. Re1
{ We have a nice position and can create play with ideas like Qh4 followed by Bh6, the f3-knight can be put on e5 where it will be powerfully placed. Once again, Black's main source of issues in this system is associated with his lack of active play and continuing annoyance with the bishop on c8 which still needs some purpose in the game! }
