1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... c6
{ The Caro-Kann Defense is one of my personal favorites as I scored a memorable 23-move victory over Kryvoruchko Yuri. This opening is named after the English player Horatio Caro and the Austrian player Marcus Kann, who analyzed it in 1886. It was a significant moment in its history and marked the beginning of this solid opening which can be molded according to the preference of the player!It is an opening that can be played and mastered by both aggressive/positional players. Do not be fooled by its appearance, many great players have fallen victim to it :@@EndBracket@@. Erwin's epic course was one of my earliest relationships with Chessable. Although I loved it with all my heart, I had to fight my personal feelings to find a clear way to advantage. In the end, I think I managed to do the impossible and cracked Erwin's bulletproof analysis! }
2. Nf3 d5 { This was the point of playing 1...c6 after all :@@EndBracket@@! }
3. Nc3
{ The Two Knights defense! In this line, we give priority to piece play instead of building a pawn center! After many hours of research on literally most of the course lines, I finally made my conclusion that this was indeed the ideal way to fight for advantage! }
3... a6 { A funny move which must be met with energetic play! } 4. d4
{ When Black is joking around playing around with pawn moves, it is time we take the center firmly under control and make Black regret the fact that he wasted an entire move on playing something silly like 3...a6 instead of fighting for the center :@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Bg4
{ Black is playing the mainline of Caro-Kann with the inserted a6 move which doesn't help Black in any way :@@EndBracket@@. }
5. h3
{ Continuing in the same energetic way! Not giving Black any time to respite. }
5... Bxf3
{ In this line, Black doesn't have the luxury of giving up the bishop pair as we have already achieved d4 capturing the center. }
6. Qxf3 dxe4
{ If Black plays slowly then we can continue with Bf4 and O-O-O leaving us with a big advantage. Any counter-attacking plans with b5 can be met with Bd3 and exd5 with play in the center. }
7. Nxe4
{ Of course, we are not gonna waste our time with Qe3 or Qxe4 which protects the d4-pawn. Instead we bring the knight to a powerful central post. }
7... Qxd4
{ Sadly Black doesn't have any other way to justify his opening concept. } 8.
Be3
{ In the life of a gambiteer... we can't concern ourselves with the counting of material. Our main objective is the king on e8! }
8... Qxb2
{ Once again Black doesn't have much choice! Not taking the pawn on b2 would be met with Rd1 or O-O-O which will depend on where the queen goes! }
9. Bc4
{ A brilliant double rook sacrifice!! Giving up the a1-rook and the h1-rook... if that is what it will take to get to the king on e8! }
9... Qxa1+
{ I felt it would be more fun to show the greedy rook grab.   9...Qb4+  10.Nd2  Protecting the c4-bishop.  10...e6  Preventing Qxf7+  11.O-O  Getting the king to safety with the idea to play Rab1 next with a big advantage and a powerful initiative. }
10. Ke2 { The threat of Rxa1 and Qxf7 turns out to be deadly for Black. } 10...
Qxh1 { When you say A... } 11. Qxf7+
{ With a mate in 4! Due to the combined might of the queen, bishops and the knight! }
