{ The Two Knights defense! In this line, we give priority to piece play instead of building a pawn center! After many hours of research on literally most of the course lines, I finally made my conclusion that this was indeed the ideal way to fight for advantage! }
3... d4
{ This tempting pawn push doesn't sit well with the caro-kann strategy since Black needs to waste another tempo to protect the d4-pawn which gives us the time to gain the upperhand and the initiative. }
4. Ne2
{ Going for the d4-pawn and we need to make Black regret making this premature advance. }
4... c5
{ Black needs just one more move with Nc6 to have a completely fine game. } 5.
c3
{ Attacking the center before Black has the time to comfortably protect it. }
5... dxc3
{ The only way to save the pawn but at the cost of giving up the central control. }
6. Nxc3
{ Our main threat in this line is to achieve d4 after which there is no doubt about our superiority. }
6... e6 7. d4
{ After this, Black will have take up the defensive role and must spend the rest of the game fighting against our threats. }
7... cxd4 { Otherwise, we continue advancing in the center with d5. } 8. Qxd4
{ If you don't want to enter the endgame, then  8.Nxd4  is an option that is equally good. }
8... Qxd4 9. Nxd4
{ with a clear advantage in the endgame due to the threat of Nb5 which forces Black to waste another tempo with a6 to prevent it. We can continue improving our advantage with Be3, Be2 followed by f3. Ideally, we can place our rooks on c1 and d1, while our king can be well placed on f2. }
