{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... c6
{ The Caro-Kann Defense is one of my personal favorites as I scored a memorable 23-move victory over Kryvoruchko Yuri. This opening is named after the English player Horatio Caro and the Austrian player Marcus Kann, who analyzed it in 1886. It was a significant moment in its history and marked the beginning of this solid opening which can be molded according to the preference of the player!It is an opening that can be played and mastered by both aggressive/positional players. Do not be fooled by its appearance, many great players have fallen victim to it :@@EndBracket@@. Erwin's epic course was one of my earliest relationships with Chessable. Although I loved it with all my heart, I had to fight my personal feelings to find a clear way to advantage. In the end, I think I managed to do the impossible and cracked Erwin's bulletproof analysis! }
2. Nf3 d5 { This was the point of playing 1...c6 after all :@@EndBracket@@! }
3. Nc3
{ The Two Knights defense! In this line, we give priority to piece play instead of building a pawn center! After many hours of research on literally most of the course lines, I finally made my conclusion that this was indeed the ideal way to fight for advantage! }
3... Bg4
{ This is Erwin's recommendation and although it is very solid, I feel we can claim a slight edge which is already a big achievement in this biased 0.00 computer era :@@EndBracket@@. }
4. h3
{ Politely asking Black to give up the bishop pair or be objectively worse! }
4... Bxf3 5. Qxf3
{ To be honest, I wouldn't mind stopping the analysis here :@@EndBracket@@. We have the bishop pair and most likely will win the battle for the center control. What more do we want in life? }
5... e6 6. Be2
{ A simple developing move, asking Black to define his piece placement. } 6...
Nd7
{ is another passive way to finish development, not concerning with the prevention of our ambitious plans! }
7. d4 { No need to restrain ourselves anymore! } 7... dxe4
{ At some point, Black will have to exchange on e4 if he wants to develop his kingside knight. }
8. Nxe4 Ngf6
{ Black having less space would like to exchange as many pieces as possible. }
9. Nd2
{ A genius retreat which surprisingly has been played only once! I think after this move which keeps our knight, we have a solid advantage due to the bishop pair and the d2-knight will try to go for the places where the bishops can't or don't want to go :@@EndBracket@@. }
