[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Philidor"]
[Black "4...Nbd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... d6
{ The primitive 'Philidor Defense'. Black literally doesn't care about space and just wants to finish his plans at his own pace with the intention to lash out after all the preparations are complete. I had to make sure I got a good position out of the positions recommended by Pepe in his Chessable course.I would also add not to be fooled by the passive nature of this line. Many lines contain a lot of venom and we must act with precision to stop all of Black's counterplay. In this line we necessarily don't need to show any plans, just controlling Black's idea is enough to guarantee a stable advantage. }
2. d4
{ The best move, I had also tried the enterprising  2.Nc3  with the idea to meet  2...e5  3.f4  taking the game to King's Gambit type positions which many of the Philidor fans won't like. I think it is a good alternative to research for interested readers! }
2... Nf6 3. Nc3
{ Although  3.Bd3  was a tempting option to continue with  3...e5  4.d5  .  In the end, I decided we needn't avoid the mainstream theory and go for the mainlines with my guided approach! }
3... e5 4. Nf3
{ Supporting the center, the endgame arising after  4.dxe5  dxe5  5.Qxd8  Kxd8  is a very good alternative for people who like slightly better endgames. In my personal opinion having White's pieces and more space advantage, it is better to avoid a lot of exchanges which might reduce our advantage by a tiny bit. }
4... Nbd7
{ is a major branch dubbed as 'Hanham variation' where Black avoids giving up the center without a fight and wants to continue his plans with Be7-O-O-c6. }
5. Rg1
{ Welcome to the jungle! This very strong idea, designed to prepare g4, became popular during the covid/online era and is even more deadly than immediate 5.g4. The golden principle of 'The threat is stronger than the execution' holds here. }
5... c6 6. g4
{ The g-pawn feels so much stronger with a mighty rook backing him up! } 6...
h6
{ Stopping our g-pawn in its tracks!   Fianchetto with  6...g6  just allows us to gain too much on the kingside giving us a big advantage after  7.g5  Nh5  8.Be3  followed by Qd2 and O-O-O. }
7. Be3
{ We are happy on the kingside for the time being and want to focus on finishing the development on the queenside. }
7... b5
{ Gaining space on the queenside and preparing to annoy the c3-knight with b4. }
8. a3
{ Stopping the b-pawn in its tracks, just like how Black did it :@@EndBracket@@! Giving Black a taste of his own medicine :@@EndBracket@@! }
8... Bb7 9. h4
{ Now that the situation is stable and development is better, it is time for Phase 2: Assault along the g-file. }
9... h5
{ A cool concept, Black hopes to create an outpost on g4 for his knight...if we go for g5. }
10. gxh5
{ Not giving Black what he wants, opening up the g-file even at the cost of slightly weakening the h-pawn. Such trivial things don't matter when the struggle is for bigger goals like keeping the initiative! }
10... Rxh5 11. Be2
{ Using the h5-rook as the catalyst for developing one more piece. } 11... Rh8
{ 'Better safe than sorry!' } 12. Qd2
{ All the obligations have been satisfied, it is time to get the king to safety and then unleash chaos on the enemy king with our more mobile army! }
*

