{ Supporting the center, the endgame arising after  4.dxe5  dxe5  5.Qxd8  Kxd8  is a very good alternative for people who like slightly better endgames. In my personal opinion having White's pieces and more space advantage, it is better to avoid a lot of exchanges which might reduce our advantage by a tiny bit. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4
{ We have achieved a static advantage due to the superior center pawn on e4 compared to its counterpart on d6. }
5... Be7
{ Black's strategy is similar to the 'compressed spring' method, where he hopes one day when the position opens up all his pieces will come to life with renewed power and purpose. @@StartBracket@@SPOILER ALERT: This will never work against a well prepared and cautious person armed with our course :@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@.   5...Nc6  6.Bb5  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  lines. }
6. g3
{ This setup involving the fianchetto is one of the soundest replies to the Philidor and steers the game into positional territories where Black needs to find creative ways to create counterplay to avoid getting completely bamboozled by White. }
6... d5
{ Black is striking in the center before we can get the bishop to g2... Such behavior will not be tolerated :@@EndBracket@@! }
7. e5 { Only way is to move forward and avoid exchanges! } 7... Ng4 8. Bg2
{ Priority to finishing the development! } 8... Nxe5
{ is the most human move. } 9. Qe2
{ Gaining a crucial tempo, attacking the e5-knight before going for the d5-pawn. }
9... Nec6
{ 9...Nbc6  10.Nxc6  The simplest solution.  10...Nxc6  11.Nxd5  We gain the bishop pair thanks to the pin along the e-file, this advantage is enough to win the game :@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Be3
{ Developing with tempo and the d5-pawn is sadly ignored by both sides :@@EndBracket@@. Next we would like to take on d5 with the c3-knight. }
10... Nxd4
{ This and castling are very similar in nature.  10...O-O  11.Nxd5  Nxd4  12.Bxd4  should transpose to the mainline. }
11. Bxd4 O-O { Black is the first one to get the king to safety. } 12. Nxd5
{ Ideally, we would like to spend a tempo on finishing castling first but unfortunately, we don't have that luxury since we are a pawn down. }
12... Bb4+ { Black is starting to use the fact that our king is still on e1. }
13. Nxb4 { Other moves would allow Re8. } 13... Qxd4 14. c3
{ Followed by O-O offers a simple edge, if you are not into gambits :@@EndBracket@@. }
