{ Black's strategy is similar to the 'compressed spring' method, where he hopes one day when the position opens up all his pieces will come to life with renewed power and purpose. @@StartBracket@@SPOILER ALERT: This will never work against a well prepared and cautious person armed with our course :@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@.   5...Nc6  6.Bb5  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  lines. }
6. g3
{ This setup involving the fianchetto is one of the soundest replies to the Philidor and steers the game into positional territories where Black needs to find creative ways to create counterplay to avoid getting completely bamboozled by White. }
6... O-O 7. Bg2
{ The bishop is very well placed on g2, overprotecting the e4-pawn keeping an eye on the safety of the kingside while also preventing any future ideas from Black. }
7... Re8
{ Black is preparing the retreat of the bishop to f8, though in principle such a slow plan can hardly bother us.   7...Nc6  This is just downright bad as it allows us to weaken Black's pawn structure permanently.  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.O-O  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p1n2/8/3NP3/2N3P1/PPP2P1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  lines. See the comments on how the play might continue in that line.   7...c6  8.O-O  One of our main concepts is to play b3 followed by Bb2 and then proceed to squeeze Black into submission.  8...Re8  9.h3  with a transposition to 8...c6 lines. }
8. O-O c6
{ This is Dubov's direction where he even ended up beating the strongest player on the planet - World Champion Magnus Carlsen. }
9. h3 { This is always an useful move preventing Bg4 or Ng4 moves from Black. }
9... Bf8 10. g4 { This direct approach used by Karjakin looks best. } 10... h6
{ So far we have been following @@StartBracket@@Karjakin-Dubov Rapid 2020@@EndBracket@@. }
11. Re1
{ Our plan is to continue with a4 followed by b3-Bb2 or Bf4-Qd2. We have to decide based on Black's piece placement. }
