[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Pack the Pirc"]
[Black "3...c6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... d6
{ Black is keeping all his options open with this 'Philidor style' move order. }
2. d4
{ The best move, I had also tried the enterprising  2.Nc3  with the idea to meet  2...e5  3.f4  taking the game to King's Gambit type positions which many of the Philidor fans won't like. I think it is a good alternative to research for interested readers! }
2... Nf6
{ Black attacks the e4-pawn and makes sure that we can't go to lines involving c4 or c3 systems. }
3. Nc3
{ Supporting the center and the knight could come under future threats like a6-b5 or c6-b5 threatening to win the e4-pawn with b4. }
3... c6 { This is a bad line and frankly shouldn't challenge us. } 4. Nf3
{ I feel this is at least as good as Wesley's and Sethu's recommendation of 4. f4...if not stronger :@@EndBracket@@. Continuing our development and asking Black to transpose back to Pirc with 4...g6. }
4... g6 5. Bg5
{ Which is the most aggressive square for the bishop? A: The g5-square } 5...
Qa5
{ Black is hoping to find peace due to the pin along the a5-e1 diagonal.   5...Bg7  will transpose to the Pircmainline. }
6. Bd2 { Breaking the pin and asking the queen to go back accepting defeat! }
6... Qc7
{ Once again Black hopes to achieve e5 and hopefully get some hope... } 7. e5
{ In this line, the entire fight revolves around the control of e5 square... whoever wins it, gets the advantage. In fact, we are ready to sacrifice a pawn to achieve that goal! }
7... dxe5 { Black can't afford to let a pawn on e5 for long. } 8. dxe5
{ This feels stronger than  8.Nxe5  due to the continuous threat on Black's pieces. }
8... Ng4
{ Black feels we may have missed something as there doesn't seem to be a way to save the e5-pawn. }
9. Qe2 Bg7
{ Black is very happy with himself, he is developing by attacking our central pawn. }
10. Bf4 { Continuing to protect our stronghold! } 10... Nd7
{ Black has to keep on attacking e5, even one move delay would allow us to kick the g4-knight with h3. }
11. O-O-O
{ Fine, you can take the e5-pawn! We will win back the lost material with interest :@@EndBracket@@. }
11... Ndxe5
{ Finally, Black's relentless efforts have been rewarded and he has won a pawn! }
12. Kb1
{ A cool-headed move preventing any Nd3+ ideas that would allow Black to escape from the deadly pin along the h2-b8 diagonal. Our threat is to play Re1 followed by h3 next leading to a big advantage! Let's not forget that Black's king is still in the center! }
