{ Black is keeping all his options open with this 'Philidor style' move order. }
2. d4
{ The best move, I had also tried the enterprising  2.Nc3  with the idea to meet  2...e5  3.f4  taking the game to King's Gambit type positions which many of the Philidor fans won't like. I think it is a good alternative to research for interested readers! }
2... Nf6
{ Black attacks the e4-pawn and makes sure that we can't go to lines involving c4 or c3 systems. }
3. Nc3
{ Supporting the center and the knight could come under future threats like a6-b5 or c6-b5 threatening to win the e4-pawn with b4. }
3... g6 4. Bg5
{ Staying very principled and aggressive! Being a loyal fan of 4.Be3 for all these years, I must say that I am surprised that this move is the 4th most popular move. }
4... Bg7
{ The bishop makes its grand appearance on the g7-square. We are well-advised to take precautions against tricks along the a1-h8 diagonal. }
5. Nf3
{ Deviating from Sethu's direction. He has recommended 5.Qd2 followed by f4, while I am more in favor of quick kingside development with Nf3. Practically this feels more dangerous as we are not making any weakness and preparing the central e5 advance if Black is not careful. }
5... O-O
{ Braveheart! Black is castling into the line of fire! He is hoping that his center/queenside counterplay will be in time to save him! }
6. Qd2 { Time to go for the kingside attack with Bh6 followed by h4-h5! } 6...
Bg4 7. h4
{ Show no restraints! Our opponents should regret the day they chose to play Pirc against us!! }
7... c5 8. d5
{ Keeping the structure closed and maintaining the space advantage. A necessary skill for an attacker to develop is prophylactic play against the opponent's counterplay, this is essential to ensure that our attack continues without any sudden dramatic turnarounds! }
8... Qb6 { At first the computer is optimistic about Black's chances. } 9. Nh2
{ Getting rid of the bishop on g4 which was stopping our h5 plan.   Taking on  b2  with  9...Qxb2  would end up losing a piece after  10.Rb1  Qa3  11.Rb3!  and then proceeding to take on f6 winning the g4-bishop. }
9... Bc8 10. Rb1
{ The b2-pawn is a key link in keeping our position together, hence it is worth spending a tempo to protect it. Also please don't fall for cheapos like  10.O-O-O  Nxe4  and Black wins on the spot using the battery along the a1-h8 diagonal. }
10... h5
{ This might end up hurting Black more, since when we achieve the g4 break... Black's kingside is going to fall off like a deck of cards. }
11. Be2
{ Followed by O-O and then preparing the kingside attack at our leisure. } *

