[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Modern Medicine"]
[Black "2...c6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... g6
{ The Modern Defense... The name was derived from Wikipedia as the author was too lazy to find the origin story :@@EndBracket@@. Black wants to give up the center and wants to finish his development with the hope that one day when he strikes back, White won't be in a position to control the outcome of the center battle.I have played it myself with good results in shorter time controls as I feel it is very easy to handle and many times White players end up underestimating the latent potential of this system. This is something we won't be doing! I think the approach I suggest is bulletproof and will make sure that you will get an easy advantage doesn't matter in what time control you will face this! }
2. d4
{ NO NEED TO ASK AGAIN! We happily take the center and will have the final laugh :@@EndBracket@@. }
2... c6
{ This poor imitation of Caro-Kann is just horrible as we haven't committed Nc3 yet... }
3. c4 { Going for maximum control of the central squares. } 3... d5
{ Black has to strike before we can play Nc3.   3...Bg7  4.Nc3  gives us a big advantage as we have firm control over the center and can continue developing with Nf3-Be2-O-O with easy play. Black's setup resembles Kings-Indian where the move c6 doesn't go well with the spirit of KID! }
4. cxd5
{ It was also possible to play direct  4.e5  with a similar fate for Black. }
4... cxd5 5. e5
{ I think now it looks like a horrible version of the French Advance :@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Nc6 6. Nc3
{ Black doesn't have the firepower to challenge our powerful center with d4-e5. }
6... f6
{ Other moves will be too slow. Both Bg7 and Nh6 can be met with the prophylactic 7.h3 preventing Bg4 ideas and then proceeding to develop with Nf3 with stable support over the central pawns with a nice space advantage. }
7. Nf3
{ Supporting the center and fxe5 is too early for Black due to his poor development. }
7... Bg7 8. Bb5
{ This way we keep we end the fight for the e5-square and Black has to accept to play a passive worse position. }
8... Bg4 { Black's last resort. } 9. h3
{ Forcing Black to give up the bishop pair. } 9... Bxf3 10. Qxf3
{ Threatening to win the d5-pawn. } 10... e6 11. O-O
{ Finishing the development while Black still needs two more moves to do it which gives us the time to activate our forces at the best possible locations cementing our advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
