{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... g6
{ The Modern Defense... The name was derived from Wikipedia as the author was too lazy to find the origin story :@@EndBracket@@. Black wants to give up the center and wants to finish his development with the hope that one day when he strikes back, White won't be in a position to control the outcome of the center battle.I have played it myself with good results in shorter time controls as I feel it is very easy to handle and many times White players end up underestimating the latent potential of this system. This is something we won't be doing! I think the approach I suggest is bulletproof and will make sure that you will get an easy advantage doesn't matter in what time control you will face this! }
2. d4
{ NO NEED TO ASK AGAIN! We happily take the center and will have the final laugh :@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Bg7
{ The sniper is ready from g7 to put maximum pressure on d4 and along the h8-a1 diagonal. }
3. Nf3
{ This is the second most popular move that has been outlasted by 3.Nc3 for no apparent reason. I think in principle people don't want to allow 3...d5 options for Black and want to have the option of going the English Attack style ideas like Be3-Qd2-f3 which in my opinion gives Black the necessary time to create his counterplay.In this course, I would like to endorse the approach with 3.Nf3 which is mainly aimed against a6 systems which can be brutally met with c4 killing Black's entire setup involving b5-Bb7. I am reminded of the quote 'People often fear what they don't understand', I feel it is fitting for 3.Nf3. }
3... c6
{ Black is mixing the concepts of the Caro-Kann and Modern to make an abomination of both systems :@@EndBracket@@. It is a sneaky move order and we mustn't be fooled into thinking that Black only wants 4...d5, he can also do 4...d6 reverting to normal Modern lines :@@EndBracket@@. }
4. h3
{ A nice prophylactic move keeping all our trump cards! Avoiding Nc3 @@StartBracket@@since we want to play c4 first before going Nc3@@EndBracket@@ and at the same time it was necessary to make a useful move which will be helpful for us if Black decided to be greedy by suddenly switching his plan from d5 to d6. }
4... d5
{ Falling for our concept, but we can hardly blame Black for not understanding our idea! After all, this was the main idea behind 3...c6. }
5. e5
{ Since we have already taken the necessary precautions against Bg4 ideas thanks to the epic prophylaxis with h3...We can now claim the center with this powerful space-grabbing move which cuts into Black's piece development and gives us the undeniable space advantage. }
5... f6
{ Black decides to strike in the center without finishing his development! } 6.
Bd3
{ We are people armed with the classical foundation of chess. Hence we do follow the golden principles of finishing our development before getting into any dirty business :@@EndBracket@@ of destroying our opposition! }
6... fxe5 7. dxe5
{ Continuing to bully the knight on g8 and not letting him have an easy life. }
7... Nh6 { Hoping to find some role for the knight on h6. } 8. O-O
{ We have the solid advantage due to our strong pawn on e5 which once again cuts into Black's coordination. We can continue with Re1 followed by c4 and Nc3 putting pressure on d5 to provoke Black into playing e6 which will weaken the f6-square. }
