3... c6
{ Black is mixing the concepts of the Caro-Kann and Modern to make an abomination of both systems :@@EndBracket@@. It is a sneaky move order and we mustn't be fooled into thinking that Black only wants 4...d5, he can also do 4...d6 reverting to normal Modern lines :@@EndBracket@@. }
4. h3
{ A nice prophylactic move keeping all our trump cards! Avoiding Nc3 @@StartBracket@@since we want to play c4 first before going Nc3@@EndBracket@@ and at the same time it was necessary to make a useful move which will be helpful for us if Black decided to be greedy by suddenly switching his plan from d5 to d6. }
4... d5
{ Falling for our concept, but we can hardly blame Black for not understanding our idea! After all, this was the main idea behind 3...c6. }
5. e5
{ Since we have already taken the necessary precautions against Bg4 ideas thanks to the epic prophylaxis with h3...We can now claim the center with this powerful space-grabbing move which cuts into Black's piece development and gives us the undeniable space advantage. }
5... Nh6
{ The black knight is resisting the injustice done to him and develops through another path to break with f6 one day to put pressure on the man responsible for his current plight. }
6. Bd3
{ The ideal location for the bishop where it is actively placed and we needn't worry about the bishop exchange with Bf5 due to our huge space advantage. }
6... f6 { Fighting for his rights in the game! } 7. exf6
{ The simplest way to advantage. } 7... exf6
{ Black's discoordinated army, his passively placed knight on h6 and the bishop on g7 are some of the reasons why computer likes the White side a lot! }
8. O-O { Re1+ incoming! } 8... O-O
{ Just in time before Black's situation would become highly difficult. } 9. c4
{ What Black would give to transport the h6-knight to e7. Due to the current affairs happening in the center, Black is unable to deal with the pressure and assault on the center. He has to assume a passive role in the coming middlegame battle. }
9... Be6 10. Re1
{ A cool move attacking the bishop on e6 with tempo before making any decision about the c4-pawn. }
10... dxc4 { is a greedy alternative that doesn't work. } 11. Bxg6
{ A stunning intermezzo which guarantees our advantage as the blow is ruining Black's kingside forever irrespective of whether he takes on g6 allowing Re6 or protecting the bishop which would permanently ruin his kingside protection. }
