{ This is the second most popular move that has been outlasted by 3.Nc3 for no apparent reason. I think in principle people don't want to allow 3...d5 options for Black and want to have the option of going the English Attack style ideas like Be3-Qd2-f3 which in my opinion gives Black the necessary time to create his counterplay.In this course, I would like to endorse the approach with 3.Nf3 which is mainly aimed against a6 systems which can be brutally met with c4 killing Black's entire setup involving b5-Bb7. I am reminded of the quote 'People often fear what they don't understand', I feel it is fitting for 3.Nf3. }
3... d6
{ Black controls the center and prepares ideas like Bg4 and e5, when the time is right. }
4. Be3
{ Continuing to toy with the move orders and asking Black to decide on his queenside plans. }
4... Nd7
{ Although this is a typical knight move, it seriously weakens the e6-square. }
5. Bc4 { Immediately pointing out the drawback of Black's last move. } 5... e6
{ Black is forced to stop our threats with this unnatural move which ruins Black's entire strategy. }
6. Nc3 { Getting our army ready for the middlegame. } 6... a6
{ Black is desperately trying to gain some play with b5 followed by Bb7. } 7.
a4
{ Putting an end to Black's feeble ambitions. The future looks quite depressing for him due to less space and lack of active play for his pieces while our center looks stable. }
