{ Preparing to castle next and Black is left struggling to find a way to battle our c4-d4-e4 center. }
7... Ng4
{ Black is hoping to annoy us with this knight jump, but like in the 6...Ng4 variation...We are not bothered by this at all!   A@@EndBracket@@  7...e5  Nakamura used this idea in a blitz game against Svidler trying to take the game into Kings-Indian type territories.  8.dxe5  Opening the d-file.  8...dxe5  9.Qb3!  Not exchanging the queens and keeping a good advantage thanks to  Rd1  next followed by  Nd5  ideas.   B@@EndBracket@@  7...Bg4  This move should never bother us since Black is giving up the bishop pair.  8.h3  Bxf3  9.Bxf3  Threatening the deadly e5 move opening the long diagonal.  9...Nc6  Black just needs one more move i.e to play e5 and gain good control over the dark-squares.  10.d5!  Not allowing Black the time he needs!  10...Ne5  Attacking c4 and f3.  11.Be2  Preserving the bishop pair and protecting c4. We can follow with f4 next with a space advantage and the mighty bishop pair.   C@@EndBracket@@  7...c6  Black threatens to gain some play on the queenside with  b5  .  8.O-O  'We literally don't care!'.  8...b5  Threatening to win the e4-pawn with b4.  9.Nd2!  A cool retreat preventing against b4 ideas and stopping Ng4 at the same time. We have the space advantage and good center. }
8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4
{ We continue with O-O next, followed by h3 kicking the knight back. The space advantage and the center give us a free hand to do whatever we want and can play wherever we want. I will let the readers choose :@@EndBracket@@. Ideally, I would say it should be a mix of central and kingside play which would be very difficult for Black to fight against. }
