{ Continuing with 4.c5 gives away most of our advantage, hence we are happy with the two extra tempos provided by the b6-knight. }
4... d6 5. f4
{ Name: Four pawn's Attack. Mission: Destroying the enemy with extreme firepower. }
5... dxe5
{ Opening the d-file to increase the pressure on d4.   A@@EndBracket@@  5...Bf5  6.Nc3   A1@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/1n1p4/4Pb2/2PP1P2/2N5/PP4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...dxe5  7.fxe5  Nc6  8.Be3  would lead to a transposition.   A2@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/1n1p4/4Pb2/2PP1P2/2N5/PP4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  7.Nf3  dxe5  8.fxe5  is another way to reach the same position.   B@@EndBracket@@  5...e6  This is the fifth most popular move, but in my opinion, it is just horrible and passive!  6.Nc3  followed by Nf3 with a decisive advantage as Black hasn't put any effort in fighting against our plans. }
6. fxe5
{ 6.dxe5  As someone who wants to destroy our opponents using our space army, we definitely do not want to chicken out with this lame way  6...Qxd1+  7.Kxd1  Black is to be preferred in this position due to our over-stretched pawns which has only weakened our position. }
6... g6
{ Ideally Black would like to challenge our might pawn center and this is one such possibility. }
7. Nc3 Bg7 8. c5
{ The knight on b6 is slowly starting to question his existence :@@EndBracket@@. }
8... Nd5
{ If Black can stabilize his control over the d5-square, he might have a decent game. }
9. Bc4
{ A juicy spot for the bishop where it targets the f7-pawn which is a good target for us due to additional pressure which can be exerted along the f-file. }
9... c6 10. Qb3
{ Stopping the c8-bishop from easily developing and increasing the pressure along the a2-g8 diagonal. }
10... O-O 11. Nf3
{ Let's give priority to finish our development, there is no need to prove our superiority by grabbing any material! This could end badly for us since we haven't finished our development. }
11... Nxc3 12. bxc3
{ Our pawn center is so sweet and ideally it was a good time to stop here, but I decided to show one sample line: }
12... b5
{ There was no other easy way to get rid of the pressure from the bishop+queen combo. }
13. Bd3
{ and the bishop shall find its right place on e4 where it will become a monster! }
13... Na6 { Preparing a cheapo with Nc5. } 14. Be4 Be6 15. Qa3
{ Not allowing a moment's peace to Black. } 15... Qc8 16. O-O
{ Finally! At the best moment after achieving many things we could dream of, it was time to get the king to safety which secures us a big advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) The Tragic End of the Alekhine"]
[Black "2...Nd5 with 5...dxe5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... Nf6
{ An opening that was popularised by one of my favorite world champions, Alexander Alekhine who used this as part of his hypermodern approach to chess where the emphasis is on piece activity more than anything else! As much as I love this line... unfortunately I had to find the best way to end its career once and for all! }
2. e5
{ Bullying the knight and creating a strong pawn hook on e5 which cuts into Black's plans! }
2... Nd5
{ Black is trying to bait White into overextending his pawn structure... } 3.
c4
{ We just fall for it :@@EndBracket@@, we are nice people after all :@@EndBracket@@! }
3... Nb6 4. d4
{ Continuing with 4.c5 gives away most of our advantage, hence we are happy with the two extra tempos provided by the b6-knight. }
4... d6 5. f4
{ Name: Four pawn's Attack. Mission: Destroying the enemy with extreme firepower. }
5... dxe5
{ Opening the d-file to increase the pressure on d4.   A@@EndBracket@@  5...Bf5  6.Nc3   A1@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/1n1p4/4Pb2/2PP1P2/2N5/PP4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...dxe5  7.fxe5  Nc6  8.Be3  would lead to a transposition.   A2@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/1n1p4/4Pb2/2PP1P2/2N5/PP4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  7.Nf3  dxe5  8.fxe5  is another way to reach the same position.   B@@EndBracket@@  5...e6  This is the fifth most popular move, but in my opinion, it is just horrible and passive!  6.Nc3  followed by Nf3 with a decisive advantage as Black hasn't put any effort in fighting against our plans. }
6. fxe5
{ 6.dxe5  As someone who wants to destroy our opponents using our space army, we definitely do not want to chicken out with this lame way  6...Qxd1+  7.Kxd1  Black is to be preferred in this position due to our over-stretched pawns which has only weakened our position. }
6... c5
{ is a horrible line, but it is always good to know how to refute it :@@EndBracket@@! }
7. d5 { Black was forcing us to do this! } 7... e6
{ Black threatens the dangerous Qh4+. } 8. Nc3
{ Protecting the d5-pawn and also preventing Qh4-Qe4 ideas. } 8... exd5 9. cxd5
{ Our center pawns make such a nice impression. } 9... Qh4+
{ This lame attempt to exchange the queens also won't end well for Black. } 10.
g3 Qd4 { Black was putting his hopes on this move. } 11. Bb5+
{ An useful check since exchanging the light-squared bishop are in our favour. }
11... Bd7 { Otherwise Black will have to give up his castling rights. } 12. Qe2
{ Avoiding the exchange of the queens and preparing Nf3 next with a big advantage due to the powerful pawns in the center, additionally e6 is also a dangerous threat. }
12... Nxd5
{ I think only in this line, we need to know what to do. Other lines can be easily met with Nf3 controlling the situation in the center. }
13. e6 { Demolishing Black's defences. } 13... fxe6 { Only move. } 14. Qxe6+
{ The queen is looking very strong on e6 using the pin along the a4-e8 diagonal. }
14... Ne7 15. Nf3
{ with a huge attack and Black will soon suffer material losses to stop getting mated :@@EndBracket@@. }
