{ Attacking the center pawns. Lines with  6...Bf5  will reach the mainline after transposition.  7.Nc3  Nc6   7...e6  8.Nf3  Nc6  9.Be3  with a transposition to 6... Nc6.  8.Nf3  with a transposition to 6...Nc6. }
7. Be3
{ Caution is required here as the natural  7.Nf3  would allow Black to equalize immediately with  7...Bg4! }
7... Bf5
{ The bishop is sent to the most active post before the next bishop is due to make his debut via the f8-a3 diagonal. }
8. Nc3 e6 { The advances in the center by White is controlled by this move. }
9. Nf3
{ Overprotecting our strong center is always a good idea, this way our queen feels slightly more relaxed and doesn't feel burdened with the task of just protecting the d4-pawn. }
9... Bg4 { Black is trying to do some damage to our center. } 10. Be2
{ We literally don't care!! } 10... Bxf3
{ Otherwise there was no point in playing Bg4 the previous move! } 11. gxf3
{ Taking with the bishop would lose the c4-pawn. } 11... Qh4+
{ For some stupid reason...this line is quite popular, I think it is high time I end its career! }
12. Bf2
{ Forced moves are the best :@@EndBracket@@, as it removes all the confusion :@@EndBracket@@! }
12... Qf4
{ Black just needs one more move like Rd8 or O-O-O and he would start the attack on our center. }
13. c5
{ Showing our enemy who is the boss! Black won't get any time to show his plans! }
13... Nd5 14. Nxd5 exd5
{ After this recapture, our pawn on d4 is safe from the evil eyes of the a8-rook and we can proceed to show our mighty bishop pair with the added bonus of space advantage. }
15. O-O
{ Our king can be tucked into h1 and we can start our expansion plans on the queenside. The queen can be placed on d3 followed by Be3 kicking the annoying queen from f4, this will also enable our own f-pawn to advance. All these factors ensure our advantage. }
*

