{ Opening the d-file to increase the pressure on d4.   A@@EndBracket@@  5...Bf5  6.Nc3   A1@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/1n1p4/4Pb2/2PP1P2/2N5/PP4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...dxe5  7.fxe5  Nc6  8.Be3  would lead to a transposition.   A2@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/1n1p4/4Pb2/2PP1P2/2N5/PP4PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  7.Nf3  dxe5  8.fxe5  is another way to reach the same position.   B@@EndBracket@@  5...e6  This is the fifth most popular move, but in my opinion, it is just horrible and passive!  6.Nc3  followed by Nf3 with a decisive advantage as Black hasn't put any effort in fighting against our plans. }
6. fxe5
{ 6.dxe5  As someone who wants to destroy our opponents using our space army, we definitely do not want to chicken out with this lame way  6...Qxd1+  7.Kxd1  Black is to be preferred in this position due to our over-stretched pawns which has only weakened our position. }
6... Nc6
{ Attacking the center pawns. Lines with  6...Bf5  will reach the mainline after transposition.  7.Nc3  Nc6   7...e6  8.Nf3  Nc6  9.Be3  with a transposition to 6... Nc6.  8.Nf3  with a transposition to 6...Nc6. }
7. Be3
{ Caution is required here as the natural  7.Nf3  would allow Black to equalize immediately with  7...Bg4! }
7... Bf5
{ The bishop is sent to the most active post before the next bishop is due to make his debut via the f8-a3 diagonal. }
8. Nc3 e6 { The advances in the center by White is controlled by this move. }
9. Nf3
{ Overprotecting our strong center is always a good idea, this way our queen feels slightly more relaxed and doesn't feel burdened with the task of just protecting the d4-pawn. }
9... Be7
{ Well, Black really can't do anything to challenge our mighty center...so he decides to at least finish the development. }
10. Be2
{ Due to our space advantage, it is not advisable to exchange pieces with 10.Bd3. }
10... O-O 11. O-O { Step 3: King Safety. } 11... f6 { Attack on titans! } 12.
exf6 { Ruining Black's pawn structure. } 12... Bxf6
{ 12...gxf6  with the idea to keep the pawns united would seriously weaken Black's position as a whole :@@EndBracket@@.  13.Bh6  followed by d5-Nd4 ideas smashing open the center and light squares and we have a stable advantage due to many weaknesses around the black king. }
13. Qd2
{ Xiong went for 13. b3 against Duda winning an important game which won him the match in the World Cup 2019, but, later on, he switched to our mainline and I also feel it is not worth spending a tempo on over protecting c4 for the time being. }
13... Qe8
{ This has been tried by some strong players and I found that they scored reasonably well since White missed the following strong exchange of a minor piece... }
14. Bg5
{ Exchanging a pair of bishops and freeing the e3-square for the queen that eliminates any pinning ideas from Black rook along the d-file. }
14... Rd8 15. Bxf6 Rxf6 16. h3
{ The only way Black can try to disturb our d4-pawn is with ideas like Bg4 hence we just stop it and claim a big advantage! }
16... Bg6 17. Qe3
{ Followed by Rad1 next and even g4 maybe to continue dominating Black! } *

