[White "14) Scandinavian Scarecrow"]
[Black "2...Nf6 3.d4 Nxd5 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... d5
{ The Center Counter Defense is one of the coldest recorded openings as it was played between Francesc de Castellví and Narcís Vinyoles in Valencia in 1475. Analysis by Scandinavian masters in the late 19th century didn't change its status and it remained an unplayable opening for Black. Although the Scandinavian Defense has never enjoyed widespread popularity among top-flight players, I mean why should it? It gives up the center and helps White to develop his army with tempo. - Sethu's LTR  @@StartBracket@@source@@EndBracket@@.Just when all hope had been lost for this opening... one crazy guy decided to play it against the reigning World Champion Magnus Carlsen in Tata Steel 2017 and even managed to achieve a winning position... What more do you want from this opening? Abandoning the usual cautious approach exhibited by the Black side, here the strongest piece is brought into the battle in the very first opportunity with the hope to singlehandedly annoy White's army and his coordination. }
2. exd5
{ It is a fight for the honor of center, we capture the pawn and ask Black to choose between two branches:   One - Bring the queen out early and get embarrassed by White's army.   Two - Continue in the spirit of a gambiteer and get a worse position. }
2... Nf6
{ Black wants to retain the option of capturing with the queen while introducing a new concept of recapturing the d5-pawn with the knight which will enable better control of the central squares... though it does allow White to gain an extra tempo by attacking the knight with c4. }
3. d4
{ What can be more natural than taking control of the center with the d-pawn? For some unexplainable reasons both Wesley and Sethu have refrained from this. They have instead recommended 3.Nf3. }
3... Nxd5
{ The knight is just too strong in the center of the board and we won't tolerate it! }
4. c4
{ I like this direct approach asking Black to decide where to put his knight. I feel restricts Black's choices than 4.Nf3. }
4... Nb6
{ The knight wants to have some control over the queenside and keep an eye on the c4-pawn. }
5. Nf3
{ It is important to pay attention to the development of the correct knight. If we are careless and go for 5.Nc3 then Black can strike in the center with the powerful pawn sacrifice with 5...e5 getting good play. }
5... g6
{ Black wants to exert long term pressure along the a1-h8 diagonal for that the fianchetto is the ideal way to do it. Other forms of development schemes are less reliable. }
6. Nc3
{ Q: Do you always prefer knights over bishops? A: Only in the opening stage :@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Bg7
{ The bishop feels happy with his job from g7 and he hopes one day he will control the entire diagonal starting from h8 to a1. For us, it is a good idea to exchange this super sniper bishop as it would weaken his kingside protection and enable better control over the dark-squares. }
7. Be3
{ I make my deviation from Wesley and Sethu's recommendation of 7.h3 which is also quite strong. I feel we can try to make use of our queenside development first as we have already heavily committed towards it due to c4/ Nc3. }
7... O-O
{ It is advisable to castle first before making any attack against White's mighty center. If Black tries to do it prematurely, he will be blown apart by our mobile army.   7...Bg4  can be easily met with  8.h3  with a big advantage as Black is forced to give the bishop pair. }
8. Qd2
{ This is one of the hidden points of early 8.Be3. We move away from any potential pin along the d1-h5 diagonal with Bg4 and prepare to reinforce our pretty center with Rd1 overprotecting d4-pawn. }
8... Nc6
{ Other moves don't have any independent values. Black tries to put some pressure on our center, though we can hardly be bothered by it.   8...Bg4  9.Ng5!  Not allowing Black to get rid of his jobless light-squared bishop.  9...Nc6  10.h3  Bc8  11.Nf3  we reach a transposition to 8... Nc6 lines. }
9. h3
{ A nice prophylactic move preventing Bg4 ideas by making the c8-bishop desperate to find a useful role in this game. The main theme of our system is to prevent Black from gaining any counterplay against our center, if we kill off any hopes of activity from Black then our space advantage will determine our superior advantage. }
9... e5
{ Black doesn't have any other good idea to have sort of play against the center and hence he wishes to change the pawn structure. }
10. d5
{ Now the d-pawn is a force to be reckoned with and has the potential to become a beautiful queen if I might say so :@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Ne7
{ The only way. If Black goes  10...Nd4  11.Nxd4  exd4  12.Bxd4  he doesn't get sufficient compensation for the pawn. }
11. g4
{ Ladies and gentlemen, always remember...The move h3 has many hidden talents, it isn't just a move to prevent Bg4. Here it actively takes part in neutralizing Black's play on the kingside! Black can achieve f5 only at the cost of angering our forces :@@EndBracket@@. }
11... f5
{ Here Black's position is mainly held together by just one piece and If we figure out who that is, then it is easy to strike him! }
12. Bh6
{ Exchanging the dark-squared bishop which will make Black's position super hopeless as our attack will become 100 times stronger. }
12... fxg4 13. Bxg7
{ A cool intermezzo before making our next decision about the g4-pawn. } 13...
Kxg7 { Black can't afford to let the dark-squared bishop live! } 14. hxg4
{ A brilliant piece sacrifice that Black can't hold to accept as it allows Qh6+ followed by Qxh7+ with an irresistible attack. We are cruising here with a big advantage. The c3-knight can easily join the chaos with Ne4 making Black's position desperate. The extra piece doesn't allow any respite for Black as the pawns c4, g4, and d5 restrict Black's entire army making it impossible for him to use his material advantage. }
