{ In these early 4.c4 lines, it is necessary to play Nf3 first to stop any evil e5 breaks from Black. Once again the careless 5.Nc3 would allow Black to lash out in the center with the epic 5...e5! }
5... g6
{ Black gives up the fight for the center and just wants to place his pieces in good squares with the hope that he will gain a solid position to compensate for our superiority in the center. }
6. Nc3
{ Due to the long-range of the bishops, it is ideal to finish the development of the knights first as the best place for their deployment is f3 and c3...while the bishop can be placed on different locations depending on the current demands of the position. }
6... Bg7 7. Be2
{ Although the d3-square is the most active location for the light-squared bishop, in this specific situation, it will be pointing at the brick wall which is the pawn on g6...while If we develop it to e2, it might find a glorious future on f3 someday controlling the h1-a8 diagonal. }
7... O-O 8. O-O
{ Black has many ways to continue here, but none of them challenge our mighty center control. We can continue with Re1 followed by h3, Bf4, Qd2, Rad1 with full steam ahead to the middlegame battle! }
