6. Be2
{ Wesley recommends 6.Be3, while Sethu gives 6.Ne5 though both options are very good... I like my recommendation as we are hiding our evil intentions and have some nasty plans if Black is not careful. }
6... Bg4
{ Black is a bit careless and allows us to execute one of the key ideas behind the silent 6th move. }
7. h3 { Part with the bishop or go back! } 7... Bh5
{ Black doesn't want to allow us any easy advantage! } 8. g4
{ An aggressive thrust, this usually doesn't go well with the bishop on e2 as the general idea is to play g4 followed by Bg2 but here we have a concrete idea in mind and want to punish Black for his poor development using the e5-square as the hook. }
8... Bg6 9. h4
{ Harry the h-pawn makes his move! Black is in a pickle as both h5 and h6 have shortcomings. }
9... h5
{ The only way as  9...h6  would allow  10.Ne5  followed by g5 with a devastating initiative that guarantees the advantage. }
10. Ne5
{ Black's position looks pitiful as there is no easy to stop the destruction of the pawn structure made possible due to the bishop on g6. }
10... Nxg4 { Black at least wants to get rid of our bishop. } 11. Bxg4
{ The natural recapture, it would make no sense to take on g4 with the knight on e5 which is doing an amazing job there. }
11... hxg4 12. Qxg4 { Threatening to take on g6 and the deadly Qc8+. } 12...
Nd7 { Of course Black can't allow Qc8+, hence this is the lesser of evil. } 13.
Nxg6
{ Ruining Black's pawn structure permanently by giving him the doubled pawns on g-file and also making the e7-pawn a lonely island. }
13... Qxg6
{ Better to reduce the tension by exchanging the queens, otherwise Black won't survive the middlegame. }
14. Qxg6 fxg6 15. Bg5
{ Black will suffer for the remainder of the game due to his horrible pawns on the kingside, while we can continue with O-O-O & Rhe1 targetting the e7-pawn with an endgame advantage. }
