{ The strongest direction! Attacking the queen and asking her majesty to choose a wise direction :@@EndBracket@@. This is officially the beginning of the Scandinavian! The Black queen could go to a5 @@StartBracket@@The first@@EndBracket@@, d6 @@StartBracket@@The trendy@@EndBracket@@ and finally the d8 @@StartBracket@@The lame@@EndBracket@@.   Other queen retreats are too lame like  3...Qe5+  which can be met with  4.Be2  followed by d4 with a big advantage due to the huge lead in development and the queen will continue giving us more momentum by attacking her.   The other tries like @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  or  3.d4  allow Black very good chances to equalize. }
3... Qd6
{ This retreat saw a huge rise in popularity as it was employed by Magnus Carlsen, Caruana, and Ivanchuk with a lot of success in classical time control. Hence people had to take it seriously and soon destructive countermeasures were created. }
4. Nf3
{ A very sneaky move order! The g1-knight's destined place is on f3, but we can delay d4 for one more move and wait to see how Black will react :@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Nf6 5. d4
{ Switching back and returning to the mainlines. Taking control of the center and e5-square, asking Black to show compensation for giving up the center without a fight. }
5... Bg4
{ This line has to be treated with slight precision as we need to play energetically for some moves to win the fight for initiative and advantage. }
6. h3 { GO BACK SIMON! } 6... Bh5
{ Simon is not happy, but he has to go back...the alternative was to take on f3 with a horrible position due to the lack of bishop pair. }
7. g4
{ Zero hesitation! I think in the Scandinavian, we should be ready to advance our pawns on the kingside to punish Black for his opening deeds! }
7... Bg6 8. Bg2
{ The difference in class between the two light-squared bishops can be seen. Our bishop on g2 has a great future, while his counterpart is staring into the sky with no plan. }
8... Nc6
{ Although the Black knight does exert some pressure on the d4-pawn, Black is not in time to do so as we are faster in creating our initiative. }
9. O-O
{ Here Black's two best replies  9...e6  &  9...O-O-O  are both met with the strong  10.Nb5  followed by c4 with a crushing advantage as Black will struggle to neutralize White's attack. }
*

