{ The strongest direction! Attacking the queen and asking her majesty to choose a wise direction :@@EndBracket@@. This is officially the beginning of the Scandinavian! The Black queen could go to a5 @@StartBracket@@The first@@EndBracket@@, d6 @@StartBracket@@The trendy@@EndBracket@@ and finally the d8 @@StartBracket@@The lame@@EndBracket@@.   Other queen retreats are too lame like  3...Qe5+  which can be met with  4.Be2  followed by d4 with a big advantage due to the huge lead in development and the queen will continue giving us more momentum by attacking her.   The other tries like @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  or  3.d4  allow Black very good chances to equalize. }
3... Qd6
{ This retreat saw a huge rise in popularity as it was employed by Magnus Carlsen, Caruana, and Ivanchuk with a lot of success in classical time control. Hence people had to take it seriously and soon destructive countermeasures were created. }
4. Nf3
{ A very sneaky move order! The g1-knight's destined place is on f3, but we can delay d4 for one more move and wait to see how Black will react :@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Nf6 5. d4
{ Switching back and returning to the mainlines. Taking control of the center and e5-square, asking Black to show compensation for giving up the center without a fight. }
5... g6
{ This fianchetto system used to be a major annoyance for the White players for some time as it wasn't easy to come up with a good idea against Black's plan of queenside play with a6-b5-Bb7 followed by c5 which Fabiano managed to execute and went on to win a nice game against Dominguez making everyone look at this line with different eyes. }
6. Nb5
{ The most direct way attempting to refute Black's concept. Attacking the queen and Black has only two ways to continue. }
6... Qb6
{ Black wants to keep his queen a bit active to avoid the embarrassment of losing two many tempi roaming around without any purpose. }
7. a4
{ Preparing the deadly a5 which would seriously dictate the terms and play on the queenside. }
7... c6
{ Preparing to run to d8 where the queen will finally be safe from our army.   7...a5  8.Bc4  with a big advantage as the queenside pawn structure is fixed favorably. Black can never achieve b5 move and we can always retreat to c3 after c6. We can continue with O-O followed by Re1 with strong pressure along the e-file and the a2-g8 long diagonal.   7...a6  8.Na3  The knight will be rerouted to e5 via c4 leading to a stable advantage due to the overwhelming control of the e5-square. }
8. a5
{ Never back down! The a-pawn is a thorn in Black's position and gets in the way of his coordination. }
8... Qd8 9. Nc3
{ The knight has successfully fulfilled its duty of achieving a lot of space on the queenside thanks to the advance of the a-pawn. Now the a1-rook can just remain there to support the a5-pawn, while we can focus on activating the remaining forces. }
9... Bg7 { Black's only hope is now to create play against the d4-pawn. } 10.
h3
{ This strong prophylactic move is aimed against the previous comment. We just take away Black's only hope and stop Bg4 ideas which in turn makes any threats on the d4-pawn purely imaginary! }
10... O-O 11. Bc4
{ The most active square for the bishop to put pressure on one of Black's vulnerable spots - the f7-pawn. We follow it up with O-O and Re1 with a binding advantage since I don't see any good plan for Black. }
