{ This retreat saw a huge rise in popularity as it was employed by Magnus Carlsen, Caruana, and Ivanchuk with a lot of success in classical time control. Hence people had to take it seriously and soon destructive countermeasures were created. }
4. Nf3
{ A very sneaky move order! The g1-knight's destined place is on f3, but we can delay d4 for one more move and wait to see how Black will react :@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Nf6 5. d4
{ Switching back and returning to the mainlines. Taking control of the center and e5-square, asking Black to show compensation for giving up the center without a fight. }
5... g6
{ This fianchetto system used to be a major annoyance for the White players for some time as it wasn't easy to come up with a good idea against Black's plan of queenside play with a6-b5-Bb7 followed by c5 which Fabiano managed to execute and went on to win a nice game against Dominguez making everyone look at this line with different eyes. }
6. Nb5
{ The most direct way attempting to refute Black's concept. Attacking the queen and Black has only two ways to continue. }
6... Qd8 7. Bf4
{ I think this recommendation of Wesley is the strongest as it provokes Black into weakening his position. Activity can be gained back, but the weaknesses created will remain constant :@@EndBracket@@. Sethu recommends 7.c4 which also offers a stable advantage thanks to the good control over the center. }
7... Nd5
{ Black actively defends the c7-pawn by counterattacking the bishop on f4. } 8.
Be5
{ An important provocation forcing the weakness with f6 which makes Black's kingside permanently weak on the light squares. }
8... f6 { Moving the rook to g8 would allow 9.c4 winning on the spot. } 9. Bg3
{ Happy with his achievements, the bishop returns to g3 where it continues controlling the h2-b8 diagonal. }
9... c6 { Kicking the knight. } 10. Na3
{ The knight retreats to the corner and will reposition itself to c4. The main idea is to not exchange the knight with 10.Nc3. We have more space, so consciously we must avoid exchanging pieces unless they increase our advantage. }
10... Bh6
{ The bishop is more active here and pretends to control something along the c1-h8 diagonal. Instead, If he goes Bg7 he would have nothing to do there :@@EndBracket@@. }
11. Bd3
{ The bishop is best placed here as the c4-square belongs to the a3 knight and now it can create some play on the recently weakened g6/h7 squares on the kingside. }
11... Qa5+
{ The only move which at least pretends to challenge us.   11...O-O  12.O-O  followed by Re1 with a pleasant advantage due to the weaknesses accumulated due to the provoked f6 move. }
12. Kf1
{ We don't mind losing the right to castling as the only defect of this would be the inactive rook on h1...it can be activated via different means. }
12... O-O
{ Black feels like he has achieved something... he can castle while we can't, but this joy is short-lived and he will have a rude awakening after our next move. }
13. h4
{ This was exactly what I was talking about! The rook joins the game with renewed power! The threat of h5 will force weakening by Black making his kingside situation highly suspect. The ideal way to develop our pieces would be c3 followed by Nc4 and Qe2 with very strong control over the central e-file. Black has no good way to challenge our dominating advantage. }
