{ A very nice direction shown by Wesley which has been seen in only one correspondence game so far! Sethu also recommends this and now I am also joining the club :@@EndBracket@@ since I feel practically this is the best way for White, I couldn't find an alternative path that guarantees our advantage like this line. }
8... Qxd4 { Black has to take up the gauntlet. } 9. Be3
{ Attacking the queen and preparing to castle queenside or play Rd1 to put pressure along the d-file. There are many retreats for the queen, but only one of them gives a fighting chance. }
9... Qd8
{ The safest.   9...Qb4  Attacking the b2-pawn hoping for O-O-O from White.  10.Bd2!  A strong retreat of the bishop threatening g5 or queenside castling and Black can't take on b2 which allows Rb1 followed by Rxb7 completely dominating Black. If Black doesn't take the pawn then our compensation will soon become very hard to control and the bishops will have their say due to Black's poor development. }
10. g5 { Forcing Nd5 which allows O-O-O. } 10... Nd5
{ The only move which doesn't make things worse for Black.   10...Nfd7  11.O-O-O  e6  12.h4  followed by h5-g6 ideas with a crushing advantage for White. The game will be over before Black's queenside pieces enter the game :@@EndBracket@@. }
11. O-O-O { Black's demise will happen along the d-file. } 11... e6
{ Hoping that the knight on d5 will hold his position together. } 12. Nxd5
{ Time to blast open Black's position step by step. } 12... cxd5
{ This is the only way.   12...exd5  13.Re1  and the end will happen via the e-file. }
13. c4
{ I must say that Wesley found the best direction where Black won't have much hope to save his position. Breaching the last line of defense. }
13... Qc7 { Stalling for time! } 14. Kb1 { The threat of cxd5 is renewed. }
14... dxc4 15. Qe4
{ With Bxc4 next and Black's king will soon come under heavy fire irrespective of whether he stays on e8 when he will be assaulted by our piece army or if he goes for short castling when the attack will shift to a pawn storm with h4-h5 and g6. }
