{ This move is the mainline which has managed to stand the test of time... until my course is out :@@EndBracket@@. I can confidently say that I found a very convincing way to advantage.   5...c6  has no independent value as we can force a transposition to 5...Bf5 lines.  6.Bc4!  Bf5  7.Ne5  with a transposition. }
6. Ne5
{ If White can occupy such a commanding outpost with his knight in the center of the board on the 6th move something has gone wrong for Black! We are preparing g4 ideas and will always have Nc4 ideas in hand.Wesley recommends 6. Bc4 followed by Bd2 which can hardly scare Black players from playing the Scandinavian. If someone wants to play this line, he should be regretting his choice till the end of the game and for that, it is necessary to play with a strong mind and destructive preparation! To support my point further this is also the top choice of both Stock and Lc0.   6...e6  7.g4  Preparing the incoming pawn storm  7...Bg6  8.h4  and the threat of h5 gives White the decisive advantage. }
6... c6
{ Black takes precaution against Nc4 and controls a lot of key squares on the queenside and her majesty feels much safer after this prophylactic move. }
7. Bc4
{ Provoking e6 before proceeding with g4. This is also the most ideal location for our bishop where it puts pressure on e6 and f7. }
7... e6 { Other moves are significantly worse for Black. } 8. g4
{ Let the pawn storm begin! This is also Sethu's recommendation, but I feel I was able to make some changes and refine it further for my LTR. }
8... Bg6
{ The bishop hopes to survive our brutal onslaught thanks to the pin along the a5-e1 diagonal.   8...Be4  can be cooly met with a developing move.  9.O-O!  Threatening to win a piece with g5.  9...Bd5  10.Bd3!  The bishop on d5 is looking like a silly big pawn with an undisputed advantage for us thanks to that. }
9. h4 { Winter is coming! } 9... Nbd7
{ Black hopes to reduce the pressure on the kingside and center by exchanging the powerful knight on e5.   9...Bb4  can be met with the most natural move.  10.Bd2  supporting c3 and Black will be forced to lose his castling... if he doesn't want to end up in a precarious situation. }
10. Nxd7
{ The simplest and the only way, we can't afford to waste time defending our knight. Time is of the essence here and we have to strike when the iron is hot! }
10... Nxd7 { Black's only hope is the pin along the a5-e1 diagonal. } 11. h5
{ No hesitation! We are gonna finish what we started by sticking to our principles till the end! }
11... Be4 12. O-O
{ This is the bomb! Although Rh3 has been the undisputed mainline thanks to the phenomenal victory by Vishy Anand against Joel Lautier which has made its way into many books, I feel this is fast and surprisingly our king will be quite safe on g1. The over-stretched pawns on g4 and h5 make a very good cover for the safety of our king. }
12... Bd5 { The bishop has managed to survive in one piece :@@EndBracket@@ ! }
13. Nxd5
{ Happy to get the bishop pair and our dominance on the light squares will be the deciding factor. }
13... cxd5
{ Obviously Black can't afford to take back with the e-pawn due to Re1+. } 14.
Bd3
{ The bishop has no future left in the a2-g8 diagonal and it quickly shifts its trajectory to the next best thing which is the b1-h7 diagonal. }
14... g6 { Black wants to open the g-file to target our king. } 15. Bd2
{ This is a nice move forcing Black to choose and then proceeding to plan our strategy according to that. I feel this is stronger than Sethu's recommendation 15.Be3 and also we stick to one principled plan in all lines - Bd2 followed by c3. }
15... Qb6
{ This does look like the most active square for the queen to keep pressure on d4 and b2... but unfortunately for Black, both the pawns are poisoned! Taking on b2 would open the b-file and taking on d4 would open the a1-h8 diagonal. }
16. h6
{ This seems the most convincing human reaction... though I feel even AlphaZero would be proud of this move, after all, he is a big fan of putting the pawn on h6. We permanently close the h-file and create a potential future queen as our pawn is just two steps away from fulfilling his destiny. It doesn't matter whether Black does kingside or queenside, he won't have an easy life and has to play a defensive trying to defuse our initiative. }
16... Bd6
{ The bishop occupies the most active diagonal where he hopes to create the future battery after Bc7-Qd6 trying to use the weaknesses on our kingside. }
17. c3 { Protecting the d4-pawn and stabilizing our center. } 17... O-O
{ Black feels that the kingside is the lesser of evil, since if he goes O-O-O he will be hunted by a pawn storm with a4-a5 followed by c4 crashing through on the light squares. }
18. Qf3
{ The most active place for our queen where it stops the central break with e5 due to the pressure on the d5-pawn }
18... Rae8 { Black wants to prepare e5 at some point. } 19. Rfe1
{ We are in full control and can steadily improve our position with Re2 and Rae1. The pawn hook on h6 will make sure that his king on g8 will never be safe.   The tempting  19...Qxb2  can be met by  20.Red1  threatening Rab1.  20...Qb6  21.Rab1  Qc7  22.c4!  Blasting open the light squares with advantage and the sooner the position gets open, the faster the bishop pair will reign their dominance. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Scandinavian Scarecrow"]
[Black "2...Qxd5 3.Nc3 Qa5 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... d5
{ The Center Counter Defense is one of the coldest recorded openings as it was played between Francesc de Castellví and Narcís Vinyoles in Valencia in 1475. Analysis by Scandinavian masters in the late 19th century didn't change its status and it remained an unplayable opening for Black. Although the Scandinavian Defense has never enjoyed widespread popularity among top-flight players, I mean why should it? It gives up the center and helps White to develop his army with tempo. - Sethu's LTR  @@StartBracket@@source@@EndBracket@@.Just when all hope had been lost for this opening... one crazy guy decided to play it against the reigning World Champion Magnus Carlsen in Tata Steel 2017 and even managed to achieve a winning position... What more do you want from this opening? Abandoning the usual cautious approach exhibited by the Black side, here the strongest piece is brought into the battle in the very first opportunity with the hope to singlehandedly annoy White's army and his coordination. }
2. exd5
{ It is a fight for the honor of center, we capture the pawn and ask Black to choose between two branches:   One - Bring the queen out early and get embarrassed by White's army.   Two - Continue in the spirit of a gambiteer and get a worse position. }
2... Qxd5 3. Nc3
{ The strongest direction! Attacking the queen and asking her majesty to choose a wise direction :@@EndBracket@@. This is officially the beginning of the Scandinavian! The Black queen could go to a5 @@StartBracket@@The first@@EndBracket@@, d6 @@StartBracket@@The trendy@@EndBracket@@ and finally the d8 @@StartBracket@@The lame@@EndBracket@@.   Other queen retreats are too lame like  3...Qe5+  which can be met with  4.Be2  followed by d4 with a big advantage due to the huge lead in development and the queen will continue giving us more momentum by attacking her.   The other tries like @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  or  3.d4  allow Black very good chances to equalize. }
3... Qa5
{ The most popular queen retreat. This formed the basis for the creation of the Scandinavian defense. Black has given up the center and also managed to lose some tempi in the process... What for? The queen has gotten out and feels like she can influence many things in the queenside by making use of the pin along the a5-e1 diagonal and not to mention the fact that she can quickly switch to h5 in just one move to generate play in the kingside.Tiviakov is one of the biggest pioneers of the Scandi and has used it for many years against the strongest opposition with a lot of success! That being said, I feel I have found the way to advantage using our superior army and central control which can never be compensated by Black's sole queen. }
4. d4
{ Capturing the center and taking control of the important e5-square which will prove to be an attacking hook by placing a knight there controlling Black's position. I also tried to make the exciting 4. b4 work, but it was not to be and we don't get enough compensation for the pawn. }
4... Nf6
{ Black develops his knight and prepares to develop his c8-bishop to f5 or g4, he can also play Ne4 trying to use the pin along the a5-e1 diagonal.   4...c6  5.Nf3  Nf6  will transpose to 4...Nf6 lines. }
5. Nf3
{ This feels like a better move order than 5.Bc4 as getting the knight to e5 is the top priority! And I will keep repeating this until the readers are completely bored of this saying and it becomes drilled into their bloodstream 'knights before bishops' in the opening stages :@@EndBracket@@! }
5... Bf5
{ This move is the mainline which has managed to stand the test of time... until my course is out :@@EndBracket@@. I can confidently say that I found a very convincing way to advantage.   5...c6  has no independent value as we can force a transposition to 5...Bf5 lines.  6.Bc4!  Bf5  7.Ne5  with a transposition. }
6. Ne5
{ If White can occupy such a commanding outpost with his knight in the center of the board on the 6th move something has gone wrong for Black! We are preparing g4 ideas and will always have Nc4 ideas in hand.Wesley recommends 6. Bc4 followed by Bd2 which can hardly scare Black players from playing the Scandinavian. If someone wants to play this line, he should be regretting his choice till the end of the game and for that, it is necessary to play with a strong mind and destructive preparation! To support my point further this is also the top choice of both Stock and Lc0.   6...e6  7.g4  Preparing the incoming pawn storm  7...Bg6  8.h4  and the threat of h5 gives White the decisive advantage. }
6... c6
{ Black takes precaution against Nc4 and controls a lot of key squares on the queenside and her majesty feels much safer after this prophylactic move. }
7. Bc4
{ Provoking e6 before proceeding with g4. This is also the most ideal location for our bishop where it puts pressure on e6 and f7. }
7... e6 { Other moves are significantly worse for Black. } 8. g4
{ Let the pawn storm begin! This is also Sethu's recommendation, but I feel I was able to make some changes and refine it further for my LTR. }
8... Bg6
{ The bishop hopes to survive our brutal onslaught thanks to the pin along the a5-e1 diagonal.   8...Be4  can be cooly met with a developing move.  9.O-O!  Threatening to win a piece with g5.  9...Bd5  10.Bd3!  The bishop on d5 is looking like a silly big pawn with an undisputed advantage for us thanks to that. }
9. h4 { Winter is coming! } 9... Nbd7
{ Black hopes to reduce the pressure on the kingside and center by exchanging the powerful knight on e5.   9...Bb4  can be met with the most natural move.  10.Bd2  supporting c3 and Black will be forced to lose his castling... if he doesn't want to end up in a precarious situation. }
10. Nxd7
{ The simplest and the only way, we can't afford to waste time defending our knight. Time is of the essence here and we have to strike when the iron is hot! }
10... Nxd7 { Black's only hope is the pin along the a5-e1 diagonal. } 11. h5
{ No hesitation! We are gonna finish what we started by sticking to our principles till the end! }
11... Be4 12. O-O
{ This is the bomb! Although Rh3 has been the undisputed mainline thanks to the phenomenal victory by Vishy Anand against Joel Lautier which has made its way into many books, I feel this is fast and surprisingly our king will be quite safe on g1. The over-stretched pawns on g4 and h5 make a very good cover for the safety of our king. }
12... Bd5 { The bishop has managed to survive in one piece :@@EndBracket@@ ! }
13. Nxd5
{ Happy to get the bishop pair and our dominance on the light squares will be the deciding factor. }
13... cxd5
{ Obviously Black can't afford to take back with the e-pawn due to Re1+. } 14.
Bd3
{ The bishop has no future left in the a2-g8 diagonal and it quickly shifts its trajectory to the next best thing which is the b1-h7 diagonal. }
14... Bd6 { The ideal location for the bishop controlling the b8-h2 diagonal. }
15. Bd2
{ Attacking the queen and forcing her to choose between b6 or d8 @@StartBracket@@c7 is really stupid as the battery of queen/bishop should be the other way :@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@. }
15... Qd8
{ I faced this in a blitz game and I was very proud to find the strongest continuation there. If I can find it in a 3-minute game, then obviously the position is easy to handle. }
16. Kg2
{ Black's hope is based on the h-file. Either he wants to get Qh4 or g6...so with this move I am preparing Rh1 to kill two birds with one stone! }
16... g6 { Black wants to open the g-file. } 17. Rh1
{ and I won a nice game thanks to the dominating position exhibited due to the bishop pair. }
*

