{ This move is the mainline which has managed to stand the test of time... until my course is out :@@EndBracket@@. I can confidently say that I found a very convincing way to advantage.   5...c6  has no independent value as we can force a transposition to 5...Bf5 lines.  6.Bc4!  Bf5  7.Ne5  with a transposition. }
6. Ne5
{ If White can occupy such a commanding outpost with his knight in the center of the board on the 6th move something has gone wrong for Black! We are preparing g4 ideas and will always have Nc4 ideas in hand.Wesley recommends 6. Bc4 followed by Bd2 which can hardly scare Black players from playing the Scandinavian. If someone wants to play this line, he should be regretting his choice till the end of the game and for that, it is necessary to play with a strong mind and destructive preparation! To support my point further this is also the top choice of both Stock and Lc0.   6...e6  7.g4  Preparing the incoming pawn storm  7...Bg6  8.h4  and the threat of h5 gives White the decisive advantage. }
6... c6
{ Black takes precaution against Nc4 and controls a lot of key squares on the queenside and her majesty feels much safer after this prophylactic move. }
7. Bc4
{ Provoking e6 before proceeding with g4. This is also the most ideal location for our bishop where it puts pressure on e6 and f7. }
7... e6 { Other moves are significantly worse for Black. } 8. g4
{ Let the pawn storm begin! This is also Sethu's recommendation, but I feel I was able to make some changes and refine it further for my LTR. }
8... Bg6
{ The bishop hopes to survive our brutal onslaught thanks to the pin along the a5-e1 diagonal.   8...Be4  can be cooly met with a developing move.  9.O-O!  Threatening to win a piece with g5.  9...Bd5  10.Bd3!  The bishop on d5 is looking like a silly big pawn with an undisputed advantage for us thanks to that. }
9. h4 { Winter is coming! } 9... Nbd7
{ Black hopes to reduce the pressure on the kingside and center by exchanging the powerful knight on e5.   9...Bb4  can be met with the most natural move.  10.Bd2  supporting c3 and Black will be forced to lose his castling... if he doesn't want to end up in a precarious situation. }
10. Nxd7
{ The simplest and the only way, we can't afford to waste time defending our knight. Time is of the essence here and we have to strike when the iron is hot! }
10... Nxd7 { Black's only hope is the pin along the a5-e1 diagonal. } 11. h5
{ No hesitation! We are gonna finish what we started by sticking to our principles till the end! }
11... Be4 12. O-O
{ This is the bomb! Although Rh3 has been the undisputed mainline thanks to the phenomenal victory by Vishy Anand against Joel Lautier which has made its way into many books, I feel this is fast and surprisingly our king will be quite safe on g1. The over-stretched pawns on g4 and h5 make a very good cover for the safety of our king. }
12... Bd5 { The bishop has managed to survive in one piece :@@EndBracket@@ ! }
13. Nxd5
{ Happy to get the bishop pair and our dominance on the light squares will be the deciding factor. }
13... cxd5
{ Obviously Black can't afford to take back with the e-pawn due to Re1+. } 14.
Bd3
{ The bishop has no future left in the a2-g8 diagonal and it quickly shifts its trajectory to the next best thing which is the b1-h7 diagonal. }
14... Bd6 { The ideal location for the bishop controlling the b8-h2 diagonal. }
15. Bd2
{ Attacking the queen and forcing her to choose between b6 or d8 @@StartBracket@@c7 is really stupid as the battery of queen/bishop should be the other way :@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@. }
15... Qb6 { Black has created a nice double attack on b2 and c3. } 16. c3
{ Protecting both d4 and b2 in one move! Black can't afford to take on b2 which would unleash our sleeping rook on a1 to the powerful 7th rank after Rb1 & Rxb7. }
16... Bc7
{ A cool retreat preparing Qd6 and Qh2 checkmate!   16...g6  can be met with  17.h6  transposing to 14...g6 lines. }
17. a4
{ I strongly feel this AlphaZero inspired thrust puts an end to the Scandinavian... }
17... O-O
{ Alex @@StartBracket@@Chessforlife@@EndBracket@@ only checks 18.f4 here.   17...a5  stopping our advance makes the b5-square very weak.  18.Qf3  with a big advantage as Black won't have any play on the queenside while our initiative on the kingside will be unstoppable. }
18. h6
{ Creating an epic pawn hook on h6 which will permanently remain a thorn in Black's flesh. }
18... Qd6
{ I desperately tried to make this line work to save the honor of the Scandi... but it was all in vain! }
19. f4 { Closing the b8-h2 diagonal. } 19... gxh6
{ This was the point of provoking f4 :@@EndBracket@@. Now White is forced to embark on a king walk to maintain his advantage! }
20. Qf3 { The most powerful piece joins the kingside fight. } 20... Kh8
{ This is the only testing option, other moves will be easily met by 21.Rae1 followed by Kg2 with attacking advantage due to Black's doubled pawns on h6 which compromises his king's safety making the h-file a huge target. }
21. Rae1
{ Black was preparing f5 ideas and hence it was necessary to pay attention to the e-file and keep an eye on e6. }
21... Rg8
{ Preparing Nf6. If Black goes  21...Nf6  22.Kf2  will also lead to the same. }
22. Kf2
{ The king is ready for his morning stroll and clears the g and h-files for the rooks. }
22... Nf6 { Other moves shouldn't trouble us. } 23. g5
{ Never back down! It is important to fight for the initiative and not make defensive moves like Rg1. }
23... hxg5 24. fxg5
{ Since the king feels safe on f2, it was time to reopen the b8-h2 diagonal. }
24... Qh2+
{ The queen has managed to achieve her life's purpose :@@EndBracket@@. } 25.
Ke3
{ The fun is just starting :@@EndBracket@@! The king stands amidst his army leading them to advantage! }
25... Ne4
{ Black forces the exchange of the bishop for the knight to reduce the control over h7 which was becoming dangerous.   25...Nh5  Black is preparing the deadly Bf4+ winning the queen  26.Rf2!  Freeing the e2-square for the king's return.  26...Qh4  27.Ke2  The king has spectacularly fulfilled his duty and returns to his new palace on the queenside. }
26. Bxe4 dxe4 27. Qf6+
{ An important check supporting the g5-pawn and gaining time to attack the queen on h2. }
27... Rg7 28. Rh1 { Asking the queen to politely leave h2. } 28... Qg3+
{ Hoping our White king won't have the courage to take on e4...   28...Qd6  doesn't change anything.  29.Kxe4!  Although the material is equal, the g5-pawn is stopping both f7 and h7, while our queenside/ center pawns will become the main focus of attention in the upcoming war! }
29. Kxe4
{ What a way to end the line! The king stands strong in the center of the board honoring my 1.e4 LTR to witness the end of the Scandinavian... }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) Owen and His Relatives"]
[Black "Owen's Defense: 1..b6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... b6
{ There was a time when I was so happy with my 1.b3 course direction that I believed it was possible to make the 'Owen Defense' work from the Black side! Unfortunately, I had to face the sad reality when I took an objective look and there were at least 3 ways to gain a clear advantage with White. }
2. d4
{ I think the system with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  b6  2.c4  might be still tenable from Black, but capturing the center with 1.e4 and 2.d4 is just too much to take for Black and he can't hope to equalize anymore... }
2... Bb7 3. Nc3
{ The most natural way to protect the pawn, forcing Black to make a useful developing move before continuing with the attack on our strong center. }
3... Nf6
{ A careless alternative trying to be greedy without making the key move with  3...e6  . }
4. e5
{ Going forward to punish Black for his crimes against the nature of chess! }
4... Ne4 { The brave knight! } 5. Nce2
{ Creating the deadly threat of f3 and Black is forced to accept a horrible position with f6 which is only weakening his structure giving us the undisputed advantage since we can utilize the weaknesses with moves like Ng3 and Bd3 threatening to play Qh5 with a hopeless situation for Black. }
*

