{ There was a time when I was so happy with my 1.b3 course direction that I believed it was possible to make the 'Owen Defense' work from the Black side! Unfortunately, I had to face the sad reality when I took an objective look and there were at least 3 ways to gain a clear advantage with White. }
2. d4
{ I think the system with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  b6  2.c4  might be still tenable from Black, but capturing the center with 1.e4 and 2.d4 is just too much to take for Black and he can't hope to equalize anymore... }
2... Bb7 3. Nc3
{ The most natural way to protect the pawn, forcing Black to make a useful developing move before continuing with the attack on our strong center. }
3... e6 4. Bd3
{ The entire fight revolves around the e4-square, hence it makes a lot of sense to overprotect it! }
4... Bb4 { Slowly bringing the fight to the e4-square. } 5. Nf3
{ The most natural form of development for the knight, we needn't worry about the doubling of our pawn structure after Bxc3...as it only helps us to solidify our center control on d4 and opens up a new life for the c1-bishop along the a3-f8 diagonal if at all he is bored with his life in the c1-h6 diagonal :@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Nf6
{ Finally Black has managed to make his first real threat against us by continuing to put pressure on the central e4-point. }
6. Nd2
{ The stunning retreat which put a big question mark over Black's entire opening concept! We simply protect the e4-pawn again and also break the pin along the a5-e1 diagonal! This was also Shankland's recommendation, but it was reached via 1.d4 b6 2.e4 move order. }
6... c5 { No other move even comes close to being an alternative. } 7. dxc5
{ The simple retort missed by both Shankland and Lawrence! Both of them have a contrasting opinion in the position arising after  7.a3  Bxc3  8.bxc3  ,  I was reminded of the famous quote from the Godzilla movie 'Let them Fight' and decided to recommend a stronger direction which I had found long before Trent's course came out! }
7... bxc5 { Taking back the pawn this way would end very badly for Black! } 8.
e5
{ Suddenly the path to Qg4 is opened up. This was another hidden idea behind the sneaky knight retreat on move 7! }
8... Nd5 { What else? } 9. Nxd5 Bxd5 10. c3
{ Kicking the bishop to a5 and breaking the pin along the a5-e1 diagonal also basically ending its career! }
10... Ba5 11. Qg4
{ Black is in a lot of trouble here as both O-O or Kf8 gives us the decisive advantage! }
11... O-O { This does seem like the natural way... } 12. Ne4
{ White is just too dominant, thanks to the threats of Nf6-Bh6-Ng5. Also Black can't take on e4 due to Qxe4 with a double attack on h7 and a8 winning the rook :@@EndBracket@@. Black is just lost here. }
