[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) Owen and His Relatives"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch Defense: 1...Nc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... Nc6
{ This feels like a lame imitation of the Alekhine Defense :@@EndBracket@@. Black is not even threatening anything :@@EndBracket@@. That being said, 'Let's take an objective look at how to continue with White'. }
2. d4 { Capturing the center and asking Black to choose between two options. }
2... d5 { This would be the preference of Caro-Kann and Scandinavian players. }
3. exd5
{ There are many ways to get the advantage, but I feel we can brute force our way with this direct attempt at refuting the line. }
3... Qxd5 4. Nf3
{ Supporting d4 and preparing to kick the queen with c4 or Nc3 next. The knight on c6 won't feel very comfortable very soon... }
4... e5
{ Black has to strike back in the center before he is squeezed into submission. }
5. Nc3 { Attacking the queen and Black's reply is forced. } 5... Bb4
{ The only way...Black wants to keep the queen on d5 even at the cost of giving up the bishop pair. }
6. Bd2 { Renewing the threat of attacking the queen. } 6... Bxc3 7. Bxc3
{ Happy to have got the bishop pair, Black is doomed to defend against our mighty bishops for the rest of the game. }
7... e4
{ Taking on d4 would just unleash the full power of the dark-squared bishop on c3. }
8. Ne5 { Threatening the deadly Bc4 targetting the f7-pawn. } 8... Nxe5 9. dxe5
{ We have achieved a stable advantage thanks to the energetic play. } 9... Ne7
{ The best move trying to fight for equality. } 10. Qd4
{ Preparing to play Bc4 or Qa4+ with slight advantage due to the bishop pair. }
*

[Event "?"]
