{ Other moves lack the power punch. } 9... e6 { Attacking the key pawn on d5. }
10. O-O
{ Finishing the final developing and preparing a devilish sacrifice... } 10...
Nf6 11. dxc6
{ It was this queen sacrifice that almost arises by force that drove me to recommend this line :@@EndBracket@@! }
11... Rxd1 12. cxb7+
{ The pawn on b7 will remain a constant source of worry for Black and even if by some miracle Black manages to win this pawn, it will end up weakening the king's safety. Hence Black has the difficult choice of letting the pawn stay on b7 with mating threats or trying to get rid of it which ruins his safety net :@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Kb8 13. Raxd1
{ It was very tempting to stop here, but since we do lack the most powerful piece on the board... I decided to continue my analysis for some more moves to make sure that Black has no attacking chances against our king. }
13... Bd6
{ Moves like  13...Bc5  can be met by  14.Rfe1  retaining the advantage. } 14.
g3 Qf5
{ Black is going all-in with his attack as slow approaches are doomed to fail. }
15. Rd3
{ A very strong move defending the bishop on f3 with the tactical point of Bxa7+ winning the queen due to a discovered attack. }
15... h5 { Black is hoping to create some threats along the h-file. } 16. Rfd1
{ It was time to go on the offensive. } 16... h4
{ Otherwise there was no point in playing h5. } 17. b4
{ Black's threats along the h-file are illusionary while our threats along the d-file are real! One of our ideas is to play Bc6 followed by Nb5 leading to a mating attack. }
