1... Nc6
{ This feels like a lame imitation of the Alekhine Defense :@@EndBracket@@. Black is not even threatening anything :@@EndBracket@@. That being said, 'Let's take an objective look at how to continue with White'. }
2. d4 { Capturing the center and asking Black to choose between two options. }
2... e5 { I think 1...e5 players would be inclined to aim for this. } 3. dxe5
{ This seems the clearest way to advantage. } 3... Nxe5 4. Nf3
{ Continuing to develop at full speed! } 4... Qf6
{ Black is trying to hold on to his beautiful knight on e5. } 5. Nc3
{ We don't waste on time on worrying about Nxf3 and continue with speedy development. The threat of Nd5 doesn't leave much options for Black. }
5... Bb4
{ Pinning the c3-knight and stopping Nd5.   5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  was clearly better for White due to Black's poor development and no existing pension plan for the future as seen in @@StartBracket@@Tari-Djurhuus 2017@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Bd2 { Unpinning the knight and renewing the threat of Nd5. } 6... Ne7
{ Our World Champion Magnus Carlsen went for this line in one of the rapid CCT events :@@EndBracket@@. I just don't know what to say...  @@StartBracket@@Wesley-Carlsen Meltwater Rapid 2021@@EndBracket@@. }
7. Nxe5 Qxe5 8. Bd3
{ followed by O-O, a3, and f4 with a big advantage due to our powerful initiative. }
