[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) Owen and His Relatives"]
[Black "George Defense: 1...a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ With this move, we make our intentions very clear... we want to destroy our enemy forces with extreme prejudice! The King's Pawn Opening is certainly the favorite of the Romantic era of Andersson & Morphy, when the only target was to checkmate the black king! It was only later that they found the positional school of thought championed by Steinitz.   In this course, we'll go back in time and try to play chess like them :@@EndBracket@@! Do not be deterred if you are a positional player, I will offer cool options for everyone in this course! After all, it is not possible to become a strong player by mastering just one element! }
1... a6
{ Whenever I think of this move, I always associate this with the stunning game between Karpov-Miles...the latter creating history by winning against such a terrifying opponent by making an offbeat move! }
2. d4 b5
{ Although this is a complete joke even more than the 'Owen defense', I have lost some bullet games not understanding what to do against it. Hence it is time I take it a bit more seriously and find a clear-cut way to advantage. }
3. Nd2
{ I like this prophylactic move aimed against Black's main idea of Bb7. We just protect the e4-pawn in advance :@@EndBracket@@! The knight is better placed on d2 as it is away from the evil eyes of the b5-pawn and can't be dislodged as easily compared to the c3-square. }
3... Bb7
{ Black's ideas involve playing e6 followed by c5 and taking the game to Sicilian-type positions. }
4. a4
{ An useful inclusion provoking b4 which makes sure that our d2-knight will have a good future either from c4 or the b3-square controlling a lot of key squares on the queenside. }
4... Nf6 { Trying to fight actively against our plans. } 5. e5 Nd5
{ Black is baiting us by sacrificing the pawn on b5.   5...Ne4  6.Ngf3  Threatening axb5 again with advantage due to difference in the development. }
6. Ngf3
{ Not falling for it, after this we have a big advantage as Black will have to concede at some point and take on a4 which ruins his pawn structure. }
*

