[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Santhosh Matthew vs. Ornek Ozer, ICCF, 2008"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Let's take a look at how one of the correspondence players managed to crush his opponent using our recommendation. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3
{ After this Black can forget about creating any attacking chances against our king due to our pawn mass on the queenside. }
6... Be7 7. Bf4 { Reviving this old line! } 7... O-O 8. Qd2 Re8 9. O-O-O Nd7
10. h4
{ The most aggressive attempt! We are trying to demolish our opposition with maximum firepower! }
10... Nc5 11. Ng5 h6
{ 11...Bf6  Two of Fressinet's opponents went for this line and got worse :@@EndBracket@@ .  12.Bc4±  White had the advantage already. }
12. Bc4 Bxg5 13. hxg5 Ne4 14. Bxf7+
{ I am glad to have found a game with our main recommendation :@@EndBracket@@ .   14.Qd3!?  I didn't give this line in the LTR since I felt it was too forcing and didn't give many chances to get something... If Black plays accurately.  14...Nxf2  15.Qf3  Nxh1  16.g6  16...Re6  Only move!  17.gxf7+  Kf8  18.Rxh1  Qf6!  Black manages to beat off the attack. }
14... Kxf7 15. Qd5+ Re6 16. gxh6 Qf6
{ A big mistake after which Black gets no chance to save the game. I think this game is a good example of what might happen...If Black is not ready to face this line. Also ironic is the fact that this is an ICCF game where Oznek did have the access to the computer :@@EndBracket@@ .   16...Bd7  is Black's best bet with decent saving chances. }
17. Be3 { White takes control of the game. } 17... gxh6 18. Rxh6 Qe5 19. Qc4 c6
20. Rdh1 { The rooks are gonna deliver the final mating attack. } 20... Qd5 21.
Rh7+ Ke8 22. Rh8+ Kd7 23. R1h7+ Re7 24. Qe2 { The queen joins in on the fun! }
24... Qe6 25. Qh5 Nf6 26. Rxe7+ Qxe7 27. Qh4 Kc7 28. Rh6
{ Winning back the lost material with two extra pawns :@@EndBracket@@. } 28...
Be6 29. Qxf6 Qxf6 30. Rxf6 Kd7
{ The rest is easy...with or without computer assistance :@@EndBracket@@. } 31.
f3 Rh8 32. b3 a6 33. g4 Rh7 34. Kd2 Rf7 35. Rxf7+ Bxf7 36. c4 Bg6 37. c3 c5 38.
a3 b6 39. Bf2 a5 40. Bg3 Bh7 41. Ke3 Bc2 42. b4 Bd1 43. Kf4 axb4 44. axb4 Be2
45. Ke3 Bd1 46. Ke4 { I wish that the readers can pull off such a victory! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Karjakin Sergey vs. Caruana Fabiano, Berlin Candidates, 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3
{ Karjakin is one of the leading experts of this line having delivered defeats to Kramnik, Gelfand, and in this game Caruana. All of them being some of the greatest experts of Petroff. }
5... Nxc3
{ 5...Nf6  This is a sideline which assures us the better game.  6.d4  Be7  7.Bd3  7...O-O  8.h3  An interesting move preventing Bg4 ideas, though O-O is our mainline.  8...Nbd7  9.O-O  Re8  10.Ne2  A nice plan bringing the knight to the kingside where it has a nice spot on f5.  10...Nf8  11.Ng3  Ng6  12.c4  c6  13.Qc2  Qc7  14.Re1  Bd7  15.Bg5!  A powerful move forcing Black to make some weakening.  15...Bf8  16.h4!  White's threats are just too strong and there is little Black can do against it.  16...Be7  17.h5  Nf8  18.Rxe7!  Rxe7  19.h6  19...Ne6  20.Bh4  The pin along the h4-d8 spells the doom for Black.  20...Ree8  21.hxg7  Ng4  22.Bxh7+  Kxg7  23.Nh5+  Kf8  24.Qf5  A cool display of power in  @@StartBracket@@Motylev-Belous ,Vladivostok 2014@@EndBracket@@. }
6. dxc3 Nc6
{ 6...Be7  7.Be3  O-O  8.Qd2  Nd7  9.O-O-O  Ne5  10.h4!  We can see that this is the most aggressive way to create attacking chances on the kingside.  10...c6  11.c4  Preventing Qa5 ideas.  11...Be6  12.Ng5!  Bf5  13.Kb1  Re8  14.f3  14...h6  15.Be2  Cool as a cucumber!  15...d5  16.g4  Bg6  17.f4  White is already killing it! There was nothing Kramnik could do against Karjakin's steady assault.  17...dxc4  18.Qc3  Nd3  19.f5  Bxg5  20.fxg6  This grants Black chances to get back in the game.   20.Bxg5  hxg5  21.Rh2!!  followed by Rdh1 was the right way to conclude the attack.  20...Rxe3  21.gxf7+  Kf8  22.Qxc4  Rxe2   22...Bxh4  Black was holding here.  23.hxg5  Qxg5  24.Qxd3  Qe3  25.Qh7  The queen enters the fray forcing Black king out into the open.  25...Qe4  26.Qg8+  Ke7  27.Qxg7  Qxc2+  28.Ka1  Rf8  29.Rhf1  Rd2  30.Rfe1+  Re2  31.Qc3  Kxf7  32.Qf3+  1-0 @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Karjakin, S. @@StartBracket@@2760@@EndBracket@@-Kramnik, V. @@StartBracket@@2790@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2010 }
7. Be3 Be7 8. Qd2 Be6 9. O-O-O Qd7 10. a3
{ This is a useful move against threats from Black's future ...Qa4 ideas. }
10... h6 11. Nd4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Rg8 13. Be2 c5
{ After this weakening, Black's d-pawn will need constant supervision. } 14.
Be3 d5 15. f4 O-O-O 16. Bf3 Bg4 17. Bxd5
{ A brilliant positional exchange sacrifice to change the character of the game. }
17... Bxd1 18. Rxd1 Qc7 19. c4
{ Black is doomed to suffer after this stabilization of the bishop. } 19...
Rge8 20. Qf2 b6 21. g4 { Gaining space on the kingside. } 21... Bf6 22. Kb1 Rd7
{ 22...Qe7  23.Rd3  b5!!  A surprising resource that would have saved Fabi, but it was hard to find this over the board. }
23. Rd3 { No more second chances for Black. } 23... g5 24. Ka2
{ One of comp's top choices! Karjakin was clearly in his element in this game. }
24... Ree7 25. Qf3 Kd8 26. Bd2 Kc8 27. Qf1 { Preparing Rh3 next. } 27... Rd6
28. fxg5 Bxg5 29. Bxg5 hxg5 30. Qf5+ Rdd7 31. Qxg5
{ The rest is easy! Just promote the h-pawn. } 31... Qe5 32. Qh6 Kd8 33. g5 Qd6
34. Qh8+ Re8 35. Qh4 Qg6 36. Qg4 Re5 37. h4 Ke7 38. Rd2 b5 39. Bxf7 Qf5 40.
Rxd7+ Kxd7 41. Qxf5+ Rxf5 42. g6 Ke7 43. cxb5
{ White has way too many pawns :@@EndBracket@@ . } 43... Rh5 44. c4 Rxh4 45. a4
Rg4 46. a5 Kd6 47. a6 Kc7 48. Kb3
{ One of the most convincing displays by Karjakin. } *

