{ Finally, it is time to take a look at the game of our dear author :@@EndBracket@@. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. d3 d6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bg5
{ This victory is very special for me since Jorden is a big expert in the Italian. }
6... h6 7. Bh4 Qe7
{ 7...a5  8.Nbd2  Ba7  9.a3  I think this is a very interesting alternative to our mainline with 9. O-O.  9...O-O  10.h3!  A very strong idea by Demchenko.  10...g5  A big mistake.   10...Be6  11.Qe2↑  .  11.Nxg5  hxg5  12.Bxg5  White is winning due to the deadly pin along the h4-d8 diagonal.  12...Kg7  13.Qf3  Be6  14.Nf1!  Things will be difficult for Black, once the knight joins the fight to attack the pinned knight on f6.  14...Nb8  15.Ng3  Rh8  @@StartBracket@@Demchenko - Vidit Chess.com Rapid 2022@@EndBracket@@  16.Nf5+!  Bxf5  17.Qxf5  Nbd7  18.h4  followed by Rh3-Rg3 with a winning attack.   7...a6  8.Nbd2  Ba7  9.O-O  g5  10.Bg3  O-O  This is one of the most popular replies to the Bg5 systems.  11.a4  Nh7  12.Kh1!  I think this is a very cool alternative to our course recommendation with 12. d4.  12...Kg7  This move is a waste of time.   12...h5  13.h4!  g4  14.Nh2  followed by f3 next with a cool kingside attack.   12...Qf6  13.d4!  Opening up the game.  13...exd4   13...Re8  14.Rc1!  Preparing for the future opening of the c-file and we can continue putting pressure on e5 with b4-Be2 followed by b5.  14.Nxd4  Nxd4  15.cxd4  Bxd4  16.f4  with a strong attack using the f-file.   12...Kh8  13.d4!  13...h5   13...exd4  14.Nxd4  Nxd4  15.cxd4  Bxd4  16.Qc2  followed by f4 next with a strong compensation for the pawn.  14.h3  g4  15.Nh4  Qf6  16.f4  exd4  17.e5!  with a messy game with chances for both sides, though Black should be careful.  13.d4!  No more restraints! We have done all the necessary preparation for this central pawn sacrifice.  13...h5  14.h3  Since we have already committed d4, it makes sense not to close the kingside with h4.  14...Qf6   14...h4  15.Bh2  g4  16.hxg4  Bxg4  17.Be2!  Breaking the pin followed by b4-b5 next loosening the support of the e5-pawn with a clear advantage.  15.dxe5  dxe5  @@StartBracket@@So - Firouzja Rapid 2021@@EndBracket@@ Here we can improve on White's play.  16.Bd5!  Black can't handle the pressure on the e5-pawn giving us a winning advantage. }
8. Nbd2 g5 9. Bg3 a6 10. O-O Ba7
{ This setup with ...Qe7, ...a6, and ...Ba7 is another way to play against the Bg5 systems. }
11. Kh1 Nh5
{ 11...O-O  12.b4  Kg7  This plan feels slow.  13.a4  I just continued improving on the queenside.  13...Nh7  14.b5  Forcing the knight to leave the control of the center.  14...Na5  15.Ba2  f5  16.exf5  Bxf5  17.d4  was clearly superior for me in @@StartBracket@@Adhiban -Ju Wenjun, Chessable Masters, 2021@@EndBracket@@ }
12. b4
{ 12.a4  Nf4  was seen in @@StartBracket@@Demchenko -Anand Riyadh Blitz 2017@@EndBracket@@ and here our Bg5 hero had the chance to get a big advantage!  13.Bxf4!  Getting rid of the powerful knight. In the game, he went for  13.b4  , and after  13...Ng6!  He was worse and lost the game. @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/bpp1qp2/p1np3p/4p1p1/P1B1PB2/2PP1N2/1P1N1PPP/R2Q1R1K b kq - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...gxf4  14.b4  followed by b5 with a huge advantage. }
12... O-O 13. a4 Be6
{ This doesn't go well with the comp :@@EndBracket@@. He is not happy with this exchange. }
14. b5 Na5 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. d4
{ 16.h3!  followed by Nh2 is another solid way to gain the advantage using the weak light-squares on the kingside. }
16... exd4 17. Nxd4 Nxg3+ 18. hxg3 Rf7 19. Qg4 c5 20. Nxe6 Kh8 21. Nf3
{ Missing Black's strong option!   21.f4!  was necessary.  21...h5  22.Qd1  Qxe6  23.Nf3!!  A brilliant resource leading to a winning attack. }
21... h5
{ 21...Rf6!  Trapping the knight with advantage to Black! For some reason, we both missed this move and were purely focusing on ideas involving h5. }
22. Qxg5 { Refuting Black's concept. } 22... Qxe6 23. Qxh5+ Kg8
{ 23...Rh7?  24.Qxh7+  Kxh7  25.Ng5+  easy win. } 24. Ng5
{ The rest is easy :@@EndBracket@@. } 24... Qf6 25. e5
{ Opening more lines for the two rooks. } 25... dxe5 26. Nxf7 Qxf7 27. Qxe5 Nc4
28. Qg5+ Qg7 29. Qxg7+ Kxg7 30. Rad1 axb5 31. axb5 Kf6 32. Rd7 Bb6 33. Rxb7 Ba5
34. Ra1 Nd6 35. Rh7 Nxb5 36. c4 Nd4 37. Kg1 Nb3 38. Ra3 Rb8 39. Rh5 Rb4 40. Rd5
Bb6 41. Ra6 Ke6 42. Rh5 Kd6 43. Rh6+ Kc7 44. g4 Kb7 45. Rhxb6+
{ I thought this led to a winning endgame! } 45... Rxb6 46. Rxb6+ Kxb6 47. g5
Nd4 48. g6 Nf5 49. f4 Ne7
{ 49...Kc7!  was surprisingly enough to save the game!  50.g4  Ne7  51.f5  Kd6  . }
50. g7 { After this there is no more escape for Black. } 50... Kc6 51. f5 Ng8
52. g4 Kd6 53. g5 Ke7 54. f6+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
