[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 Bg4 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 e6 6. Be2
{ 6.g3!?  This could be an interesting alternative to our mainline.  6...g6  Black tries to copy our concept, but this is just very slow.  7.d4!  Capturing the center.  7...Bg7  8.Be3  Nf6  9.Bg2  O-O  10.O-O  Na6  @@StartBracket@@Nakamura - Shankland, Saint Louis, 2016@@EndBracket@@  11.e5!  Nd7  12.Qe2±  followed by f4 next with a clear bind and advantage. }
6... Nf6 7. Qf4
{ Once again this is a decent alternative to our course recommendation.   7.O-O  d4  This tempting move releases the tension prematurely after which we can prepare the f4 push on the kingside.  8.Nb1  Nbd7  9.d3  Bd6  10.g3!  e5  11.Qg2  The fianchetto of the queen! How often do we get to see this happening?  11...h6  12.Nd2  O-O  13.f4  Bc7  14.f5  Bd6  15.Nf3±  followed by g4 with a crushing kingside attack. @@StartBracket@@Konstantinov -Rodrigues, LSS email, 2017.@@EndBracket@@ }
7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. d4 dxe4 10. Rd1
{ This was why Qf4 was included! White protects the d4-pawn and proceeds to take back on e4. }
10... Bd6 11. Qh4 Nbd7 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4
{ If we can pull this off, we are assured of a solid advantage, and this game is a good example for plans in the middle game. }
13... Re8 14. Qf3 h6 15. c3 Nf6 16. Bc4 Qe7 17. Re1 Rad8 18. a4
{ Always a useful inclusion, giving Black difficult choices - Allow a5 or fix the pawn structure with a5 himself. }
18... a6 19. Be3 Nd5 20. Bd2 Qc7 21. Re2
{ 21.Re4  This doesn't work here.  21...c5  22.Rg4  f5  Black beats off the attack. }
21... Re7 22. Re4 { Now this is very strong! } 22... Nf6
{ 22...c5  Let's compare the line here.  23.Rg4!  f5  24.Rg6±  If the rook was not on e7, Black can simply play ...Qf7 trapping our rook...but now it becomes a force to be reckoned with! }
23. Rh4 { Threatening Bxh6. } 23... Nd5 24. Bb3 Ree8 25. Rg4 Kf8 26. Re1
{ Bringing in the final cavalry! } 26... b5 27. g3 Qe7 28. axb5 axb5 29. Bxd5
cxd5 30. h4 b4 31. h5 bxc3 32. bxc3 Bb8 33. Qd3
{ Threatening the deadly Qh7 and forcing Black to weaken his pawn structure. }
33... f5 34. Rg6 Qd7 35. Qf3 Qf7 36. Bf4 Rc8 37. Bxb8 Rxb8 38. Qf4 Rb6 39. Re3
Ra8 40. Kg2
{ We will prepare the g4 break and Black's defensive setup will collapse after that. A nice display of power by the White pieces and in correspondence chess! }
