{ This game is the reason why I changed my repertoire choices from recommending the mainstream d4-lines to making interesting lines like this work! }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ There are not many model games in this line due to his freshness! My coach TS Ravi couldn't stop laughing when I told him that this is going to be my main recommendation against 2...Nc6 }
3... e6 4. O-O d5
{ 4...Nf6  5.d3!?  A brainchild of Fedoseev, who was one of the earliest exponents of the 3.Bc4 line.  5...Be7   5...d5  6.Bb5  Bd7  7.Nc3  with an interesting middlegame fight.  6.Bb3  O-O  7.c3  b5  @@StartBracket@@Fedoseev - Antipov, Moscow, 2017@@EndBracket@@  8.Re1  followed by d4 with chances for both sides. }
5. Bb5 { What a move! Giving up the e4-pawn for the initiative. } 5... dxe4 6.
Ne5 Qc7 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Bc4
{ We have completely ruined Black's pawn structure for good. } 8... Bd6 9. Kh1
{ This is a very decent alternative and If you are sure that your opponent won't be aware of this game, then definitely go for this! I have also given this as an alternative in our course.   9.Nc3  This deadly novelty is the main recommendation of our course. }
9... Nf6 10. Nc3 e5 11. f3 exf3 12. Qxf3 O-O 13. d3 Be6
{ A big collapse!   13...Kh8  Black had to find this important move after which he has good chances to equalize.  14.Bd2  followed by Rae1 with strong compensation for the pawn. }
14. Bxe6 fxe6
{ Black's pawns deserve the statutory honor of 'Worst pawn structure' in the history of all chess games. }
15. Bg5
{ After this, Black's pawn structure is just so bad that I am running out of words to make fun of it. }
15... Qd7 16. Bxf6
{ To be honest, I am not happy with this exchange, I think White should continue making fun of the pawns :@@EndBracket@@.   16.Qe2⩲  was better. }
16... gxf6 17. Ne4 f5 18. Nxd6 Qxd6 19. Rae1 f4 20. Re4 Rab8 21. b3 Rb4 22.
Rfe1 Rf5 23. Qe2 Rxe4 24. Qg4+ Kh8 25. Rxe4 f3
{ I think Prag was quite impatient in this game for some reason. } 26. gxf3 Qf8
27. Qg3 h6 28. Kg2 Qf6 29. Rg4 Kh7 30. Qh4 Qxh4 31. Rxh4 Rf4 32. Rg4
{ Of course, Jorden is not going to go for the pawn endgame. } 32... h5 33. Rg5
Rf5 34. Rg3 Rf4 35. Kf2 Rf7 36. Rg5 Rf5 37. Rg1 c4 38. dxc4 e4 39. Rg3 h4 40.
Rh3 Kg6 41. Ke3 exf3 42. Rxf3 Ra5 43. a4 Re5+ 44. Kd3 Rg5 45. b4 Rg1 46. b5 c5
47. a5 Rd1+ 48. Ke4 Rd4+ 49. Ke5 Rxc4 50. b6 axb6 51. axb6 Rxc2 52. Rb3 c4 53.
Rb1 c3 54. b7 Re2+ 55. Kd4 c2 56. Rg1+
{ An epic game with lots of twists and turns! I hope this is just the beginning of the revolution with 3. Bc4. }
