6... a6 7. Ba4 e6 8. c4 Be7
{ Taking on e4 is very dangerous.   8...Nxe4  9.Re1  Nec5  10.Nc3  Be7  11.Bxd7+  Nxd7  Otherwise the c5-knight will be trapped with b4.  12.Rxe6!  An epic rook sacrifice which can't be accepted by Black.  12...O-O  @@StartBracket@@Ter Sahakyan - Korobov Blitz, 2021.@@EndBracket@@ Here White had to crank it up a notch!  13.Nd5!!  with a big advantage! }
9. Nc3 O-O 10. Qe2 Qc7 11. f4
{ 11.Kh1!?  is a safe alternative with good chances for an advantage, as in @@StartBracket@@Bacrot -Shankland FIDE GP 2022.@@EndBracket@@ }
11... Nb6 12. Bb3 e5 13. Nf5 Bxf5 14. exf5 Rfe8 15. g4 exf4 16. Bxf4 Bf8
{ 16...h6!?  Black can equalize with this cold-blooded defense. } 17. Qg2
{ White has a very powerful attack! } 17... Nxc4 18. g5 Nh5 19. Nd5 Qc5+ 20.
Kh1 b5 21. g6 { Crashing through on the kingside! } 21... Rab8 22. Rad1 Nxf4
23. Rxf4 Re5 24. Rh4 Rxf5 25. Bc2
{ So far it was all fine and this was the final straw after which Black managed to survive!   25.Rxh7  fxg6  26.Qxg6  Rxd5  27.Rf1!  followed by Rf7 or Rf8 next with a mating attack. I must say that this is not easy to see! }
25... Qf2 26. gxf7+ Kxf7 27. Bxf5
{ 27.Qe4!  was still enough to gain a huge advantage. } 27... Qxh4 28. Rf1 Kg8
29. Rf4 Qe1+ 30. Rf1 Qe5 31. Qh3 Qxd5+ 32. Rf3 Qd1+ 33. Rf1 Qd5+ 34. Rf3 Qd1+
{ A big miss for the World Champion and generally he never misses! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Bacrot Etienne vs. Giri Anish, Germany, 2013"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ I managed to choose the game where my lord Mr.Anish Giri had lost a game against the Moscow :@@EndBracket@@. }
1... c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+
{ If you think the Moscow is boring, wait till you see Black's response :@@EndBracket@@. }
3... Bd7 { This is boring the bored :@@EndBracket@@. } 4. c4
{ Our recommendation! } 4... Nf6
{ 4...e5  5.Bxd7+  Nxd7  6.Nc3  g6  7.Rb1!  followed by b4 breaking the queenside with advantage in  @@StartBracket@@Naiditsch -Armanda, 2014.@@EndBracket@@ }
5. Nc3 g6 6. O-O
{ 6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  Bg7  8.Be3  O-O  9.Bxd7  Qxd7  10.h3  An alternative setup.  10...Rc8  11.b3  11...a6  12.a4  Killing Black's hope of counterplay with b5.  12...Nc6  13.O-O  All of Black's tricks have been neutralized with a stable advantage for White @@StartBracket@@Naiditsch - Mista, Linares, 2018@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Bg7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 O-O 9. Bxd7 Qxd7
{ 9...Nfxd7  This is just bad as Black is not fighting against the central pressure.  10.Be3  Nc6  11.b3  a6  12.Qd2  Qa5  13.Rac1  Rfc8  14.Rfd1  Rab8  15.h3  Nxd4  16.Bxd4  Bxd4  17.Qxd4  Qc5  18.Qd2  Nf6  19.Nd5!  A cool move changing the pawn structure.  19...Nxd5  20.exd5  Re8  21.b4  Qc7  22.c5±  White was dominating in @@StartBracket@@Efimenko -Demchenko, Konya, 2018@@EndBracket@@. }
10. b3 { The Cowboy setup! } 10... Nc6 11. Bb2 a6 12. Nxc6 Qxc6
{ Not to be recommended!   12...bxc6  is safer with good chances to equalize in the long run. }
13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. exd5
{ I noticed from the last two games that this is our most ambitious setup taking on d5 with the e-pawn to create a queenside majority. }
14... Qc5 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Re1 { The e7-pawn is a nice target for our rooks. }
16... Rfe8 17. Qd2 b5 18. Rac1 Qa7
{ 18...bxc4  19.Rxc4±  followed by Rh4 with a winning attack as h5 can be met by Rxh5 with Qg5+ next. }
19. b4 { Creating an outside passed pawn. } 19... bxc4 20. Rxc4 h5 21. Qc3+ Kg8
22. Rc7 Qb6 23. a4 Rab8 24. Re4
{ We are controlling the entire board and can stop Black from achieving any sort of play. }
24... f6 25. g4 Rb7 26. Qxf6
{ What a way to finish the game and to end the model games on a high note! I hope you had a lot of fun and learnt many instructive ideas by studying the model games! }
